<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 2356EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Iran-Iraq-Interviews     07-25 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Iraq-Interviews,0402</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Secretary General Hopes to Set Date in 10 Days</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-UN-Iran-Iraq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
said Monday he hoped a date for a cease-fire between Iran and Iraq
could be set within 10 days, but said this would be only a first
step toward resolving the 8-year-old war.
   In a televised interview, Perez de Cuellar said he wanted a
cease-fire declared ``as soon as possible.'' He is scheduled to
meet Wednesday with the foreign ministers of Iran and Iraq in
separate talks on setting up a U.N.-supervised truce.
   ``The ceasefire is not an end in itself. It's the first very
important step. We want a total solution of the problem,'' Perez de
Cuellar said in the interview on PBS's ``The MacNeil-Lehrer News
Hour.''
   Mohammad Ja Afar Mahallati, the Iranian ambassador to the United
Nations, said on the same program that Iraq was continuing to use
chemical warfare against his country, even though Iran has said it
is ready for an immediate suspension of the conflict.
   Ismat Kittani, Iraq's U.N. ambassador, did not deny that his
country had used chemical weapons but added that ``people should
have learned by now not to take allegations by Iran at their face
value.''
   ``We have said, and I can't go beyond that, that we will use
every means available at our disposal to repel this aggression,
this persistent aggression by the Iranians against our country,''
Kittani said.
   ``Nobody should blame us after they have seen how these people
behave,'' he said. ``We want to see genuine signs that Iran is
really coming back to the ranks of civilized countries, and abiding
by the rules.''
   Vernon Walters, U.S. ambassador to the United Nations, also
appeared on the program and said he sees Iran and Iraq making a
serious effort to end the war.
   ``I think they both made a decision to go for peace. Eight years
is a long time, you get weary. It's unbelievable, eight years, how
they could stand it,'' he said.
   Walters said the war's casualties have taken their toll on both
nations.
   ``It's the flower of their youth. It's their coming generation
that they're going to be losing and I think that's why they have
both come to the conclusion that this is the time to stop that kind
of activity,'' he added.
</TEXT>
