<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0695 07-25 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0695,0437</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS Pagels; An AMs separate moved as a0598 on McClory as
a0562 on Phillips and a0725 on Silver.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Robert McClory</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert N. McClory, former Representative and
Illinois Republican thrust into the national spotlight for his role
in impeachment proceedings against President Richard Nixon, died
Sunday. He was 80.
   McClory was elected to the Illinois House of Representatives in
1950. He served in the state Senate from 1952 to 1962. He was the
second-ranking Republican on the House Judiciary Committee during
congressional hearings on the break-in at the Democratic National
Committee headquarters in the Watergate complex in Washington.
   McClory was one of the leading House supporters of an article of
impeachment in 1974 charging Nixon with abusing his constitutional
powers in the Watergate matter. He drafted another article charging
the president with contempt of Congress for resisting subpoenas.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Ann Phillips</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRISTOL, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ann Phillips, Princess Anne's
mother-in-law, died Monday of a pancreas ailment at the age of 62.
   Mrs. Phillips was the mother of Capt. Mark Phillips, who in 1973
married Anne, the only daughter of Queen Elizabeth II.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>James Silver</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James Wesley Silver, 81, whose book critical
of white supremacy in Mississippi led to his dismissal from the
University of Missisippi faculty in the 1960s, died Monday.
   Silver came to Ole Miss as a history professor in 1936 and left
in 1965 at the request of the university's board of trustees
following publication of ``Mississippi: A Closed Society.''
   The book explored the racial divisions in Mississippi and
sharply criticized the state's white political establishment for
hanging on to visions of Confederate glories. Silver wrote five
other books: ``Edmund Pendleton Gaines,'' ``Confederate Mississippi
and Church Propaganda,'' ``A Life for the Confederacy,''
``Mississippi in the Confederacy'' and ``Running Scared: Silver in
Mississippi.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Heinz Pagels</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASPEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heinz R. Pagels, physicist, executive
director of the New York Academy of Sciences and adjunct professor
at The Rockefeller University, was killed Saturday in a
mountain-climbing accident. He was 49.
   Pagels began his academic career at The Rockefeller University
in 1966 and left as an associate professor in 1983 to become the
executive director and chief executive officer of the New York
Academy of Sciences.
   He was a theoretical physicist working in the area of
relativistic quantum field theory and cosmology and the author of
three books, including ``The Cosmic Code,'' ``Perfect Symmetry,''
and ``Dreams of Reason.'' Pagels was also a former board member of
the Aspen Physics Institute.
</TEXT>
