<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 0026EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-TrainDerailment     07-25 0165</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Train Derailment,0169</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Derailed Tanker Dumps Chemical</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WHITE BLUFF, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 20 railroad cars derailed
Sunday, dumping a chemical that can kill fish into a creek,
authorities said.
   About 20,550 gallons of a petroleum refinery waste product
drained from an overturned tanker, said Millie McGuigan, operations
officer for the Tennessee Emergency Management Agency. It was not
known how much of the substance actually went into Indian Camp
Creek, which eventually flows to the Harpeth River, Ms. McGuigan
said.
   There were no injuries and no evacuations, and the spill should
not threaten any drinking water supplies because of purification,
she said.
   But she added, ``It is harmful to aquatic life. When it gets in
the water it takes out oxygen.''
   The CSX Transportation rail cars were expected to be righted
Monday, she said.
   Officials from the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency, the
Dickson County sheriff's department and the Public Services
Commission were investigating, but the cause of the derailment was
unknown, Ms. McGuigan said.
</TEXT>
