<DOCNO> AP880725-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 0050EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BestCity     07-25 0623</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Best City,0646</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Danbury Ranked Top Place To Live</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NXJ1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA STOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DANBURY, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union Carbide Corp.'s chairman was
delighted that a national magazine named Danbury America's best
place to live, but another resident says she was stunned because
she finds the city boring.
   In its second-annual rating of 300 U.S. areas, Money magazine's
current issue ranked the Danbury metropolitan area as the most
livable
   Danbury, about 60 miles northeast of New York City in
southwestern Connecticut, once was known as the ``hat city''
because hatters plied their trade here starting before the American
Revolution. The last hat factory closed in 1987.
   Today, the city of about 70,000 people is the home of Union
Carbide, Danbury's largest employer.
   ``We are very happy here,'' said Robert D. Kennedy, chairman and
chief executive officer of the giant chemical company. And the
company, which moved its headquarters from New York City to an
innovative suburban complex in 1980-81, is here to stay, he added.
   ``There's no better place to be. We came at a time when the city
of Danbury was beginning the sort of comeback they've since
enjoyed,'' Kennedy said.
   But a shopper on Main Street said she was surprised about the
honor.
   ``I don't know why,'' said the woman, who identified herself
only as Barbara. ``It's boring. When we want to do something, we go
into the (New York) city.'' She said she hopes to move soon.
   Money magazine said Danbury unseated last year's No. 1 area,
Nashua, N.H., because of a lower crime rate, slightly better
schools and its proximity to New York.
   John Everett, an aide to Nashua Mayor John Donchess, said the
mayor, who was unavailable for comment, would not be upset about
losing the top spot because Nashua remained in the top 10.
   Everett said last year's top ranking gave the city more exposure.
   ``I'd go somewhere and say I'm from Nashua, New Hampshire, and
people would say they'd heard of it,'' he said. ``The old saying
used to be you go to Nashua on the way to somewhere else.''
   The magazine said its staffers studied government and private
data on the 300 largest metropolitan areas, ranking their crime
rates, housing, health care, economy, arts, education, transit
system, weather and leisure activities.
   Danbury Mayor Joseph H. Sauer Jr. said he was ``very proud.''
   ``I'm not naive to think this took place in the last eight
months,'' said Sauer, who became mayor in November. ``The reasons
are the objects of our concentrated efforts _ low crime rate,
medical facilities, parks and recreation _ we've worked on all of
it.''
   Sauer and Money magazine acknowledged that Danbury has its
problems. For example, a three-bedroom house typically costs
between $175,000 and $250,000.
   Danbury has had other troubles. The administration of former
Mayor James E. Dyer is the target of an FBI probe that resulted in
the confiscation of city expense and payroll records last year. And
a former part-time probate judge and Danbury lawyer allegedly
embezzled more than $3 million from trust funds under his care
before committing suicide last year.
   But many business owners who have worked and lived here their
entire lives wouldn't live anywhere else.
   Mary G. Cappiello, who runs a card shop on Main Street, said she
and her seven siblings were born in Danbury. Today, her 15 nieces
and nephews all live and work here.
   ``I would say it is (the best place to live),'' she said. ``I
think we have a lot going for us.''
   Her brother, Frank J. Cappiello, who runs a jewelry shop down
the street, said he was a little surprised by the top ranking.
   ``Palm Springs has got to be a better place,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
