<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SpeedTrapFlap     07-25 0254</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Speed Trap Flap,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>German Politicians Reported Angered By New Italian Speed Limits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some West German politicians are
calling lowered speed limits on Italian highways downright
inhospitable, saying they appear aimed at catching unsuspecting
German vacationers unawares.
   ``The purpose of this law is apparently to take money from
vacationers,'' the mass-circulation newspaper Bild quoted federal
lawmaker Ernt Hinken as saying.
   ``Many Germans will be caught without knowing the law has been
changed,'' Hinken, a federal lawmaker for the governing Christian
Democrats, reportedly told the paper.
   Under new rules that took effect on Sunday, the maximum speed
permitted on Italy's superhighways has been lowered to 110
kilometers per hour (68 mph) from 140 kilometers per hour (87 mph).
The maximum speed on Italy's regular highways fell to 90 from 110
kilometers per hour.
   Italian authorities said the speed limits were lowered because
of an increase in highway deaths.
   Thousands of West Germans are now taking to the road _ many of
them en route to Italy and other southern points _ to start their
summer vacations.
   There are no maximum speed limits on some sections of West
Germany's autobahns.
   Erwin Huber, a high-ranking politician with the Christian Social
Union, the CDU's Bavarian sister party, also criticized the lowered
Italian speed limits.
   ``Italy is a much-beloved vacationland with a reputation for
hospitality. But I do not think these measures are hospitable,''
Bild quoted him as saying.
   Bild's report, appearing it today's editions, was telexed to
other news organizations in advance.
</TEXT>
