<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Drought-Fires 1stLd-Writethru a0777 07-25 0849</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Fires, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0777,0866</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Forest Fires Around And Inside Yellowstone Park</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 4th graf `Hot, dry' to UPDATE with
Spokane fire under control. SUBS grafs 11-15 bgng `On the western'
with six grafs to UPDATE with North Fork blaze doubling in size,
sending up huge smoke column. UPDATES percentage of Sawtooth fire
contained. Picks up 16th graf pvs `The fire.'</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Mink Creek Fire, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A big Wyoming forest fire edged into Yellowstone National Park
on Sunday but appeared to be slowing down, and firefighters fought
to keep a separate fire inside the park from burning into Idaho.
   The south entrance to Yellowstone, along with the Grant Village
hotel and two campgrounds, remained closed Sunday because of other
fires in the park, but officials stressed that all major park
attractions remained open.
   Two fires that burned together over some 10,800 acres in
California's Gold Rush country were contained Saturday and 80
percent controlled Sunday, officials said. A fire is considered
contained when a fire break is built around it, and controlled when
it is reduced to smoldering patches.
   Hot, dry weather remained a factor as hundreds of acres of trees
and brush also burned Sunday in smaller fires in parts of
Washington, Oregon, Montana, Colorado and Utah.
   Despite temperatures that reached 94 degrees on the fire lines,
about 210 firefighters Sunday afternoon brought a 2,420-acre blaze
on the Spokane Indian Reservation in Washington under control, said
Norm Anderson, a Wenatchee National Forest official.
   The 22,650-acre Mink Creek fire in the Bridger-Teton National
Forest's Teton Wilderness grew by only 150 acres overnight but it
crossed the boundary of Yellowstone into a rugged backcountry area,
Dave Steinke, a fire information officer said Sunday.
   ``It pushed past Falcon Creek last night and moved just slightly
into the park, probably one-quarter of a mile,'' he said. ``We have
a few spots in the Yellowstone Meadows area. But we have a crew up
there mopping that up and it looks pretty good on the north end.''
   A lack of wind during the night helped the fire stay within
containment lines on its southern end, where it was within a few
miles of private property.
   ``We think it's calmed down,'' Steinke said. He said 737
firefighters were strengthening firebreaks and mopping up hot spots.
   ``We made very good progress (Saturday), and one reason was that
we didn't get the predicted adverse weather,'' said Dale Jarrell,
incident commander. ``Also, the crews are doing an outstanding
job.''
   On the western side of Yellowstone, a 1,300-acre blaze
threatening grizzly bear habitat in the park more than doubled in
size by nightfall Sunday, sending a column of smoke more than seven
miles into the air, authorities said.
   John Quackenbush, a helicopter pilot helping dump water on the
fire, said it was one of the biggest columns of smoke he had seen
in 14 years of such work.
   Forest Service spokesman Bruce Fox said earlier that 200
firefighters, assisted by nine fire engines, a helicopter and two
bulldozers, withdrew to construct a fire line running roughly
adjacent to the park's boundary to keep the North Fork fire from
crossing into the Targhee National Forest in eastern Idaho.
   ``Basically, we've decided to allow nature to take its course,''
he said.
   The blaze began Friday about a quarter mile inside the Targhee,
and then spread eastward into Yellowstone six miles south of the
point where the Idaho, Montana and Wyoming borders meet.
   Elsewhere in southern Idaho, in the Sawtooth National Forest
southeast of Twin Falls, the Poison Creek fire was about 40 percent
contained at more than 2,000 acres, authorities said.
   The fire was threatening a cutthroat and rainbow trout fishery
along with valuable deer habitat and recently transplanted bighorn
sheep and wild turkeys.
   In California, firefighters fought shifting wind, high
temperatures and a threat of lightning Sunday in an effort to
extinquish twin blazes in Calaveras County that caused $11 million
in damages. Fire crews hoped to put them out by Monday night.
   ``We're holding our breath, waiting to find out what the
weather's going to do to us,'' said Barbara Dashiell, a spokeswoman
for the California Department of Forestry in the Mother Lode
community of Rail Road Flat, 150 miles east of San Francisco.
   Six homes, nine other buildings and eight vehicles have been
lost since the arson-suspected blazes broke out Tuesday. There were
1,700 firefighters and support personnel on hand Sunday, down from
a maximum of 3,400 Friday.
   In Montana, 160 firefighters worked to contain a 250-acre blaze
in the Selway-Bitterroot Wilderness that threatened to spread into
an area filled with dead and dying trees, said Deanna Riede, a
Forest Service spokeswoman in Missoula.
   At least 120 firefighters battled summer heat and wind at a
blaze that scorched more than 250 acres of brush and timber near
Flaming Gorge Dam on the Utah-Colorado border, Ashley National
Forest spokeswoman Merle Young said.
   ``It's still an uncontrolled fire,'' Young said. No injuries or
property damage were reported from the blaze, which is believed to
have been ignited by fireworks.
</TEXT>
