<HEAD>Steven Spielberg's Beach Home Destroyed in Fire</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS to damaged sted destroyed in 1st graf, INSERTS one
graf with damage figures after 5th graf, ADDS one graf with film
credits.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MALIBU, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Director Steven Spielberg's
multimillion-dollar home was damaged Sunday in a fire that spread
to another oceanfront estate, authorities said.
   Spielberg, his actress-wife Amy Irving and their son, Max,
weren't home at the time of the blaze and there were no injuries,
authorities said.
   Arson investigators were dispatched to help determine the fire's
cause, Deputy Eric Smith of the Los Angeles County Sheriff's
Department said. Smith confirmed that Spielberg's home was involved.
   It took 40 firefighters about 40 minutes to extinguish the
blaze, authorities said.
   ``The first home (Spielberg's) was fully involved when we
arrived, then the second home caught fire,'' said county fire Capt.
Derek Reyna.
   Damage to the Spielberg home was estimated at $210,000, and the
neighboring residence sustained $120,000 in damage, said Reyna.
   Firefighters arrived at 6:41 p.m. and the fire was out by 7:18
p.m., Reyna said. He didn't know the name of the other homeowner.
   Other residents of the exclusive Broad Beach celebrity enclave
include Sylvester Stallone, Robert Redford, Carroll O'Connor and
Goldie Hawn. The homes generally are valued at $3 million to $10
million.
   Among Spielberg's hit films were ``Jaws,'' ``Close Encounters of
the Third Kind,'' ``Raiders of the Lost Ark,'' ``E.T. _ The
Extra-Terrestrial,'' ``Empire of the Sun,'' ``The Color Purple''
and the recently released ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit.''
