<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 0115EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush Bjt   07-25 0771</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, Bjt,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Proposes Child-Care Program, Starts Considering Running Mates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush, after outlining a $2.2
billion child-care program designed to help close his gender gap
with women, is turning his attention to selecting a running mate.
   The vice president says he expects to have ``some kind of a
list'' of potential running mates prepared by sometime this week,
although he hopes to delay announcing his choice until the GOP
convention next month.
   The certain Republican presidential candidate was expected to
spend much of this week mulling over his vice presidential
selection and had few campaign events scheduled.
   Meanwhile, Bush was drawing mixed reviews for his proposal for
child-care tax credits of up to $1,000 per child for low-income
families. For the neediest families _ those earning less than
$10,000 a year _ the ``credit'' would become a direct government
payment of the maximum $1,000 for each child of four or younger.
   Bush made the proposal Sunday in a speech to the National
Federation of Business and Professional Women's Clubs in
Albuquerque, N.M., ending a five-day burst of campaigning in seven
states.
   ``It was a gutsy move on the part of the vice president,'' said
Deborah Steelman, domestic affairs director for Bush's presidential
campaign.
   The vice president's plan was a sharp departure from the Reagan
administration's past policies on child care, and bears a price tag
similar to a $2.5 billion Democratic plan now before Congress.
   The Democratic proposal chiefly sponsored by Sen. Christopher
Dodd, D-Conn., which Democratic presidential nominee Michael
Dukakis has endorsed ``in concept,'' would provide the money to
child-care providers instead of to individual families as under the
Bush plan.
   Betty Wray, president of the federation to which Bush spoke,
called the plan ``one of the first concrete gestures that the vice
president has made'' on issues concerning women.
   But, she added, ``We know that George Bush has a problem right
now with women voters in this country. So until the Republican
party starts to very seriously take a look at those kinds of things
that are making a difference, it could pose real problems. ...
   ``There are simply not enough Republican men to get him (Bush)
elected without the woman's vote,'' she said.
   At the conclusion of his speech, many members of the audience of
2,500 women chanted ``E-R-A'' over and over, for the equal rights
amendment which Bush opposes and which he did not mention in his
talk.
   ``We would have liked to have him address the equal rights
amendment, which continues to be this organization's top
priority,'' federation president-elect Betty Forbes said. The
organization's leaders said Dukakis and Bentsen also had been
invited to address the convention, but had conflicting plans.
   There would be no strings attached to how the proposed Bush tax
credit-payment could be spent. To qualify, at least one adult
family member would have to be employed.
   Bush arrived in Albuquerque on Sunday on Air Force Two with
former Transportation Secretary Elizabeth Hanford Dole, a
frequently mentioned vice presidential possibility whose speech to
the group followed the vice president's.
   Mrs. Dole, wife of former GOP rival, Senate Republican leader
Bob Dole of Kansas, helped worked on the final draft of Bush's
speech, according to her aides.
   Bush spokeswoman Sheila Tate said there was no discussion of the
vice presidential selection process on the plane.
   The vice president told reporters that screening of potential
running mates _ to look into backgrounds and financial histories _
would begin this week. Prospective candidates will be asked to fill
out financial disclosure statements, he indicated.
   ``So by sometime next week, there will have to be some kind of a
list,'' he said.
   Bush told his Albuquerque audience his ``Children's Tax Credit''
would range up to $1,000 per child under age 4 and would be
``refundable'' _ meaning families could receive something from the
government even if they didn't earn enough to pay taxes.
   The vice president said the credit would be phased out as income
rises. He gave no details on exactly how this would be done.
   Background information provided by Bush's staff said the tax
credit would cost $1.5 billion a year.
   Bush's four-point program also included:
   _Expansion of the existing child-care tax credit to cover more
low-income families, for a cost of $400 million a year.
   _Creation of workplace child-care centers for all government
employees and a federally underwritten liability insurance program
for private centers, $50 million a year.
   _More federal assistance to help states and local governments
set up programs such as sick child care and before-and-after school
care, $250 million.
</TEXT>
