<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 0132EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan     07-25 0642</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White House Sidesteps Questions About Baker</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan returned from a midsummer's
vacation amid heightened expectations that Treasury Secretary James
A. Baker III will resign soon to run George Bush's presidential
campaign.
   Neither Baker nor White House officials would confirm publicly
that Baker will be leaving the Cabinet soon, although presidential
spokesman Marlin Fitzwater did not flatly deny it.
   Given the opportunity Sunday to say Baker would not leave the
treasury post, Fitzwater said only: ``He's still treasury
secretary. Put it that way.''
   But an administration official, declining to be named publicly,
said Baker's resignation likely will be submitted to Reagan in
early August, possibly as soon as next Monday, with plans to hook
up with Bush in mid-August.
   A Baker move to the Bush campaign would not be shocking since
there has been speculation for months that the longtime Bush
confidant eventually would move from the Treasury Department to the
campaign. Baker managed Bush's unsuccessful run for the GOP
presidential nomination in 1980.
   Baker accompanied Reagan and his wife, Nancy, on the flight from
California to Washington on Sunday, although the treasury secretary
was not observed boarding the plane with the Reagans at Point Mugu
Naval Air Station.
   Baker evidently had boarded before the contingent of reporters
arrived to greet the Reagans, who had flown to the military base
from their ranch in the Santa Ynez Mountains.
   The secretary also spurned a request by a pool of reporters on
Air Force One to come chat with them. Instead, he sent back a
folder that contained a dollar bill. Baker wrote, ``Please note the
title under the signature is secretary of the treasury.''
   Fitzwater said only that Reagan and Baker, who had been the
president's chief of staff from 1981-85, merely had a ``very brief
chat.''
   An official who discussed the situation on grounds of anonymity
said the secretary had spoken at a fund-raiser Saturday night for
Sen. Pete Wilson, R-Calif., and ``essentially, he is hitching a
ride.''
   But another official said Baker would not have needed to inform
Reagan of his plans on the Air Force One trip, saying the
secretary's decision to take over the vice president's campaign had
been known for some time.
   When Baker got off the plane at Andrews Air Force Base just
outside Washington, a reporter asked the secretary, ``Can you share
the news with us?''
   Baker replied, ``There's no news to share.''
   Asked if he had spoken with Reagan about quitting, Baker said he
had not.
   Baker has been an unofficial adviser to the Bush campaign for
some time, and had accompanied the vice president to Wyoming last
week for a fishing trip.
   If Baker were to leave, it would be the second major Cabinet
change in recent weeks. Attorney General Edwin Meese III, a
longtime Reagan friend, has resigned effective late this month or
early next month. Reagan nominated former Pennsylvania Gov. Richard
Thornburgh as Meese's replacement.
   While Reagan vacationed last week at his ranch near Santa
Barbara, Calif., senior aides discussed the administration's agenda
for the remainder of the president's term.
   This week Reagan will assess the prospects for new U.S. military
aid to the Nicaraguan rebels _ a subject that is on the agenda for
a Tuesday morning meeting with Republican congressional leaders.
   He also plays host Wednesday to Hungarian Premier Karoly Grosz
in the first such visit by a high-ranking Hungarian official since
the country came under communist rule 40 years ago.
   Since becoming premier in June 1987, Grosz has sought improved
economic and political ties with the West. Grosz began an 11-day
U.S. tour last week.
   Reagan will receive an updated report on the drought from
Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng, who took a 10-state tour
last week. The administration's midyear budget review also is due
this week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880725-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 0138EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-CampaignNotebook     07-25 0626</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Campaign Notebook,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Would There Be a Tomato Garden in a Dukakis White House?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the American people try to figure out
whether to put Mike Dukakis in the White House, the candidate
reveals that his daydreams about 1600 Pennsylvania Avenue leave him
with a perplexing question:
   Where do you put the tomato garden?
   ``I'm trying to figure it out _ wherever there's full sun,
right?'' he told reporters traveling with him over the weekend.
   The Massachusetts governor says he grows three varieties of
tomatoes in his back yard in Boston, along with some cucumbers and
peppers. He says he worries about them when he's on the campaign
trail, although his neighbor is watering them.
   Maybe it was the swing through California and North Dakota farm
areas that got him thinking about moving that vegetable garden to
Washington.
   It wouldn't be good to cut down any of the famous White House
trees. And don't worry about the Rose Garden. No point planting
there, he says, because it's too close to the building.
   ``A good tomato garden with cukes, peppers, has got to be right
out there'' in the open, ``Right?''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Dukakis is mindful that keeping ahead in the polls sometimes
requires placing things on your head.
   On his first post-convention campaign swing last weekend he
posed for pictures with a Scottish tam-o'-shanter and an Assyrian
headpiece and some baseball caps. No doubt, before campaign's end
he'll be donning an American Indian headdress, a cowboy had, hard
hat and others.
   Although he's not usually a hat man, he was taking it all in
stride until, at a rally in Erie, Pa., Mayor Lou Tullio showed up
with the special hat he built for the Democratic convention.
   The boater had a stuffed animal attached to the top holding up a
torch, sort of like a furry statue of liberty. It was the kind of
hat usually worn only at political conventions (last week's
featured such beauties as Wisconsin's cheese hats). But Tullio has
been ailing and couldn't make it to Atlanta. So he obviously
figured that having the party's new nominee in town was a great
time to show it off.
   But when he brought it out on the stage, Dukakis made no move to
touch it, looking at it as if the furry thing might bite. Finally,
Tullio balanced it on his own head, the crowd cheered with
approval, and Dukakis smiled.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   One of the most exciting moments for reporters covering the
Dukakis campaign swing came Friday when the press plane, landing in
Houston, slammed into the runway, bounced up, and then several
seconds later landed again.
   The Secret Service, which had several of its agents on the
plane, called for an inspection and on Saturday it appeared the
plane would be pulled out of service. However, repairs were
completed on time and the press plane continued to follow Dukakis
and running mate Lloyd Bentsen to Minot, N.D., St. Louis, and Erie,
Pa.
   After Erie, Bentsen and wife B.A. boarded the press charter
flight back to Washington, instead of continuing to Boston with
Dukakis.
   ``I've heard about this plane,'' Mrs. Bentsen said.
   ``I didn't want to get on this one until we tested it with you
guys,'' the senator quipped.
   Meanwhile, as the campaign moves into full swing, there are
tentative plans for Bentsen to take over Dukakis' Boeing 737 and
for the governor to charter a larger plane.
   Bentsen will be inheriting a plane that once was Republican Bob
Dole's campaign jet. Dukakis had the Presidential Airways plane's
exterior spruced up and its interior redone with a little office up
front separated by a curtain from the press and federal agents in
the back.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
