<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Cambodia Bjt   07-25 0660</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cambodia, Bjt,0681</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rivals Parley For Future Of Cambodia</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BOGOR2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOR, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sitting stiffly and avoiding eye
contact, the leaders of four groups fighting for Cambodia began
their first talks today to try to fashion a political settlement.
   Their host, Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas, said they
would discuss such difficult issues as national reconciliation,
forming a provisional government and building a neutral Cambodia,
which has been at war almost continuously since 1970.
   ``We of course realize that on these aspects ... there are
divergences of views among you and that many years of conflict and
contention have caused estrangment that may impede a quick
convergence of positions,'' he said in an opening speech.
   Alatas said such a complex problem couldn't be solved through a
single meeting, but a solution will never be found unless a start
is made to replace war with dialogue.
   The four Cambodian leaders gathered in a chandeliered room in
the old palace of the late President Sukarno for informal
``cocktail party'' talks that have raised hopes for peace in
Cambodia.
   In large easy chairs around a thick, circular table sat Hun Sen,
prime minister of Cambodia's Vietnamese-installed government, and
leaders of three guerrilla groups opposing him. They were Khieu
Samphan of the Khmer Rouge, Son Sann of the Khmer People's National
Liberation Front, and Prince Norodom Ranariddh, who is representing
his father, Prince Norodom Sihanouk.
   As they gathered, three saffron-robed Cambodian Buddhist monks
who had traveled from the United States, Canada and France filed
into the palace to pray for success.
   Vietnam, which invaded Cambodia in late 1978 and by Western
count maintains more than 100,000 troops there, was to meet the
Cambodians in a second stage of talks in the afternoon. That
meeting was also to be attended by Vietnam's Communist ally, Laos,
and by members of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations, which
backs the guerrillas.
   At a photo session just before the morning talks, the leaders
smiled at photographers and Khieu Samphan waved, but they
studiously avoided making eye contact with one another.
   Instead they gazed at huge Western-style oil paintings on the
walls.
   Hun Senn and Sihanouk have held two previous rounds of talks
without success, and the current meeting represents the first
gathering of all four Cambodia parties.
   Vietnam has never talked with the Cambodian resistance factions.
   Sihanouk, meanwhile, was visiting Jakarta, the Indonesian
capital just 40 miles from Bogor but had no known plans to attend
the talks. A Indonesian source said the former Cambodian monarch
might make an appearance in Bogor, depending on progress in the
talks.
   Earlier this month Sihanouk resigned as president of the
guerrilla coalition, charging the Khmer Rouge were killing his men.
   The tentative schedule called for two days of talks with the
second day having the same format as the first _ the Cambodian
factions talking in the morning, then the Vietnamese and others
joining in the afternoon.
   The talks are based on a July 1987 Vietnam-Indonesia agreement
that calls for informal discussions to encourage the various
antagonists to participate and allay Vietnam's refusal to negotiate
directly with the guerrillas.
   Disputes between Vietnam and Association of Southeast Asian
Nations delayed the talks, which were not confirmed until the last
minute. The association includes the Philippines, Thailand, Brunei,
Malaysia, Singapore and Indonesia.
   Since 1970, Cambodia has suffered a devastating five-year civil
war, a reign of terror by the Chinese-backed Communist Khmer Rouge
from 1975 to 1978, a 1978 Vietnamese invasion and a continuing
guerrilla war against the Vietnamese-backed government.
   Millions of people have been killed in the turmoil.
   Vietnam has announced it will withdraw 50,000 troops, or about
half its force in Cambodia, this year and the rest by early 1990.
   Though Son Sann and Sihanouk are allied with the Khmer Rouge in
a resistance coalition, they strongly distrust the Khmer Rouge
because it killed hundreds of thousands of people when it ruled
Cambodia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
