<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     07-25 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0605</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CASTLE SHANNON, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirty drivers saddled up their buses
for a 10th annual rodeo, as ribs and chicken sizzled on open-pit
grills.
   The Port Authority Transit rodeo was slower-moving than a
Western counterpart, but competitors said it requires an equal
amount of skill.
   ``A lot of people couldn't drive a car through this course, let
alone a 40-foot bus,'' driver Ed Gillett said Sunday as he eyed the
orange cones and barrels charting the course across the Castle
Shannon subway station parking lot, near Pittsburgh.
   The buses lumbered through the cones, squashing some along the
way. Judges in cowboy hats made notations on clipboards, and a
country-western band played.
   Drivers were allowed seven minutes to steer their buses through
the maze. Jim ``J.R.'' Jones, who hit the fewest cones in the
fastest time, won.
   ``They do serpentines, three-point turns, backward parking and
curbing the bus,'' said Debra DeCourcy, an organizer. ``The rodeo
allows them to show off their talent that most people take for
granted.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It used to be that Illinois' lottery millionaires
could count on leaving their wallets home at least one day a year _
the day of the Millionaire's Reunion.
   But this year, after criticism that the lavish reunions were a
waste of taxpayers' money, a thriftier affair is planned and the
millionaires are getting stuck with some of the tab.
   The big money winners used to get lunch on a cruise ship, dinner
and dancing at a classy spot and a night at a top hotel.
   At this year's reunion, on Aug. 19, they'll get beer, bratwurst
and baseball _ and they'll have to pay for their own hotel rooms.
   Chester Nyc, a $3.8 million-winner from Elk Grove Village, says
he'll attend the luncheon, but skip the Cubs game, dinner and a
special discount night at a Hyatt hotel.
   ``I thought the cost of last year's (reunion) was kind of
exorbitant, but I'm conservative that way,'' Nyc said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nine ducklings and their parents lived it up at
the swank Ritz Carlton Hotel where they swam in a Jacuzzi and dined
on escargot, fresh lettuce, melba toast and bottled spring water
served by white-gloved waiters.
   The ducklings were flown in from North Carolina for a
fund-raising re-creation Sunday of the 1941 children's book ``Make
Way for Ducklings,'' which is set in Boston's Public Garden's pond.
   Children from a private elementary school in Morganton, N.C.,
flew in Saturday on a charter flight along with the ducks and Robin
Edwards, an organizer of the event to raise money for the school.
   ``We visited Boston two years ago on a field trip and the
children saw the ducks,'' Edwards said. ``They were very familiar
with the book and that's when the idea for this project started.''
   In the story, a Boston policeman befriends the ducks, which take
up a residence in the pond.
   As Edwards read from the book Sunday, about 200 people gathered
around a sculpture that's near the pond and is dedicated to the
story.
   The ducks, billed as the only known descendants of Mr. and Mrs.
Mallard in Robert McCloskey's story, were taken in their cages to
the pond and set free.
   Organizers hope to raise funds for an addition at the school
through a $5-an-entry ``Name the Duck'' contest for the ninth
duckling. In the story, there are just eight ducklings: Jack, Kack,
Lack, Mack, Nack, Ouack, Pack and Quack.
</TEXT>
