<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     07-25 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mental Hospital Asks Day Outing for Hinckley</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: St. Elizabeths CQ without apostrophe</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Secret Service is opposing a request from
St. Elizabeths Hospital to allow presidential assailant John
Hinckley Jr. to leave the mental institution for a supervised day
trip with other patients.
   ``We don't believe he should be released under any conditions,''
Secret Service spokesman Rich Adams said Saturday. ``We believe him
to be a threat to our protectees and will continue to believe that.
There's nothing that's been shown to us to indicate he's any
different.''
   Hinckley was committed to the hospital in 1982 after he was
found innocent by reason of insanity in the shooting of President
Reagan, White House press secretary James Brady, a Secret Service
agent and a D.C. policeman.
   City mental health officials said a review board at St.
Elizabeths has approved Hinckley's participation in an outing to a
museum, park or other public place.
   But federal prosecutors have asked a judge to hold a hearing on
the proposed day trip. The last time St. Elizabeths sought
permission for an off-grounds activity for Hinckley was last year,
but the request was dropped after it was disclosed that Hinckley
had corresponded with Theodore Bundy, a convicted serial killer.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Officials Investigating Fires At Madagascar Embassy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City fire investigators are trying to
determine the causes of two fires that broke out two hours apart at
the Embassy of Madagascar.
   No one was injured in the fires, which happened before dawn
while Ambassador Leon M. Rajaobelina was home with his family.
   ``I smelled the smoke of the fire, so I decided to awaken my
family,'' said Rajaobelina said of the first fire, which broke out
in a reception area around 2:17 a.m. EDT.
   No injuries were reported in either fire and damage was
considered minor.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Panda Ling-Ling May Be Pregnant Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Keepers at the National Zoo are watching
Ling-Ling, the giant female panda, for signs that she may be
pregnant again.
   Recent laboratory tests show the same hormonal pattern that was
observed when Ling-Ling was pregnant last year, zoo spokesman Mike
Morgan.
   ``A lot of people are feeling positive, but no one will say for
certainty that Ling-Ling is pregnant,'' he said. ``There are
reservations.''
   If she is pregnant, she probably would give birth during the
last couple of days of July or the first week of August, he said.
She has given birth to four cubs at the zoo, all of which have died.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>New Corn Plant Could Help Third World</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government agency is touting a new strain of
corn as a potential source of protein for children in the Third
World.
   The National Research Council calls the new corn QPM for
quality-protein maize because it contains about twice the usable
protein of ordinary varieties. Maize is the international word for
corn.
   A small research team, working for 10 years, developed QPM at
the same laboratories where Nobel Peace Prize winner Norman E.
Borlaug produced the new wheat varieties that brought the ``green
revolution'' in the 1950s.
   The report suggests distributing QPM in areas that already
depend heavily on corn to feed small children: South America,
Central America, most of Africa, Bangladesh, Indonesia and the
Philippines.
   ``Maize is often the crop of the poor, and in the maize-growing
areas of the world, millions of children living in poverty are not
thriving,'' says the report of a panel appointed by the council.
``Here is an opportunity to explore this new approach to relieving
an intolerable situation.''
</TEXT>
