<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson     07-25 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Leaves Atlanta, Says Convention Was `Tremendous Moment'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson quietly ended his dramatic week in
Atlanta saying his mission now is to help Mike Dukakis win the
White House this year.
   ``My focus now is on the fall campaign,'' he told reporters as
he left a downtown Atlanta hotel Saturday. ``We'll be spending a
lot of time organizing for voter registration, issue
interpretation, involving people _ many for the first time _ and a
big turnout for the fall campaign.''
   Jackson, who finished second to Dukakis in his second race for
the presidency, would not talk about whether he would make a third
run for national office.
   ``We'll have to determine what will happen, based on the outcome
of the campaign. But we take this journey one phase at a time,'' he
said.
   Jackson took members of his family, campaign staffers and
journalists who covered his bid for the Democratic presidential
nomination to Paschal's, a well-known black-owned hotel and
restaurant, for lunch, then left from Fulton County Airport in a
chartered jet.
   Jackson's relaxed departure was a marked contrast to the
motorcade of buses he took to Atlanta July 16, two days before the
start of the Democratic convention.
   He addressed thousands of cheering supporters in Piedmont Park
that day, asserting that Dukakis, then assured of the nomination,
must give Jackson a stronger voice in the party.
   Jackson said Saturday his campaign made great gains in Atlanta.
   He said blacks and others previously outside the party
mainstream will have unprecedented involvement in the fall
campaign. And he noted that several Jackson platform positions were
adopted.
   ``We can leave Atlanta with a real sense of inspiration because
of the expansion of the Democratic Party, more inclusion,
involvement in the campaign at all levels, vertically and
horizontally,'' he said.
</TEXT>
