<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 0538EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     07-25 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0556</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms and Showers Sweep Through Midwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A cold front pushed showers and thunderstorms through the
drought-plagued central United States early today after lashing
several Midwestern states with large hail and strong winds that
ripped down trees and power lines.
   The storm system swept over southeastern Nebraska, northeastern
Kansas, and from eastern Iowa to western lower Michigan early today.
   Showers and thunderstorms also extended from southeastern New
Mexico to southwestern Oklahoma, and from northeast Arkansas into
western Kentucky and western Tennessee.
   The thunderstorms Sunday night spawned severe weather in
Nebraska, Wisconsin, Iowa and Oklahoma.
   In Nebraska, Uehling, Cedar Bluffs and Garland were pelted by
hail the size of golf balls. The storms also whipped winds to 73
mph at Brainard and downed trees at Seward.
   In Wisconsin, the large hail struck areas north of Rhinelander
and high winds ripped down trees and power lines at Sheboygan.
   In Lake City, Iowa, a dispatcher of the Calhoun County Sheriff's
Department said hail covered parts of the city Sunday night. ``The
ground was completely white,'' she said.
   In Holyoke, Mass., the roof of the Sears, Roebuck and Co. store
partially collapsed Sunday morning, police said. The store was
closed at the time and there were no reported injuries.
   A night of heavy rains may have caused the section of roof _
approximately 65 feet long and 10 feet wide _ to cave in, police
said.
   Early today, a few showers lingered along a cold front in the
eastern United States.
   Today's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
over Florida, the Georgia and Carolina coast, northern New England
and northeast New York, from Michigan across the lower Ohio and
middle Mississippi valleys to northern Mississippi, Arkansas and
north central Texas; and widely scattered afternoon thunderstorms
for the Southwest, with the most numerous storms in the mountains.
   High temperatures were forecast to be in the 70s over northern
New England and the upper Great Lakes region; between 95 and 100
degrees over interior portions of the lower Mississippi Valley;
between 95 and 105 over lower elevations west of the Rockies, near
115 degrees in portions of the desert Southwest; in the 70s and 80s
through most Pacific coast; and in the 80s and 90s over the rest of
the nation.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 51
degrees at North Bend, Ore., to 95 degrees at Phoenix, Ariz.
