<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Unrest     07-25 0510</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Unrest,0524</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strikes Said To End In Disputed Region, Though Some Fight On</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ethnic Armenians in the disputed Nagorno-Karabakh
region went back to tending fields, driving buses and building
homes today after their two-month strike failed to bring unity with
Armenia, state-run media reported.
   An end to the latest strike in the predominantly Armenian
enclave of the southern republic of Azerbaijan would signal a step
toward normalcy for an area in tumult since February.
   Still, a resident in Stepanakert, Nagorno-Karabakh's capital,
said some of the region's 162,000 people will press on with the
annexation campaign.
   ``Today people went to work. Transport is operating and we have
ended our strikes,'' reported the engineer for the State
Broadcasting Committee. She declined to give her name.
   ``The situation is still very tense,'' she said by telephone.
``The decision has done little for us and we will continue this
fight to the end. But what is the sense of continuing to strike?''
   The Kremlin leadership decided a week ago that Nagorno-Karabakh
will remain part of the Azerbaijan, which has ruled it since 1923.
   Nagorno-Karabh's Armenians, predominantly Christian like their
brethren in the neighboring Armenian republic, have waged a vocal
campaign for annexation. They contend they suffer discrimination
under the Azeris, most of whom are Moslem.
   The annexation drive was opposed by the Azerbaijani leadership,
and the struggle over control of Nagorno-Karabakh has fueled ethnic
tensions in the Caucasus.
   Mass demonstrations by Armenians in Nagorno-Karabakh and the
Armenian capital of Yerevan have drawn hundreds of thousands of
people. And on Feb. 28, the unrest became violent when 26 Armenians
and six other people were killed in the Azerbaijani city of Sumgait.
   After Moscow's rejection of the annexation bid became known in
Yerevan last week, activists called for a five-day protest strike.
But most residents heeded official warnings against prolonging the
labor unrest.
   Strikes continued in Nagorno-Karabakh through the weekend, but
state-run Radio Moscow reported today that most workers in the
region had decided to end the stoppage.
   Neither Radio Moscow nor the engineer reached in Stepanakert
explained why residents decided to return to work, and other calls
to the region did not go through.
   The official news agency Tass reported that the Armenian
Communist Party leadership met Sunday and that local officials were
blamed for allowing the annexation drive to get out of hand.
   Party leaders said ``the situation that has shaped in the
republic over the recent months has been a result of gross
miscalculations and errors in the political, organizational and
ideological work of party committees, of primary party
organizations,'' Tass said.
   Adhering to the tougher stance against ethnic strife outlined by
Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev in a speech a week ago, Tass
said the Armenian party leadership ``failed to sense the political
danger of unjustifiable calls for revision of the existing
national-territorial structure.''
   Pravda, the party's central newspaper, also criticized Armenian
party leaders who took up the cause of annexing the region, calling
for review and rectification of their ``political immaturity.''
</TEXT>
