<1ST_LINE>r i PM-TourdeFranceNewspage     07-25 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tour de France Newspage,0239</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delgado Of Spain, Longo Of France Win Grueling Race</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pedro Delgado of Spain won the Tour de France while
Jeannie Longo of Grenoble captured the title in the shorter women's
version of bicycling's most important race.
   Delgado, after five years of setbacks, crossed the finish line
first Sunday in the 75th running of the race, which began July 4.
He received messages from King Juan Carlos of Spain and a personal
welcome from more than 5,000 residents of his hometown of Segovia
who traveled to Paris to cheer their hero.
   ``In this moment I am thinking only of my mother,'' said
Delgado, 28, who was forced to withdraw from the 1984 Tour de
France when his mother died during the race. ``I promised myself I
would win this race for her.''
   With five stages left in this year's 2,036-mile race, he had
another crisis that threatened his lead, which he gained July 14.
It was revealed that a drug test taken July 15 turned out positive,
and a second test confirmed he had traces of probenicid in his
system.
   He was not penalized because the drug, often used to cover
detection of anabolic steroids, is not on the list of banned
substances of the International Cycling Union.
   For the second straight year, Longo, 29, of Grenoble in eastern
France, won the 524-mile women's race, which began July 11.
</TEXT>
