<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 0714EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Thailand-Election     07-25 0625</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Thailand-Election,0647</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governing Coalition Scores Majority In Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOLLY YONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parties that formed Prime Minister Prem
Tinsulanonda's last coalition government won 58 percent of the vote
in a general election, but analysts predicted today that Prem's
probable return to power will be beset by discord.
   ``The new government will face the same difficult problems it
endured under Prem's last administration because there is growing
and open resentment of and opposition to Prem,'' said political
scientist Somboon Suksamran of Bangkok's Chulalongkorn University.
   Since no pro-Prem party scored a majority in Sunday's polling,
the next government will again have to be made up of several
parties. In Prem's last government, frictions among coalition
partners proved troublesome.
   Somboon and other political analysts predicted that Prem, if he
is returned to power, probably would not finish his four-year term
without dissolving parliament or stepping down.
   Prem has served as prime minister since 1980, having dissolved
parliament twice, survived two attempted coups and formed five
different cabinets.
   A host of domestic pressures have been mounting, including
weakened support from the powerful military, sharp criticism from
opposition parties and recent labor and student protests.
   ``These pressures will only get more intense and will very
likely force Prem to make big decisions on whether he should cling
to his office,'' Somboon told The Associated Press.
   But the head of Chart Thai (Thai Nation) Party, which polled the
most votes in the country's 17th general election, said his party
would support Prem's continuation as prime minister.
   Chatichai Choonhavan told reporters today that a ``gentlemen's
agreement'' had been made among the four coalition partners to back
Prem.
   The well-financed Chart Thai won 87 seats in the 357-seat House
of Representatives while coalition partners accumulated another
123. The Social Action Party took 54; Democrat Party, 48; and
Rassadorn (Citizens) Party 21 seats.
   The strongest parties and other power centers in Thailand in
coming days are expected to engage in intense politicking and
bargaining before the next coalition is forged and a prime minister
named.
   The candidate who emerges must also be approved by Thailand's
powerful constitutional monarch, Bhumibol Adulyadej.
   Interior Minister Prachuab Soontrangkul announced that 16.9
million out of an eligible 26.6 million voters turned out for the
election.
   The voting was marred by a grenade attack against a local
politician in which two persons were killed and six others wounded.
   Officials also said Moslem separatists set fire to nine rural
schools, a health clinic and a rest house in the southern province
of Narathiwat in an apparent attempt to disrupt the elections. Some
of the schools were used as polling stations.
   A total of 3,606 candidates from 16 political parties contested
the seats in the lower house of Parliament.
   Among the opposition groups, the Prachakorn Thai (Thai Citizens)
Party led with 31 seats and the newly formed Palang Dharma (The
Power of Virtue) captured 14.
   Prem called the election 24 months early after he dissolved
parliament April 29, disbanding his coalition government and
nullifying a no-confidence motion tabled by his increasingly vocal
opposition.
   The 67-year-old former army chief has maintained silence over
whether he would accept another term, but most analysts believe he
would.
   Thai elections are largely centered on personalities, not
political platforms, and the main contention has been whether Prem
should return or not.
   Some people call the low-key prime minister ``Papa Prem;''
others criticize him as ``boring,'' quick to compromise and slow to
tackle national problems.
   But Prem, the longest-serving prime minister in modern Thai
history, has given the country a needed stability after years of
coups and attempted power grabs.
   Although his coalition has been beset by factionalism, he
remains favored by three powerful institutions: the military,
bureaucracy and constitutional monarchy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
