<DOCNO> AP880725-0048 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 0740EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     07-25 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Stocks Slip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar dropped sharply, then bounced back most
of the way today in Tokyo for a net loss of 0.28 yen, while stocks
slipped moderately lower.
   The U.S. currency ranged 1.65 yen between its high and low for
the day, despite a lack of market-affecting news, traders said.
   ``Some participants, especially investment trusts, saw the
dollar's decline in New York last Friday ad began selling dollars
in the morning, expecting it to go lower,'' said Masaharu Takenaka
of the Bank of Tokyo. ``But the market didn't go along with them.''
   He said participants in the afternoon found themselves in
dollar-short positions, and began buying back the U.S. currency.
   The dollar opened at 130.85 yen, down 1.23 yen from Friday's
close of 132.08 yen, and fell during the morning to as low as
130.20 yen. It recovered to as high as 131.85 yen before closing at
131.80 yen, down 0.28 yen. Spot volume was estimated at $7.7
billion.
   On Friday, the dollar closed in New York at 130.84 yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-share Nikkei Stock Average
dropped 117.81 points, or 0.43 percent, to finish the day's trading
at 27,183.53.
   Volume on the market's first section was a light 650 million
shares.
   Traders said many participants stayed on the sidelines because
of uncertainty in the foreign exchange market and the upcoming
release of U.S. gross national product figures, expected Wednesday.
   The Nikkei index initially gained about 70 points, but retreated
in the late morning.
   ``Depending on which direction the yen-dollar rate heads from
the current 130-yen level, investors will start moving one way or
the other,'' said Keiichi Nishida of Kidder Peabody.
   Traders said wild fluctuations in the market last week also had
scared off some private investors. The Nikkei index plunged more
than 600 points in last week's trading.
</TEXT>
