<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BusCrashes     07-25 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bus Crashes,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bus Crashes in N.J., Alabama, Leave 1 Killed, 69 Injured</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Bus crashes in two states took the life of one woman and injured
69 passengers, with the driver of one being charged with reckless
driving and the other being praised for stopping his skidding bus
from plunging into a ravine.
   A Colonial Trailways bus en route from Mobile to New York on
Sunday swerved to avoid a car apparently driving on the wrong side
of a two-lane Alabama highway.
   The bus skidded for about 30 feet after it overturned and came
to a stop with the back of the bus in a shallow part of the ravine
and the front jutting about 15 feet in the air.
   The accident, three miles south of Camden in southwestern
Alabama, killed Rosie Gulley, 68, of Brooklyn, N.Y., according to
Alabama troopers, and left 34 other people injured.
   In Edison, N.J., a charter bus driver was charged with reckless
driving after his bus crashed into a bridge abutment, shearing off
most of the roof and injuring 35 passengers who had just left a
family reunion. One was still in critical condition this morning.
   Edison Police Sgt. Bill Bunting said the bus, which originated
in Virginia, struck the abutment of a railroad bridge Sunday
afternoon. The bus carried 46 passengers and the driver, Bunting
said.
   The driver, 43-year-old Sherman Lassiter of Suffolk, Va., was
issued a summons for careless driving, Bunting said. Lassiter, a
driver for United Coach Corp. of Suffolk, failed to observe a sign
warning of low bridge clearance and was driving above the speed
limit, he said.
   State Police Capt. George Jones said the driver of the bus
involved in the Alabama accident said he had swerved to avoid an
oncoming car. Jones said that was under investigation.
   State police spokesman Will Rogers said the bus was carrying 34
passengers and the bus driver. Four people were hospitalized
overnight for observation.
   Passenger Stephen White, a Marine sergeant, credited the driver
for keeping the bus from plunging into the ravine.
   ``I thought the driver did an outstanding job in the way he
handled the bus,'' White said. ``It might have been a lot worse for
us.''
</TEXT>
