<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PigChase     07-25 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pig Chase,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Future Looks Murky for Elusive Piglet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owner of a 40-pound pet piglet that
eluded police for three hours until it paused for a handful of
horse feed was told his porker may be killed if it isn't picked up
within five days.
   But Blackie's owner, David Allen Brown, 32, will be in the
Hillsborough County Jail until at least Aug. 5, when he's scheduled
to appear before a judge on a parole violation charge, his mother
said.
   Brown was notified Saturday that the 8-month-old pig will be
``terminated'' if it isn't claimed in five days, said his mother,
Dorothy Brown.
   She said she would take the pig into her suburban home, but
``you know what the neighbors would say.''
   She's hoping some farmer will come to the porker's rescue.
   Blackie's brush with the law began Thursday when police stopped
Brown and a computer check showed he was wanted for violating
probation on a charge of driving under the influence of alcohol.
   Blackie slipped out of Brown's arms and made a clean getaway.
Officer Gary Yost and another officer spent the next few hours
pursuing Blackie until a member of the Sheriff's Office
agricultural unit was called in for assistance.
   Deputy Jack ``Hi-Ho'' Hrabovsky used a handful of horse feed to
stop and capture Blackie, who was sent off to a Sheriff's Office
facility.
   Sheriff's Office spokesman Jack Espinosa said he was not sure
what the guidelines on animals called for, but he noted that in
many livestock cases, the animals were kept for a specific time and
then auctioned.
   ``The last thing I heard ... was that this was a pet, that we
have his pet and that we would keep the pig until it is claimed,''
he said.
   Brown's mother said her son, who has always liked pigs, received
Blackie from a friend as payment for a plumbing job. She said he
intended to give the pig to relatives who live on a farm.
</TEXT>
