<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Afghanistan 1stLd-Writethru a0482 07-25 0719</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Afghanistan, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0482,0738</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Officer Predicts Collapse of Afghan Government</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS one graf to update with report on casualties since
pullout began.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet general says he doubts Afghan troops can
survive when the Red Army withdraws from Afghanistan. He also
predicts that Islamic fundamentalists will seize power.
   The statements by Maj. Gen. Kim M. Tsagolov, who was once an
adviser to the Afghans, represent a break with Moscow's official
line.
   In an interview with the weekly Ogonyok magazine, Tsagolov says
Afghanistan's ruling party is hopelessly disorganized, plagued by
corruption and has bungled opportunities to make peace with
insurgents. He also accuses the Soviet media of exaggerating Soviet
and Afghan military victories.
   The interview appeared in the magazine's July 30 issue, which
subscribers received Sunday.
   Western military and political analysts have said for some time
they doubt the Afghan army can fight off U.S.-backed rebels on its
own. They have predicted a collapse of the communist Afghan
government in Kabul after the Soviet pullout is completed next year.
   Tsagolov, who teaches philosophy at a military academy, is
believed to be the first Soviet official to make similar
predictions publicly.
   Ogonyok has led the campaign for glasnost, or greater openness,
on selected topics.
   The official Soviet line has held that Afghan government forces
are well prepared to defend their country. Lt. Gen. Boris Gromov,
commander of Soviet forces in Afghanistan, told reporters in Moscow
last month that the Afghan government has created an effective
fighting force.
   Asked if he is confident Afghan forces can provide adequate
defense from rebel attacks after a Soviet withdrawal, Tsagolov told
Ogonyok: ``If you judge the Afghan army by its current state, then
I don't have the confidence about which you speak.''
   The Soviet Union began withdrawing its troops from Afghanistan
May 15. Under the terms of a U.N.-brokered accord, half of the more
than 100,000 troops must be out by mid-August and the rest by Feb.
15.
   The official Tass news agency said Saturday that more than
35,000 soldiers have been withdrawn. Meanwhile, Kabul is coming
under increasing guerrilla artillery fire.
   President Najib of Afghanistan says he is counting on the
continued help of Soviet advisers for his 50,000 regular army
troops after the Kremlin's forces are gone. He has said his forces
can defend the country as long as outside assistance to the rebels
is stopped.
   Tsagolov noted that Afghan forces, even when backed by Soviet
troops, have made little headway in capturing rebel-held territory.
He said official Soviet press reports exaggerated military
victories and suffered from a ``deficit of truth'' about how tough
the combat was.
   The Aghan army is weak, he said, because the ruling People's
Democratic Party and the government lack popular support and have
underestimated the threat of the armed opposition. He recommended
the government devote massive resources to building up the army.
   Asked what the situation would be like when the Soviet
withdrawal is completed, he predicted ``activization of the Islamic
factor.''
   ``In the future, it's quite possible that Islamic
fundamentalists will appear,'' he said.
   Some Afghan guerrillas want to establish an Islamic
fundamentalist state.
   Tsagolov said the Afghan leadership had been insensitive to
religion and thereby alienated much of the population, drawing them
to the opposition.
   He said Najib's policy of national reconciliation, an attempt to
bring opponents into the government, has failed even though
internal opponents are tired of war, willing to engage in dialogue
and hostile to the seven-party Afghan guerrilla alliance based in
Pakistan.
   ``This also can be considered a lost opportunity of the Kabul
leadership,'' Tsagolov said.
   He said the ruling Afghan party is split into factions, pays
little attention to people's needs and is plagued by bureaucracy
and bribery.
   ``I fear that the disease of fractional battle and system of
clans in the party has gone too far,'' Tsagolov said.
   Soviet troops entered Afghanistan in December 1979 to help the
Soviet-backed Kabul government fight the rebels.
   The Kremlin says 13,310 Soviet soldiers have been killed in the
war, 35,500 have been wounded and more than 300 are missing in
action.
   Tass reported today that since May rebel forces have bombarded
Kabul with 178 rockets and 30 mines, killing 154 people and
wounding 205 in the Afghan capital.
</TEXT>
