<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--FraserLight     07-25 0187</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Fraser Light,0193</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stoplight Signals Progress</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRASER, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Progress has found its way to this mountain
community in the form of the first traffic light in Grand County.
   ``It's going to be a shock to some people, but it's very needed
and probably will save someone's life,'' said Vicky Winter, town
clerk.
   The light is scheduled to go up at U.S. 40 and Grand County 72,
the entrance to a shopping center that has created periodic traffic
jams.
   The busy ski resorts of Winter Park and Silver Creek, about 75
miles northwest of Denver, are nearby.
   ``We've had lots of injury accidents at that intersection in the
past three or four years, but fortunately no one has been killed,''
said Richard A. Leonard, a Grand County commissioner.
   ``I would hope we could get it up before winter, but delivery
time for the arms is considerable,'' said Jim Bragdon, a traffic
engineer with the Colorado Department of Highways. ``There's a lot
more work that you would ever realize in a traffic signal.''
   The signal will leave only 18 of Colorado's 63 counties without
traffic lights.
</TEXT>
