<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 0946EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Egypt-Escape     07-25 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Egypt-Escape,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Kill Escaped Prisoner Sentenced In Sadat Murder</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police today shot and killed a former army
officer who escaped from prison while serving a life sentence in
the assassination of President Anwar Sadat, the government
announced.
   Essam el-Kemary, 37, a former major, was killed in a hail of
gunfire when police attacked an apartment he and two other
fugitives used as a hideout, an Interior Ministry statement said.
   Two police officers were wounded when the police gunfire was
returned with a volley of bullets and explosive charges from the
hideout. Both officers were reported in satisfactory condition in a
hospital, the ministry statement said.
   It was not clear whether the two other fugitives _ Mohammed
Khamis, 40, and Ahmed el-Aswani, 31 _ escaped before police stormed
the apartment in Cairo's el-Sharabiya district.
   In the apartment, the ministry said, police found plastic bombs.
   A ministry spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
security forces were searching for the two other fugitives.
   Police sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
el-Kemary was ``by far the most dangerous'' of the three escapees.
   The dawn attack ended a nationwide manhunt that the Interior
Ministry launched after el-Kemary and the two others, also serving
life sentences in Sadat's killing, escaped July 17 from the
maximum-security Tura jail on the outskirts of Cairo.
   In the dawn jailbreak, the three men forced open their prison
cell with an iron bar and overpowered the guards, seizing their
rifles and knocking one man unconscious. The fugitives then shot
their way out of the prison to a getaway car, police said.
   According to the government, the three men were members of a
Moslem fundamentalist group known as Jihad, or Holy War. Jihad was
blamed for Sadat's slaying at a military parade on Oct. 6, 1981,
and a subsequent coup attempt.
   Sadat's assassination sparked a security crackdown on Moslem
extremists. After a series of trials, three convicted assassins
were executed by firing squad, another two were hanged and more
than 120 men were given prison terms up to life.
   El-Kemary, Khamis and el-Aswani were convicted of planning the
assassination and the coup attempt, in addition to membership in an
armed group _ Jihad _ trying to disrupt the public order. The three
did not actually shoot at Sadat.
</TEXT>
