<1ST_LINE>r a PM-VanderbiltSuicide     07-25 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vanderbilt Suicide,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vanderbilt Tried To Talk Son Out Of Jumping</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heiress and designer Gloria Vanderbilt was
trying to talk her despondent son out of killing himself when he
jumped from a ledge at her 14th floor apartment and fell to his
death, police said today.
   Carter Cooper, 23, had been under treatment for depression over
the past six months. Friends speculated his depression was the
result of a break-up with a girlfriend.
   Police said Cooper, a 1987 Princeton graduate and a writer and
editor at the Public Interest in Washington and American Heritage
in New York, had gone to his mother's home on the Upper East Side
for lunch Friday.
   Ms. Vanderbilt told police her son arrived depressed and went
upstairs after lunch to lie down.
   ``A few hours later she went to check on him and she found him
sitting on a ledge,'' said Officer Hugh Barry.
   Barry said Ms. Vanderbilt was pleading with her son not to jump
when he suddenly pushed himself off.
   ``The case is considered virtually closed,'' said Sgt. Diane
Kubler.
   Toxicological tests were performed to determine if drugs or
alcohol were in his system when he died. The results will take
several days.
   ``I had a very high regard for his intelligence and his literary
skill,'' said Norman Podhoretz, editor of Commentary magazine and a
columnist at the New York Post. Cooper had a piece published in
Commentary, a neo-conservative magazine published by the American
Jewish Committee, while he was a student.
   Ms. Vanderbilt, dubbed the ``poor little rich girl'' when she
became the focus of a heated custody battle in the 1930s, was in
seclusion and under a doctor's care, police said. She has three
remaining sons.
   Ms. Vanderbilt, 64, is a great-great-granddaughter of railroad
and shipping magnate Cornelius Vanderbilt.
   Cooper's father was Ms. Vanderbilt's fourth husband, writer
Wyatt Cooper, who died in 1978.
</TEXT>
