<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Ireland-Pilgrimage 1stLd-Writethru a0511 07-25 0677</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ireland-Pilgrimage, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0511,0695</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede Belfast</HEAD>
<HEAD>Sinn Fein Member Killed In Belfast During O'Connor Visit</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 14 grafs to update with killing, O'Connor sermon
in Armagh, edit for transition. Picks up 11th graf pvs ``O'Connor
said...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICK HAMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ARMAGH, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assailants shot and killed a
Belfast member of the IRA's political wing today as Cardinal John
O'Connor of New York, delivering a sermon a mile away, denounced
Americans who ``romanticize violence'' in Ireland.
   Brendan Davidson, 33, was shot in the head as he answered a
knock at his door from three men who apparently were dressed as
policemen, police said.
   Davidson belonged to Sinn Fein, the legal political wing of the
outlawed Irish Republican Army, and was wounded in an assassination
attempt last year. Sinn Fein blamed Protestant extremists for his
killing.
   On Saturday, an IRA bomb killed a Protestant couple and their
6-year-old son as they were driving just north of the
Ireland-Northern Ireland border.
   The mostly Roman Catholic IRA, fighting to drive Britain out of
Northern Ireland and unite the island, has accepted responsibility,
saying it attacked the wrong car. Press reports say the intended
victim was a Northern Ireland judge.
   Davidson was shot at his home on Friendly Street as O'Connor,
leading a American peace pilgrims on a tour of Ireland, was
attending Mass with 400 congregants at St. Peter's Church in the
heart of Catholic West Belfast.
   O'Connor was told of Davidson's killing as he left Belfast.
Several hours later, the cardinal deplored the assassination in his
sermon to an ecumenical service at St. Patrick's Cathedral in
Armagh.
   He said the killing, along with Saturday's bombing, ``poignantly
brought into focus the stupidity, the irrationality of the cycle of
the violence ... Where can this conceivably end? How this can
conceivably please almighty God?''
   In Belfast, O'Connor criticized ``some on our own shores, some
in my own country, who romanticize violence when it is several
thousand miles away, who don't know what it does to a land, who
don't know the insecurity that it brings, who don't know how it
keeps a people oppressed.''
   The Catholic prelate developed the theme in Armagh, criticizing
Americans who ``continue to perpetuate the myth that this violence
reflects the glory of Ireland, that we can stand around pianos and
sing sentimental songs and believe that what occurs today is in the
tradition of the martyrs and the saints.
   ``Isn't it time that we dispelled such myths? Isn't it time that
we... recognized that in the sight of almighty God, a Protestant, a
Catholic, a Jew, a Moslem, a Buddhist, is a person of sacred
worth?''
   O'Connor urged Americans to heed his host in Belfast, Bishop
Cahal Daly, who ``has recognized that regardless of the motive or
the alleged motive, violence, the murder of the innocent, is
absolutely intolerably evil and can never be justified.''
   The cardinal also backed Daly's call to the British government
for more funding to combat unemployment.
   St. Peter's Cathedral in Belfast overlooks the Divis Flats
housing project, which O'Connor toured Sunday. He urged American
business to create jobs and deprive the IRA of recruits.
   O'Connor said the hopelessness he encountered at Divis Flats,
where the unemployment rate is 86 percent, ``grinds into my soul.''
   ``I think it would be a tremendous contribution, if far more
American industry were to invest over here,'' he said.
   The cardinal acknowledged that violence makes it hard to attract
industry to Northern Ireland. ``Industry is not going to risk
(coming here) if it feels it is going to be subjected to terrorist
activity. So the wheel keeps turning,'' he said.
   During his visit to Divis Flats, he was surrounded by children,
several of whom he asked to ``Give me five.''
   While slapping hands with the prelate, Mary Brannin, 10, asked
him ``What is a cardinal?.''
   O'Connor retorted with a laugh, ``It's a red bird.''
   ``That was great for me,'' O'Connor later told reporters. ``That
reminds you it's all a lot of puffery. It brings you down to
earth.''
</TEXT>
