<1ST_LINE>d a PM-AutoPrices     07-25 0217</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Auto Prices,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chrysler Tells Dealers Of Fleet Price Increase; Retail Prices
Unknown</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. has told its auto dealers that
prices for fleets of 1989-model cars will increase between 3
percent and 5 percent, a company spokesman said today.
   However, those tentative increases may not have a bearing on
final retail prices, which are expected to be announced in August
along with final fleet prices, said spokesman Tony Cervone.
   Auto dealers frequently sign contracts to deliver new cars
before the model year starts for large fleet customers, such as
rental car companies.
   ``You give your fleet prices (early) so dealers can lock in
prices early,'' he said.
   Final prices may fluctuate depending on a number of things,
including competitors' prices and, to a smaller extent, sales
figures and inventories, Cervone said.
   Last year, Chrysler announced 8 percent to 12 percent retail
price increases but wound up with final increases less than that.
The prices for some of the company's slowest selling 1988-model
cars fell, compared with 1987 models.
   At Ford Motor Co. today, spokesman Dave Krupp said there was no
firm schedule for notifying dealers of tentative fleet prices for
the coming model year.
   General Motors Corp. spokesman Dave Hudgens said today he had no
immediate comment on fleet or retail prices.
</TEXT>
