<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 1040EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SmokelessChicago     07-25 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Smokeless Chicago,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chicago's Smoking Ban Goes Into Effect</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite a new anti-smoking law, smokers were
lighting up today in taxicabs, airport terminals, bus stations and
other forbidden places.
   ``There hasn't been any difference today,'' said Loice Wright, a
ticket agent with the Chicago Transit Authority. ``People aren't
paying any attention to the ban.''
   Smoking also is banned in subway stations.
   The law, which took effect Sunday, forbids smoking in enclosed
public places and requires employers to designate no-smoking areas
if requested by workers.
   ``We're complying with the ordinance,'' Kathy Gucfa, spokeswoman
at Sears Roebuck and Co. corporate headquarters in downtown
Chicago, said today. She said she knew of no complaints about the
new law from the 8,000 headquarters employees.
   Similar laws have taken effect in New York, Los Angeles and
other cities around the country.
   However, if non-smokers here were annoyed by smokers' behavior,
the police hadn't heard about it.
   ``We've had no complaints at all,'' officer Emmett O'Connell
said Sunday night at police headquarters.
   Police Supt. LeRoy Martin has pointed out that the ordinance
creating the ban, while it established fines of $25 to $100, did
not give officers the power of arrest. He's suggested that
non-smokers give dirty looks to people smoking where they shouldn't.
   But some non-smokers don't seem to care.
   ``I don't think it should be that big an issue,'' said
non-smoker Jim O'Brien. ``Smoking has been a way of life in this
country for years. To take that away now is unfair.''
   Frank Niemien, who quit smoking two years ago, said he doesn't
like the ban either.
   ``What else are they going to take away?'' he said. ``They'll be
coming into our bedrooms pretty soon and telling us what to do
there.''
   Although smoking in taxicabs also is outlawed, taxi driver Dean
Davis, a three-pack-a-day smoker, said: ``I'll smoke in my own cab
no matter what the law says. I will never tell a passenger not to
smoke.''
   Taxi driver Suheil Ajaj, who said he doesn't smoke himself, said
he believes taxi riders have a right to light up. ``I believe the
customer is paying for the right to smoke,'' he said.
</TEXT>
