<DOCNO> AP880725-0067 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 1059EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-BoatSinks     07-25 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Boat Sinks,0238</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Death Toll in Boat Disaster Rises to 72</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescue workers have recovered 72 bodies from a
passenger boat that sank last week in the fast-flowing waters of a
Yangtze River tributary, the official Xinhua News Agency said today.
   Xinhua said rescue work continued for about 30 other people
still missing and presumed to have gone down with the vessel when
it struck a rock Thursday in the Min River in southwest China's
Sichuan province.
   The news agency said 152 people had been rescued. There have
been differing estimates of the number of dead and missing because
of the remoteness of the area and confusion about how many people
were on the boat.
   Xinhua said rescue efforts were being hampered by rapid currents
in the river, which was swollen from torrential rains.
   The Chuanyun No. 24 had been traveling in a remote mountain area
between the towns of Yibin and Leshan, stopping along the river to
pick up and unload passengers. The boat was owned by the Chongqing
Shipping Co.
   The China News Service, another official news agency, said today
the sunken boat, which had been carried downstream by the
undercurrent, had been located by Sunday and divers had reached the
location.
   The news service said most of the missing were from towns and
villages near where the boat sank. There were apparently no
foreigners aboard.
</TEXT>
