<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Chile-Candidate     07-25 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chile-Candidate,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pinochet Expected To Be Single Presidential Candidate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chile's four top military commanders will
meet Aug. 30 to pick the candidate for the presidential referendum
later this year, the government announced today.
   President Augusto Pinochet, 72, the right-wing military
commander who has ruled Chile since coming to power in a 1973 coup,
is widely expected to be the lone candidate.
   It will be the first presidential voting in Chile since 1970,
when Salvador Allende, a Marxist, was elected. He died in the coup
led by Pinochet.
   The presidential nomination is to be made by Pinochet, the army
commander, and by Air Force chief Gen. Fernando Matthei, Navy
commander Adm. Jose Toribio Merino, and national police chief
Rodolfo Stange.
   The nomination, based on a 1980 military-drafted Constitution,
must be unanimous and made within 48 hours. If the four commanders
disagree, the candidate is to be chosen by the National Security
Council, made up of Pinochet, the four-member military junta and
the presidents of the Supreme Court and the Council of State. The
latter is a Pinochet-appointed official.
   The Constitution mandates that the vote be held within 30 to 60
days after the nomination of the candidate.
   Matthei said last week that the date for the vote has been set,
but he would not disclose it. The vote is widely expected to be
held in the first week of October, according to unofficial reports.
   In the voting, Chileans will only be able to vot ``yes'' or
``no'' on the candidate.
   If he wins approval, the candidate will serve an eight-year term
starting March 11, 1989. If he is rejected by voters, a
multi-candidate election will be held in 1990, with Pinochet
remaining in power until then.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
