<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Drought-Trout     07-25 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought-Trout,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drought Has Trout Farmers Rushing From Hatcheries To Streams</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARION, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Weeks of dry, hot weather are forcing the
state's four trout farms into a race with drought as workers rush
to transfer fish from too-warm hatching troughs to cooler streams
before they die.
   ``The warmer the water the less oxygen the water has, and we
have trouble keeping them alive,'' said Tom Ort, a worker at the
state's Armstrong Fish Hatchery in Marion.
   ``We'd rather give the fishermen their fish a month early rather
than keep them.''
   Because of the summer drought, the state Wildlife Resources
Commission must finish stocking 600,000 fish in streams, lakes and
rivers by the end of July, a month earlier than usual, officials
say.
   Already, the water in Armstrong Creek, which feeds into
fish-hatching troughs at the Armstrong hatchery, has topped 70
degrees three times this month, Ort said. Water levels in the creek
have dropped as well, forcing Ort to allow seven of his 20 ponds to
dry up.
   Most of western North Carolina's 2,000 miles of trout streams,
lakes and rivers must be stocked by the commission to maintain the
popular sport of trout-fishing.
   The state's trout-stocking program breeds the fish and raises
them from eggs to a catchable size _ 8 inches or longer when the
fish are about 18 months old, officials say.
   Once in the state's rivers and streams, most trout are caught
within a week or two, said Mallory Martin, a production coordinator
for the Wildlife Commission in Marion.
   ``I would expect the catch to be higher than usual because the
water levels have been so low the fish don't have a place to escape
to,'' Ms. Martin said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
