<1ST_LINE>u i PM-India-Punjab     07-25 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Punjab,0386</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sikh Extremists Kill Golden Temple Head Priest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARBAKSH SINGH NANDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   -
   CHANDIGARH, India (AP) _ Sikh extremists today shot and killed
the head priest of the Golden Temple, Sikhism's holiest shrine in
the city of Amritsar, police said.
   The militants also killed a secretary of the temple committee,
according to police.
   The victims were identified as head priest Sohan Singh and Bhan
Singh, secretary of the Shiromani Gurdwara Prabandhak Committee,
which manages Sikh temples.
   The head of the committee, Mal Singh Ghuman, suffered at least
four bullet wounds and was reported in critical condition in a
hospital, police said.
   According to police, Sikh extremists opened fire on the three
men at noon on a street in Ludhiana, about 55 miles west of the
state capital of Chandigarh.
   The assailants sprayed them with bullets from a AK-47 Chinese
rifle as the three emerged from a board meeting of an engineering
college, Indian news agencies said.
   There was no immediate claim of responsibility for the attack.
   The temple committee appointed Sohan Singh head priest in May,
after police and paramilitary troops forced more than 150 Sikh
extremists out of the Golden Temple, which they used as a base to
wage their guerrilla war for an independent homeland in the
northwestern state of Punjab.
   The head priest's predecessor and four other Sikh high priests,
who were jailed during the operation, remain in police custody.
   The appointment of Sohan Singh, a moderate, was opposed by the
militants, who also objected to the priest's efforts to exonerate
former Punjab Chief Minister Surjit Singh Barnala. Barnala had been
excommunicated from the Sikh faith by radical priests in charge of
the temple.
   Police today reported four other deaths in extremist violence in
Punjab.
   The latest victims raised to at least 1,560 the number of people
killed by Sikh militants in Punjab this year. An estimated 690 of
those killed have been Sikhs.
   The Sikh religion was founded about 500 years ago as an
alternative to Hinduism and Islam.
   Sikhs make up less than 2 percent of India's population, but
they are a majority in Punjab. Militant Sikhs contend members of
the faith are discriminated against by India's majority Hindus.
</TEXT>
