<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru   07-25 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0529,0522</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Frees Palestinian Protesters After Riots In Occupied Lands</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS 6th graf ``The army today...'' to remove reference
to Negev desert being in the Gaza Strip.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arab assailants today stoned an Israeli army
jeep in the occupied Gaza Strip, forcing the jeep to veer off the
road and turn over, the army said. Four military police were
injured.
   The incident occurred several hours after the army freed 148
Palestinian prisoners from Gaza as a goodwill gesture to Moslems on
the four-day Eid al-Adha holiday, or ``Feast of the Sacrifice.''
   An army spokesman said the jeep carrying green-uniformed border
patrol guards was stoned as it patrolled the Jabaliya refugee camp.
   The driver was injured in the hand and veered off the road, said
the spokesman, who could not be identified in accordance with army
regulations. Three other police suffered minor injuries and two of
them were taken to a hospital, he said.
   Arab news reports said soldiers immediately clamped a curfew on
the camp, banning more than 60,000 residents from leaving their
homes.
   The army today freed 148 Palestinians from the Ketziot tent
prison in the Negev desert, a spokesman said.
   He said some had been jailed without trial and the rest were
serving short sentences for crimes linked to the Palestinian
uprising.
   Israel radio said more than 3,000 Palestinian detainees would
remain in Ketziot. The army said it held more than 5,000
Palestinian prisoners in Ketziot and other prisons.
   The prisoners' release came a day after confrontations in the
occupied territories left two Palestinians dead and six wounded,
raising to 233 the Arab death toll since the uprising began Dec. 8.
Four Israelis have also died.
   Seven cities and refugee camps in the West Bank remained under
curfew today after the clashes, the army said.
   The unrest was partly triggered by coinciding Jewish and Moslem
holidays. The Moslem feast marks when the biblical patriarch
Abraham was ordered by God to sacrifice his son, Isaac.
   The Jewish commemoration marks the destruction of a Jerusalem
temple by Roman rulers nearly 2,000 years ago.
   A holiday custom calls for the Moslems to visit cemeteries and
leaders of the uprising called on their followers to visit the
graves of Arabs slain during the uprising.
   In an unprecedented ruling Sunday, Israel's Supreme Court upheld
an army decision to temporarily occupy a Palestinian home so
soldiers could oversee a highway that has been the scene of
numerous stoning attacks on Israeli vehicles.
   Court spokesman Shmaryahu Cohen said the ruling appeared to be
the first time the court had allowed soldiers to take over an Arab
house for security purposes.
   In the past, the army has confiscated, wrecked or sealed homes
belonging to Palestinians suspected of involvement in anti-Israeli
violence. Army radio said soldiers have wrecked or sealed up 52
Palestinian homes since December.
   The ruling was one of a series of decisions since the uprising
began in which the court has consistently upheld measures of the
Israeli military authorities.
</TEXT>
