<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Yugoslavia-Fires,0141</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Forest Fire in Southern Yugoslavia Brought Under Control</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A blaze that raged for eight days
and destroyed more than 10,000 acres of forests near the
Yugoslav-Greek border has been brought under control, media reports
said Monday.
   The fire occurred in the Valandovo region of Macedonia several
miles north of the frontier with Greece.
   The blaze was started by a farmworker who did not extinguish a
cigarette, a newspaper reported. It eventually was subdued by
thousands of firefighters, soldiers and local inhabitants, with
help from three air force water bombers.
   The intense temperatures from the fire set off explosions in a
World War II minefield, but no one was hurt, reports said.
   Southern Yugoslavia and neighboring Greece have been hit by a
protracted heat wave that has sparked other forest fires.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
