<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 1215EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Military     07-25 0217</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Military,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Sentenced To Six Years For Refusing To Serve In Military</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A white university student who
refused to do cumpulsory military service on the grounds he would
be ``defending racism'' was sentenced Monday to six years in prison.
   Magistrate P.H. Bredenkamp imposed the maximum penalty on David
Bruce for his refusal to undergo the military training required of
all white males in South Africa.
   ``The consequences of your imprisonment are in you own hands,''
Bredenkamp told Bruce, 25. ``You have had the opportunity ... to
provide a useful service to the public.''
   The training involves two years of initial service. Afterward,
men are subject to annual military call-ups that can last as long
as three months.
   ``My view of the South African Defense Force is that it is not a
peace-keeping force but that its basic function is that of
upholding and defending racism,'' Bruce said last week at his trial.
   Bruce declined to request a non-combat posting, which sometimes
is granted to men who object to military training on religious
grounds. Bruce refused to serve for moral and political reasons,
saying he strongly opposed the government's apartheid policies of
racial segregation.
   The government does not release statistics on how many white men
refuse to serve in the military.
</TEXT>
