<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 1225EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Prices     07-25 0548</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Prices,0564</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Boosts Cigarette, Liquor Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Monday announced sharp price
increases for cigarettes and liquor, but also said
inflation-battered consumers will be spared further increases this
year.
   Yuan Mu, spokesman for the State Council, or cabinet, said the
prices of famous brand cigarettes and spirits will be allowed to
float as of Tuesday, putting an end to government-fixed, and
generally arbitrarily low, prices.
   Yuan said the State Council had decided not to carry out any
other price reforms this year to curb inflation, which has been
rising at an alarming rate since the beginning of 1988, the
official Xinhua News Agency reported.
   The State Statistics Bureau said last week that consumer prices
in June were 19 percent higher than in the same month in 1987,
compared to an inflation rate of 7.2 percent for all of last year.
   The government earlier this year raised the prices of eggs,
vegetables, pork and sugar as part of reforms aimed at ending state
controls over prices and allowing the value of goods to be
determined by market forces.
   The elimination of government controls has caused the prices of
some goods to soar as the inefficient economy fails to keep up with
rising demand. Black market dealings and hoarding of goods still
sold at government-set prices have also boosted prices.
   Xinhua quoted Li Changbi, an official of the State
Administration of Commodity Prices, as saying the prices of famous
brand cigarettes could go up between 15 and 290 percent after they
are allowed to fluctuate.
   Li said the price for a bottle of ``Maotai,'' China's most
famous and sought-after spirit, will jump from $5.40 to $32.40.
   Yuan said the price increases for choice cigarettes and wines
will have little social impact ``because most buyers are government
organizations and those individuals with high incomes.''
   But Li said the price of B-grade cigarettes will also be boosted
by 13.4 percent and all alcohol made from grain will go up in price
by 20 percent.
   China uses 14 million tons of grain a year to make beer and
other alcohol, and the government has said this is a luxury the
nation can't afford when it is struggling to produce enough grain
just to keep its 1 billion people fed.
   Communist Party General Secretary Zhao Ziyang and other
reform-minded leaders in recent months have emphasized that price
reform is risky but inevitable if China is to modernize its economy
and end the heavy financial burden of price subsidizing.
   The government has put off decontrolling prices, partly because
of mounting public discontent over the rising cost of living.
   The Politburo, the party's supreme decision-making body,
announced in June that systematic plans for price reform were being
drawn up. Senior officials said the program would take three to
five years to carry out.
   Yuan said price adjustments will resume Jan. 1, 1989, when
newspapers, which have been hit by jumps in the price of newsprint,
will cost more. He did not say what the increase would be.
   Yuan said the rise in the cost of cigarettes should curb
speculation and profiteering that has thrived under the current
pricing system.
   China is the world's biggest cigarette producer and consumer,
turning out 228 billion cigarettes a year for its 300 million
smokers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
