<DOCNO> AP880725-0085 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 1226EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Burma 1stLd-Writethru   07-25 0701</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burma, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0479,0722</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Delegate Says Ne Win Resignation Accepted</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with party delegate saying
congress accepted Ne Win's resignation but rejected his call for
referendum on one-party rule. Pick up 2nd pvs, The three-day...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A special ruling party congress today
accepted the resignation of strongman Ne Win but rejected his call
for a referendum that could have ended 26 years of one-party rule,
a congress delegate said.
   Official Rangoon Radio, however, said only that Ne Win's
resignation had been debated by the delegates and did not indicate
what action, if any, was reached.
   The delegate, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
ruling Burma Socialist Program Party congress agreed to accept the
resignations of Ne Win as party chief and San Yu as the vice
chairman, but to retain them as ``inactive members.''
   Burmese analysts suggested that the vagueness of the official
radio broadcast reflected divisions within party ranks.
   The broadcast said the 1,061 party delegates empowered the
party's central committee to evaluate a sweeping proposal for
economic reform. But it gave no indication of whether any of the
new measures had been accepted.
   The three-day congress of the ruling Burma Socialist Program
Party has been considering dramatic changes in a state-controlled
economic system that turned a potentially prosperous country into a
debt-ridden, poverty-stricken nation.
   The key architect of the system, Ne Win, tendered his
resignation Saturday as chairman of the party and offered to remove
himself from political life. Five other top leaders likewise
submitted resignations.
   State Radio announced Sunday that an emergency session of
Parliament would convene Wednesday, apparently to act on Ne Win's
proposal of holding a referendum on whether Burma should scrap a
quarter century of one-party rule in favor of a multi-party system.
   The emergency session could also deal with the appointment of
new government leaders to replace the five who are resigning. The
five, including President San Yu, held government posts in addition
to their party positions.
   Prime Minister Maung Maung Kha, one of the few top leaders not
on the resignation roll, was expected to be named today to replace
the 77-year-old Ne Win as chairman of the ruling party.
   The sudden and generally unexpected changes come in wake of
bloody anti-government riots and worsening economic conditions in
the isolationist Southeast Asian nation.
   The official radio, broadcasting from the congress, carried
speeches of several among the more than 1,000 delegates asking Ne
Win to reconsider his retirement ``until success has been
achieved.''
   Indeed, some Western diplomats doubt that Ne Win _ who has held
undisputed power for 26 years _ will desist from interference in
the future party and the organization of the new government.
   Not only did the former military chief, who seized power in a
1962 coup, crush anti-government opposition that occasionally
flared. He also moved against leaders within his own ranks when
they exhibited too much promise and independence.
   This has left a leadership vacuum in Rangoon that may prove
difficult to fill if there is a wholesale removal of officials from
party and government ranks, as Ne Win indicated.
   Maung Maung Kha, who assumed the prime ministership in 1977, has
to date not exhibited any particular dynamism or vision that would
be necessary to implement the wide-ranging reforms being debated by
the congress.
   In a speech on Sunday, party general secretary Aye Ko admitted
that economic production had declined, working skills have
deteriorated and ``losses and wastages cannot be controlled
effectively.''
   ``Because of these weaknesses and as a result of adverse
repercussions from the world economic conditions today, the state
economic situation is declining,'' he said.
   Aye Ko called for cutting most state involvement in agriculture,
mining, fisheries, industry, transportation and other economic
sectors.
   He also called for allowing private joint ventures between
Burmese entrepreneurs and foreign investors, something Ne Win
outlawed shortly after seizing power.
   Since October, student-led demonstrations have erupted three
times in Rangoon and the unrest spread to other cities.
   Martial law continues in Prome, 180 miles north of the capital,
where there were riots last week.
   Last month, at least 50 people died in anti-government unrest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
