<DOCNO> AP880725-0087 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 1243EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Poll-SpaceProgram Bjt   07-25 0713</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poll-Space Program, Bjt,0726</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poll Finds Americans Favor Space Station, Mars Landing</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans believe the United States has lost its
edge in space exploration and favor initiatives including a U.S.
space station and manned flights to Mars, a Media
General-Associated Press poll has found.
   A sizable share of the respondents in the national poll said the
United States was doing too little in space exploration. As well as
backing new efforts, a majority expressed support for the space
shuttle program.
   NASA plans to resume shuttle launches in September, more than 2{
years after the shuttle Challenger exploded during takeoff, killing
the seven astronauts aboard. However, equipment problems may delay
the launch.
   Nearly half of the 1,223 adults surveyed said the shuttle
explosion had shaken their confidence in NASA, and 60 percent of
that group said their faith in the space agency has not been
restored.
   That means that about 30 percent of all respondents lacked
confidence in NASA. Still, when asked to rate its overall
effectiveness, 58 percent said it has done a good or excellent job
while 37 percent said only fair or poor.
   About half the respondents said NASA's budget should remain the
same, and 30 percent said it should be increased. Despite concerns
over the federal deficit, only 18 percent said the space budget
should be decreased. And of those who wanted NASA's budget
increased, 74 percent said they would be willing to pay higher
taxes to accomplish it.
   In another indication of general support for space projects, 40
percent said the nation was doing too little in exploring space and
36 percent said it was doing about enough. Just about a fifth said
the United States was doing too much in space exploration.
   There was a striking split between the sexes, with men far more
likely than women to favor space programs. Fifty-six percent of men
said the United States was doing too little in space exploration;
only a quarter of women agreed. Forty-one percent of men supported
increasing the space exploration budget, compared to just 19
percent of women.
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration was created by
Congress 30 years ago to pursue civilian exploration of space, but
in recent years it increasingly has handled military payloads as
well. That was opposed by a slim plurality in the survey:
Forty-eight percent said NASA should be involved in non-military
projects only, while 41 percent approved including military work.
The split was narrowly outside the poll's margin of error of plus
or minus three percentage points.
   Fewer than a quarter of respondents said the United States is
ahead of the Soviet Union in space exploration, while the remainder
were split on whether the Soviets are ahead or the two countries
are about even.
   At the same time, there was sentiment for superpower cooperation
in space. About half of those polled favored last month's proposal
by the Soviets for a U.S.-Soviet joint effort to send astronauts to
Mars.
   An additional 15 percent said the United States should work
alone to reach Mars. Taken together, 64 percent favored some
program to land astronauts on Mars, while 30 percent were opposed.
The rest had no opinion.
   NASA has no program to send astronauts to Mars. It is seeking
funding for a space station, but the $200 million approved by the
Senate this month is only enough to phase out the program or put it
on hold. The House had approved $700 million and a joint committee
is to resolve the issue.
   The goal of a space station was supported by 55 percent, with 34
percent opposed.
   On the soon-to-be resumed space shuttle program, 40 percent said
efforts should be expanded and the same number said work should
continue at the same level. Fewer than a fifth said the shuttle
program should be cut back.
   The Media General-AP poll consisted of telephone interviews June
22-July 2 with a randomly selected sample of 1,223 adults across
the nation. Media General Inc., a communications company based in
Richmond, Va., publishes the Richmond Times-Dispatch, the Richmond
News Leader, the Tampa (Fla). Tribune and the Winston-Salem (N.C.)
Journal, and operates TV stations WXFL in Tampa, WCBD in
Charleston, S.C., and WJKS in Jacksonville, Fla.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
