<DOCNO> AP880725-0088 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 1244EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PollMethod     07-25 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poll Method,0595</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Poll-Space Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This Media General-Associated Press poll is
based on telephone interviews June 22-July 2 with 1,223 adults in
the continental United States. The phone numbers were selected
randomly by computer and interviews were conducted with the adult
in each household who had the most recent birthday.
   The results were weighted to adjust for variations in the
sample. The poll has a three-point margin of error, meaning that if
every adult American were asked the same questions, the results
theoretically would be within three points of the poll's results,
19 times out of 20. The error margin is larger for subgroups _ five
points, for example, for those who want the budget for space
exploration to be increased.
   There are other sources of potential error in polls, including
the wording and order of questions. These are the questions and
responses in this poll; because of rounding, some totals may exceed
100:
   1. In general, do you think the United States is doing too much
in space exploration right now, or too little, or about enough?
   Too much: 19 percent. Too little: 40 percent. About enough: 36
percent. Don't know or no answer: 5 percent.
   2. Do you think the space shuttle program should be expanded,
cut back, or kept at the same level?
   Expanded: 40 percent. Cut back: 17 percent. Same level: 40
percent. DK-NA: 3 percent.
   3. Do you think the United States should build a space station,
or not?
   Yes: 55 percent. No: 34 percent. DK-NA: 12 percent.
   4. The Soviet Union has suggested a joint program with the
United States to land astronauts on Mars. Do you think the United
States should try to land astronauts on Mars by itself, or should
it undertake a joint program with the Soviets, or should the United
States not try to land astronauts on Mars at all?
   By itself: 15 percent. Joint program: 49 percent. Not at all: 30
percent. DK-NA: 7 percent.
   5. Do you think the U.S. government's budget for the overall
space program should be increased, decreased, or kept at the same
level?
   Increased: 30 percent. Decreased: 18 percent. Same level: 48
percent. DK-NA: 5 percent.
   a. If increased: Would you be willing to pay higher taxes for
the increase?
   Yes: 74 percent. No: 20 percent. DK-NA: 6 percent.
   6. Who do you think is ahead in the exploration of space _ the
United States or the Soviet Union, or do you think they are about
equal?
   U.S.: 23 percent. Soviets: 31 percent. Even: 37 percent. DK-NA:
20 percent.
   7. How would you rate the overall effectiveness of the National
Aeronautic and Space Administration, known as NASA _ excellent,
good, only fair or poor?
   Excellent: 10 percent. Good: 45 percent. Only fair: 30 percent.
Poor: 7 percent. DK-NA: 8 percent.
   8. Do you think NASA should be involved in military and
non-military projects in space, or should it be involved only in
non-military projects?
   Both: 41 percent. Only non-military: 48 percent. DK-NA: 11
percent.
   9. The space shuttle program was set back when the shuttle
Challenger exploded in 1986, killing the seven astronauts aboard.
Looking back, did that accident shake your confidence in NASA, or
not?
   Yes: 47 percent. No: 50 percent. DK-NA: 3 percent.
   11. If yes: How about now _ has your confidence in NASA been
restored, or not?
   Yes: 34 percent. No: 60 percent. DK-NA: 6 percent.
</TEXT>
