<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 1257EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Hastings     07-25 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hastings,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Wants Delay On Impeachment Vote</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys for U.S. District Judge Alcee
Hastings have asked for a delay in Tuesday's scheduled vote by the
House Judiciary Committee on an impeachment recommendation,
contending the panel is rushing to a decision on a
precedent-setting issue.
   ``We can't see any need for what seems to us an unseemly
haste,'' said Terence Anderson, one of Hastings' attorneys, on
Monday.
   A committee staff member said the request for a delay had been
received, but that no decision had been made and the vote was still
scheduled for 10 a.m. Tuesday.
   Hastings, the first black appointed to the federal bench in
Florida, was acquitted in 1983 of bribery charges. But the House
Judiciary criminal justice subcommittee has recommended that he be
impeached on 17 counts of official misconduct, including some
relating to the bribery case.
   The full committee was scheduled to act on the recommendation
Tuesday.
   Anderson contrasted the handling of his client's case with that
of U.S. District Judge Walter Nixon of Mississippi. In Nixon's
case, the subcommittee heard direct evidence from three key
witnesses at his trial, which ended in a conviction for lying to a
grand jury.
   The House Subcommittee on Civil and Constitutional Rights
brought impeachment charges against Nixon, which still are pending
in Congress.
   But in Hastings' case, the panel relied on second-hand testimony
of prosecutor John Doar, even though Hastings was acquitted of the
charges by the trial jury, he said.
   Anderson also said the printed record of the subcommittee's
proceedings had not yet been printed and distributed to members.
   ``We're saying, `It's just plain unseemly for you to be trying
to decide this before you give members an opportunity to study the
record,''' he said.
   If the Judiciary Committee votes to draft misconduct charges,
the full House is expected to vote on impeachment before it
recesses Aug. 11.
   Hastings was acquitted in 1983 of conspiring with Washington
attorney William A. Borders Jr. for $150,000 in bribes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
