<DOCNO> AP880725-0092 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 1334EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Women     07-25 0256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Women,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Issues Regulations to Protect Women Workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China on Monday issued regulations forbidding job
discrimination against women and guaranteeing them healthy work
environments.
   The State Council, or Cabinet, also said employers cannot reduce
the wages or annul women's contracts during periods of pregnancy,
maternity leave or nursing.
   The regulations, to go into effect Sept. 1, extended maternity
leave from 56 to 90 days, and stipulate that women who have
difficult deliveries will have an option of another 15 days.
   China's constitution guarantees equality between the sexes, but
in reality Chinese women face various kinds of educational and job
discrimination.
   Women university graduates have much more difficulty finding
suitable jobs than men, women's wages are often lower, and factory
managers with newly won powers to dismiss workers have fired women
in larger numbers than men.
   In the countryside, many girls are forced by custom and parents
to quit school even before completing the compulsory nine years so
they can work in the fields or in factories.
   Women frequently also work in small and often unsafe mines,
although past laws, and the State Council regulations, state that
women are not allowed to engage in underground mining or heavy
labor unsuited to the individual's health.
   The regulations urge employers with a large staff of women to
provide appropriate sanitary equipment, rooms for pregnant women to
rest, and nurseries and kindergartens.
   Xinhua said, without providing details, that violators of the
regulations or those who infringe on the rights of women workers
will be punished.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880725-0093 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 1330EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SwingingBritain Bjt   07-25 0624</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Swinging Britain, Bjt,0638</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>In The '80s, England Still Swings Like the '60s</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If you thought the '60s were swinging, just look
at the '80s.
   According to a statistical study published Monday, the sexual
permissiveness associated with the 1960s is tame stuff compared
with the 1980s _AIDS and yuppie puritanism notwithstanding.
   The ``Swinging '60s'' were invented largely by British pop
musicians, fashion designers and hairstylists, so it was
appropriate that the study came from a British independent research
office, the Family Policy Studies Center.
   It reported that the divorce rate has jumped from 2.1 per 1,000
marriages in 1961 to 12.9 in 1986; illegitimate births are up from
6 percent to 21 percent; births are down from 17.9 per 1,000 to
13.3; and teen-age brides are down from 28 percent to 14 percent.
   It says that between 1960 and 1964, only one in 100 first-time
brides under age 25 lived with their partners before marrying them.
Twenty years later, the figure is almost one in four, the study
says.
   Figures for bridegrooms do not appear in the government
statistics used in the study, according to its editor, Melanie
Henwood.
   The report says the figures suggest a much more liberal attitude
in the 1980s toward childbirth out of wedlock.
   Not only has illegitimacy more than trebled, but the mothers
apparently feel much less compulsion to marry before giving birth,
while the fathers are more likely to acknowledge paternity.
   The study said 38 percent of birth certificates for illegitimate
children bore the names of both parents in 1961. In 1986, the
figure had risen to 66 percent, it said.
   ``The paradox of the 1960s may be less of a puzzle than it first
appears,'' the report concludes. ``It is, after all, the people who
grew up in, or were living through, the 1960s who are now making
their appearance in many of the cohabitation, illegitimacy,
marriage and divorce statistics. The class of '68 has come of age.''
   ``The swinging '60s do seem a bit of mythical when we look at
the facts and figures, but it really depends on the image of
'60s,'' Ms. Henwood said in an interview.
   At 30, she admits to having no firsthand experience of the
``Swinging '60s,'' but knows they were ``a period of great change _
music, clothing and politics ... We look back and assume it was a
time of free love, communes, that sort of thing. In fact, what made
the image was a few notorious figures living in permissive
relationships, but their values were not shared by most people at
the time.''
   The Times of London asked some leading figures of the '60s what
they thought of the study.
   ``The `Swinging '60s' took their name from the music, not the
morality,'' said actor Terence Stamp, who made his name playing the
title role in the 1962 film version of ``Billy Budd.''
   ``Compare Michael Jackson to Elvis Presley, Prince to Jimi
Hendrix and the Pet Shop Boys to the Beatles. There you have the
essential difference between the '60s and the '80s,'' Stamp was
quoted as saying.
   Jean Shrimpton, the model who made the miniskirt famous, was
quoted as saying: ``I never had a swinging mentality. I wore short
skirts but I was a commodity of the '60s. It was other people who
were making things happen. I just happened to be there.''
   And cartoonist Ralph Steadman was quoted as saying: ``The
permissive society was about lots of things, not just sex. We were
willing to buck authority ... Now life is getting more and more
standardized and barren, and there is a backlash spurred by AIDS, a
reformist influence which does rather tend to concentrate the
mind.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
