<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Vietnam-US     07-25 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vietnam-US,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Talks Begin on Accounting For Missing American Servicemen</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Cambodia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Vietnamese officials opened
talks Monday on accounting for 1,761 American servicemen still
missing from the Vietnam War, an American official said Monday.
   The official, who asked not to be identified, said he had no
details on the talks, being held in Vietnam's capital of Hanoi and
expected to last four days.
   Vietnam on July 13 returned 25 remains it identified as those of
U.S. servicemen killed in the war. Hanoi also handed over a list of
names and ``associations'' relating to the remains. Some of the
names appear on the official list of 1,761 Americans who remain
missing in action from the war.
   The turnover was the fifth since retired Gen. John W. Vessey,
acting as a special presidential envoy, reached an agreement in
Hanoi a year ago under which Vietnam would accelerate the search
for remains, especially several dozen on Washington's top priority
list.
   This week's talks were agreed upon during a meeting at the
Untied Nations on June 8 between Vessey and Vietnamese Foreign
Minister Nguyen Co Thach.
   The U.S. technical team was led by Lt. Col. Joe Harvey of the
U.S. Embassy's Joint Casualty Resolution Center and joined by
representatives from the U.S. Army Central Identification
Laboratory based in Hawaii, the official said.
   ``We look forward to the results of the July 25-28 meeting
between technical representatives. We hope progress can be made
quickly on resolving this longstanding problem of concern to the
POW-MIA families of U.S and American people,'' the official quoted
U.S. State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley as saying Thursday
in Washington.
   Since the war ended, Vietnam has returned more than 150 sets of
remains that the army laboratory has confirmed as Americans.
Vietnam says it has returned the remains of 241 missing Americans
and information on 45 others whose remains were ``determined to be
no longer in existence.''
</TEXT>
