<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-PlantClosing     07-25 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Plant Closing,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan To Consult Republicans On Plant Closing Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said
Monday that while it's likely President Reagan will veto Congress'
latest attempt to require employers to give workers advance notice
of layoffs or plant shutdowns, `it's always open until it's done.''
   Fitzwater told reporters the bill, which passed both the House
and Senate earlier this month by veto-proof margins, had arrived at
the White House, and that Reagan has until Aug. 3 to make a
decision.
   The spokesman said the issue was likely to be raised at a
meeting Reagan will hold Tuesday with Republican congressional
leaders, but he disputed suggestions that GOP lawmakers will urge
the president to sign the bill.
   ``I would say there are number of them who will recommend a
veto,'' Fitzwater said.
   Last week, White House chief of staff Kenneth Duberstein told
reporters in Santa Barbara, Calif. that a Reagan veto was likely.
Meanwhile, the administration's stand on the issue was repeatedly
assailed by Democrats at their national convention in Atlanta.
   Duberstein said ``our longstanding position has been that it is
unacceptable to the president, that he has signaled veto, he has
vetoed it once already as part of another bill and I would suspect
that position will be maintained.''
   But during the daily White House news briefing Monday, Fitzwater
left the door slightly ajar.
   ``Duberstein said it was likely or most likely that he would
veto it,'' the spokesman said. ``I have said that from this podium.
That certainly is the case, but it's always open until it's done.''
   ``There are some congressional leaders who would like to give us
the benefits of their advice and this is an opportunity for them to
do it,'' Fitzwater said.
   A provision requiring private industry to give workers 60 days
advance notice of plant closings was contained in legislation
Congress passed earlier this year overhauling the nation's trade
laws.
   Reagan vetoed the bill, saying he didn't want the government
legislating restrictions on the ability of company executives to
make critical decisions. Reagan said the matter of worker
notification should be left to employers and employees to work out
separately.
   Vice President George Bush, certain to get the Republican
nomination for president in New Orleans next month, has stated
sentiments similar to Reagan's on the issue, although there have
been reports the Bush campaign would prefer to see the president
let the bill become law.
   Fitzwater said Monday he didn't know anything about whether the
Bush campaign was arguing a case for the signing of the
plant-closing bill.
</TEXT>
