<2ND_LINE>AM-Genie Project,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Genie Project Lawsuit Ends With Settlement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The founders of a charity that grants
dying children their last wishes have agreed to pay a $50,000 fine
and disband to settle accusations they misused donations for
personal loans, excessive salaries and rental on an X-rated movie.
   Genie Project founders Michael and Suzanne Bates also were
accused of using the charity's money to lease a Cadillac and to pay
rent on their home.
   State Attorney General Joseph I. Lieberman announced a
settlement Monday under which the Bateses admitted no wrongdoing
and agreed never to hold any office or directorship in a
Connecticut charity.
   The agreement was in the form of a judgment in Waterbury
Superior Court entered July 7, and final notice was received last
week at the attorney general's office, Lieberman said. A lawsuit
filed Sept. 12, 1985, accused the couple of violating state charity
laws.
   The charity raised $237,000 in 1984 and was accused of spending
only $10,000 on dying children that year.
   Michael Bates has paid $18,259 to the state Consumer Protection
Department and $5,298 has been seized from various banks,
Lieberman's office said. Suzanne Bates will pay $24,259 to the
state over 122 months and $5,000 worth of computer equipment will
be turned over to the department.
   The Bateses also were put on probation for two years in a
criminal case. They had been charged with providing false
information to the consumer department.
   The Bateses, who are divorced, couldn't be reached for comment.
There is no telephone listing for either, and their attorney wasn't
in his office Monday morning, his secretary said.
</TEXT>
