<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Tibet     07-25 0203</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Tibet,0209</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Graduates of Tibet University</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tibet's only comprehensive institute of higher
learning on Friday awarded diplomas to the remote mountain region's
first university graduates, it was reported Monday.
   The official Xinhua News Agency said 246 students graduated from
Tibet University, with 74 receiving bachelor's degrees in
literature, law and philosophy.
   The university, located in the Tibetan capital of Lhasa, was
established in 1985 as Tibet's first full university. The region
also has a teacher's college.
   The university's 778 students are enrolled in eight departments,
and 14 of its 17 professors and associate professors are of Tibetan
nationality, Xinhua said.
   The Beijing government has tried to aid Tibet, one of China's
most impoverished and least developed areas, by building schools,
hospitals and roads and providing funds for industry.
   Relations between Tibetans and non-Tibetan Chinese remain
strained by a long history of confrontations climaxing in the
1966-76 Cultural Revolution, when leftists persecuted many Tibetans
and tried to suppress Tibetan religion and language.
   Last fall and again in March crowds led by Buddhist monks staged
anti-Chinese, pro-independence riots, but Beijing insists they
represented a small minority of Tibetans and that the lives of
Tibetans have improved markedly under communist rule.
