<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 1349EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-WorldBank     07-25 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-World Bank,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Volcker Says World Bank May Wither Away Unless U.S. Contributes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The World Bank may wither away as the biggest
source of aid to the Third World unless Congress acts soon to
pledge a new contribution, Paul A. Volcker, former head of the
Federal Reserve Board, warned on Monday.
   The bank, headed by Barber B. Conable, a former congressman from
New York, wants a U.S. pledge of $70.1 million a year over the next
six years for an increase in its capital.
   So far, 140 of the 151 governments that own the bank have
decided to contribute. Among the other countries that have not made
a pledge are Algeria, Cambodia, Vietnam and South Yemen.
   President Reagan has urged approval of the contribution. It has
been held up in Congress by disagreement over what should be done
to handle the bulk of the Third World's $1.2 trillion debt.
   Last year the bank got back more in repayments and interest from
Third World borrowers than it gave them in new loans. Bank
officials want to reverse that trend and increase lending to well
over $20 billion a year in the early 1990s.
   ``Our influence and leadership within the bank are certainly at
stake, and I would raise the question ... if the United States is
not going to participate in capital increases ... whether the bank
itself can survive over a long period of time,'' Volcker told a
news conference.
   He added that the bank could continue lending for a year or two
without new capital. The United States, as the biggest shareholder,
is expected to furnish more than 18 percent.
   ``But against the prospect of not getting their capital
replenished, it is not in the nature of the beast and would not be
responsible for them to continue lending at that rate of speed in
the face of a vote of no-confidence by their major shareholders,''
said Volcker, who left the Fed last year.
   A contribution has been endorsed by former presidents Carter,
Ford and Nixon. Last week they were joined by nine former
secretaries of the treasury.
   A group of supporters, the Bretton Woods Committee, is seeking
statements of backing from the major presidential candidates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880725-0102 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 1401EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Ireland Bjt   07-25 0708</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ireland, Bjt,0725</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IRA Man Murdered as Cardinal Preaches in Belfast</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY16</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Men dressed as policemen killed
an IRA man Monday while Cardinal John O'Connor of New York
delivered a sermon a mile away in which he implored Americans not
to romanticize Irish violence.
   Brendan Davidson, a member of Sinn Fein, the outlawed Irish
Republican Army's legal political wing, was shot in the head after
answering a knock on his door, police said.
   Davidson, 33, belonged to the Sinn Fein, the outlawed Irish
Republican Army's legal political wing. An IRA statement issued in
Belfast said he was one of its members.
   He was shot down 48 hours after an IRA bomb killed a Protestant
couple and their 6-year-old son, who had just driven across the
border from the Irish Republic.
   The IRA took responsibility but said the attack was on the wrong
target. Press reports suggested the intended victim may have been a
judge who drove past shortly afterward.
   O'Connor learned of Davidson's death after leaving Belfast to
deliver a sermon in Armagh.
   He said the killing, and Saturday's bombing, ``poignantly
brought into focus the stupidity, the irrationality of the cycle of
the violence. ... Where can this conceivably end? How this can
conceivably please almighty God?''
   Authorities said three men wearing police uniforms killed
Davidson and escaped in a red car.
   Sinn Fein said it did not believe policemen committed the crime,
but that the assailants could have had help from sympathizers in
the Royal Ulster Constabulary, the mainly Protestant police force
in the British province.
   When Davidson was shot on Friendly Street, the cardinal was at
St. Peter's Cathedral in the heart of Roman Catholic West Belfast,
deploring ``some on our own shores, some in my own country, who
romanticize violence when it is several thousand miles away, who
don't know what it does to a land, who don't know the insecurity
that it brings, who don't know how it keeps a people oppressed.''
   O'Connor, who is leading 300 Americans on a pilgrimage to pray
for peace in Ireland, returned to that theme at Armagh, in the
south of the province.
   Addressing an ecumenical congregation at St. Patrick's
Cathedral, he again denounced Americans who ``continue to
perpetuate the myth that this violence reflects the glory of
Ireland, that we can stand around pianos ad sing sentimental songs
and believe that what occurs today is in the tradition of the
martyrs and the saints.''
   The bombing Saturday was the fifth admitted blunder by the IRA
that has killed or wounded innocent civilians since November, when
11 Protestants at a war memorial ceremony were killed by a bomb
intended for British soldiers.
   At least 2,660 people have been killed since political and
sectarian warfare began in Northern Ireland in August 1969,
including 44 so far this year. The IRA wants to drive the British
from Northern Ireland and unite it with the predominantly Catholic
republic.
   ``The terrorism has got to be deplored on either side,'' Mayor
Edward I. Koch of New York, who is on the pilgrimage, told
reporters in Armagh. ``No one believes that, because the cardinal
and 300 pilgrims came from New York, that we were going to be
stopping terrorism. In fact the acts of terrorism underscore the
need for prayer.''
   Tom King, Britain's Northern Ireland secretary, said: ``Every
murder is an atrocity, and just this weekend we've had a
particularly awful atrocity committed by the IRA, and the trouble
is, once one is committed, then somebody on the other extreme feels
the need to strike back.''
   He met with O'Connor and Koch separately and praised their
``intelligent and constructive interest,'' compared with what he
called the ``nonsense talked in America'' and ``ignorance of the
true situation in Northern Ireland.''
   O'Connor toured Divis Flats, the high-rise homes of some of
Belfast's most impoverished Catholics, on Sunday and urged American
investors to bring business and jobs to the area.
   He said he looked across the geographical divisions of the city,
which are based on religion, and ``I asked myself: Good Lord, where
is the rationale in this? How can we purport to be made in the
image and likeness of almighty God?''
</TEXT>
