<DOCNO> AP880725-0103 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 1403EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--China-Execution     07-25 0181</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--China-Execution,0187</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Executed for Taking Bribes for Color TV</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man was executed Monday after being convicted
of taking bribes from companies speculating in much-coveted color
television sets, according to an official report.
   The Xinhua News Agency said Qiao Yonghong was executed for
receiving about $32,400 to help work units obtain color TVs.
   Qiao, an employee of the Beijing Communications and Electrical
Company, in one instance was given the equivalent of $10,800 for
selling 200 color TVs to a company.
   The demand for color TVs far exceeds supply, and profiteers able
to obtain sets can sell them on the black market for far more than
government-set retail prices.
   Qiao, 35, was arrested in September 1985 and sentenced to death
in March 1987. He appealed the verdict, but the Beijing Higher
People's Court last month upheld the lower court's ruling.
   The government has called for police and courts to deal harshly
with the rising number of economic criminals such as speculators,
profiteers and embezzlers.
   Execution in China is usually by bullet to the back of the head.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
