<HEAD>Polish Primate to Make Second Visit to Soviet Union</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardinal Jozef Glemp announced Monday he
plans to visit the Soviet republic of Byelorussia, his second trip
to the Soviet Union this year.
   Glemp, leader of Poland's Roman Catholic Church, gave no date
for the visit, but said it would be at the invitation of Russian
Orthodox Metropolitan Filaret.
   He said he also planned to invite Filaret to Warsaw.
   The primate was interviewed by state-run television upon
returning to Poland after a three-week visit to Rome, where he met
with Polish-born Pope John Paul II.
   Glemp visited Moscow in June during observances of the 1,000th
anniversary of Christianity in Russia.
   Roman Catholicism and Orthodoxy competed for centuries in the
territory of the Byelorussion republic, much of which belonged to
Poland before World War II.
   Polish church sources have estimated there are 1 million to 2
million Soviet citizens of Polish-Catholic origins in Lithuania,
Byelorussia and the Ukraine.
