<1ST_LINE>r i AM-HurricaneDay     07-25 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hurricane Day,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Virgin Islanders Observe Hurricane Supplication Day</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. CROIX, U.S. Virgin Islands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most of the Virgin
Island's 11,000 public employees took the day off Monday for
Hurricane Supplication Day, the day residents pray they won't get
hit by a hurricane.
   Hurricane Supplication Day, which marks the traditional start of
the hurricane season for the Caribbean island group, is one of 25
holidays Virgin Islanders observe each year.
   Another is Hurricane Thanksgiving Day, on Oct. 17, traditionally
the last day of the hurricane season and a day set aside for giving
thanks for sparing the U.S. territory from the storms.
   Even though the islands' civil defense service recognizes the
Atlantic hurricane season, which runs from June 30 to Nov. 30,
islanders still observe the traditional hurricane holidays.
   All government offices except for essential services such as
hospitals and the police and fire departments were closed on the
three islands of St. Croix, St. Thomas and St. John's.
   Banks and stores stayed open, however, and most people went
about their business as usual.
   Although the religious significance of the holiday is sometimes
lost, Holy Cross Roman Catholic Church in Christiansted held two
hurricane supplication services Monday. ``We had a lot of people at
the second one,'' a receptionist said.
   Elroy Harrison, coordinator of the Virgin Islands Territorial
Emergency Management Agency, said the islands have not been hit by
a major hurricane since the 1950s.
</TEXT>
