<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 1438EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Cambodia     07-25 0620</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cambodia ,0638</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cambodian Factions Meet For First Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOR, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cambodia's warring parties held peace
talks Monday for the first time, but they apparently made no
progress on negotiating an end to the country's civil war.
   The two central problems to be tackled are the future of the
communist Khmer Rouge guerrillas and organizing elections for a new
Cambodian government.
   ``Although we have not solved any concrete problems, each side
has revealed its position to the other side,`` said Cambodian Prime
Minister Hun Sen after talks with the three guerrilla groups, which
oppose his Vietnamese-installed government.
   The four Cambodian leaders gathered in the summer palace of the
late President Sukarno in Bogor, a mountain retreat 37 miles
outside Jakarta, for the so-called ``cocktail party'' of the
factions.
   ``This is a very preliminary stage,'' said Indonesia's Foreign
Minister Ali Alatas, who organized the meeting.
   On Monday, Hun Sen met with guerrilla leaders Khieu Samthan of
the communist Khmer Rouge, Son Sann of the Khmer People's National
Liberaton Front and Prince Norodom Ranariddh, who represented his
father Prince Norodom Sihanouk.
   The four later were joined by representatives of Vietnam, its
close ally Laos and the foreign ministers of the Association of
Southeast Asia Nations _ Thailand, Indonesia, Malaysia, Singapore,
the Philippines and Brunei _ which is the main backer of the
guerrillas.
   Vietnam, which invaded Cambodia in 1978 and by Western count
maintains more than 100,000 troops there, says it has withdrawn
several thousand soldiers. It has announced it will pull out 50,000
troops this year and the rest by early 1990.
   Hun Sen told reporters he presented a seven-point proposal for a
political settlement in Cambodia. The plan contains mostly
positions that already had been rejected by the guerrillas.
   It calls for maintaining the status-quo in Cambodia until
elections are organized to form a new government. Hun Sen has said
he cannot accept the guerrillas' demand that he dissolve his
government before the elections.
   Instead, he said he proposed forming a ``ntional reconciliation
council'' headed by Sihanouk to implement any peace agreements and
organize the elections.
   Sihanouk resigned July 10 as the president of the guerrilla
coalition because he said the Khmer Rouge were killing his men. He
arrived in Indonesia on Saturday as a guest of President Suharto,
but said he would not attend the Bogor talks.
   The prince is considered the central figure in a settlement and
future government, and Hun Sen said the leaders of all four
factions would meet him in Jakarta in the next few days.
   Hun Sen also demanded the dissolution of the Khmer Rouge, the
largest of the guerrilla forces.
   ``Only by eliminating the Khmer Rouge ... can we eliminate the
possibility of the Pol Pot regime returning to Cambodia,'' Hun Sen
said.
   From 1975 until Vietnam invaded, the fanatical Khmer Rouge
regime of Prime Minister Pol Pot killed hundreds of thousands of
people. Diplomats say the Khmer Rouge is storing arms for attacks
after the Vietnamese troops leave Cambodia.
   The meeting represents the first gathering of the four Cambodian
parties. Hun Sen and Sihanouk held two rounds of unsuccessful talks
since 1987, but Vietnam has never met with the factions of the
Cambodian resistance.
   Asked if he was happy with the talks, Vietnam's delegate,
Foreign Minister Nguyen Co Thach said, ``I am optimistic. I don't
say happy, but optimistic.''
   Three Buddhist monks from the United States, Canada and France
chanted prayers for the success of the talks outside the Dutch
colonial palace where the meetings were held.
   Alatas said the meeting is to continue Tuesday and would last
``as long as it takes.'' The tentative schedule called for two days
of talks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880725-0109 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 1439EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Obit-McClory     07-25 0560</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-McClory,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Illinois Congressman Who Voted for Nixon Impeachment Dies
at 80</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Rep. Robert N. McClory, an Illinois
Republican reluctantly thrust into the national spotlight for his
role in impeachment proceedings against President Richard Nixon, is
dead at age 80.
   McClory, who represented the Chicago suburbs in Congress for 20
years until 1982, collapsed at church Sunday and died a short time
later at George Washington University Hospital, his wife, Doris,
said Monday.
   ``He went out jogging, got a paper and then came back to go with
me to church. Everything was fine,'' Mrs. McClory said. ``Then it
happened. He just collapsed and never came out of it.''
   McClory was the second-ranking Republican on the House Judiciary
Committee during congressional hearings on the break-in at the
Democratic National Committee headquarters in the Watergate complex
in Washington.
   Although he was a GOP loyalist, McClory was one of the leading
House supporters of an article of impeachment in 1974 charging
Nixon with abusing his constitutional powers in the Watergate
matter. He drafted another article charging the president with
contempt of Congress for resisting subpoenas.
   ``I feel really torn,'' McClory said in an interview at the
time. ``But I'm disassociating this job from my relationship with
the president on philosophy and policies.''
   During the impeachment hearings, McClory said he was not
convinced that Nixon was directly involved in the Watergate coverup
but rejected suggestions that he had a partisan obligation to
defend the president against all of the accusations.
   ``I have heard it said by some that they cannot understand how a
Republican could vote to impeach a Republican president,'' he said
in the committee's opening debate on impeachment. ``Let me hasten
to assert that that argument demeans my role here. It would make a
mockery of our entire inquiry.''
   Nixon resigned the presidency after the committee voted three
articles of impeachment.
   Born in Riverside, Ill., McClory graduated from Dartmouth
College and Chicago-Kent School of Law and practiced law in the
Chicago area until 1950 when he was elected to the Illinois House
of Representatives. He served in the state Senate from 1952 to 1962.
   While in Congress, McClory was a House manager of the Equal
Rights Amendment and a sponsor of legislation providing that
federal holidays such as Labor Day and Memorial Day be celebrated
on Monday.
   McClory's congressional district in the northern and western
suburbs of Chicago was eliminated by reapportionment in 1981.
Rather than opposing incumbent Rep. John Porter, also a Republican,
in the expanded 10th District, he chose not to seek re-election in
1982.
   ``He will be best remembered for his leadership during the
Watergate hearings and his abiding commitment to the rule of law,''
Porter said Monday. ``Along with tens of thousands of people from
our area, I share ... a tremendous sense of loss in Bob's passing.''
   McClory had lived in the nation's capital since leaving office
and was a member of the Washington law firm of Baker & McKenzie.
   He is survived by his wife, two sons and a daughter.
   McClory will be buried Friday following a private service in
Illinois, his wife said. She said a public memorial service was
scheduled for 11 a.m. Saturday at the United Methodist Church in
Lake Bluff, Ill., where he had maintained a home since the 1930s.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880725-0110 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 1441EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SpaceShuttle 1stLd-Writethru a0577 07-25 0509</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Space Shuttle, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0577,0518</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Space Shuttle Mock Countdown Hits Snag</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs, shuttle engine test delayed; picks up 8th
graf pvs, `NASA officials...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A practice space shuttle countdown
hit a snag Monday, delaying a critical test-firing of Discovery's
three main engines 24 hours, until Sunday.
   The postponement was announced as engineers assessed methods for
fixing a small shuttle gas leak without having to take Discovery
off the launch pad, a move that could delay the planned early
September launch by as much as two months.
   The launch team started the countdown late Sunday and fell
behind early in closing out the shuttle's rear engine compartment
on the pad. That forced a one-day delay in the loading of gases
aboard the spaceship's energy-producing fuel cells.
   The plan now calls for crews to pump more than half a million
gallons of liquid hydrogen and liquid oxygen into Discovery's
external fuel tank late Wednesday and early Thursday.
   It will mark the first time a shuttle has been fueled since the
fleet was grounded by the Challenger explosion Jan. 28, 1986.
   On Thursday, when the countdown reaches 10 seconds before a mock
liftoff, a simulated problem is to force a postponement. Crews then
will rehearse what they call a 72-hour launch turnaround exercise.
They will empty the fuel tank, start another countdown and aim for
a test-firing of Discovery's main engines at 7:30 a.m. Sunday.
   The 20-second firing, with the shuttle locked firmly on the pad,
will check modifications made to turbopumps and other engine
systems and is considered crucial to Discovery being certified for
the first post-Challenger shuttle flight.
   The launch, with a five-man crew, is scheduled for early
September, but the date is uncertain because of the leak in a
steering engine system that is separate from the main engines.
   NASA officials believe that even if the leak can be fixed on the
pad, the launch will be delayed past the middle of September.
   Experts were considering several ways to reach and plug the
inaccessible leak, from cutting a hole through the shuttle cargo
bay wall to running a snake-like tube 20 feet through the
half-inch-diameter gas line.
   Tests over the weekend ruled out using the tube in two
configurations. One would have used it to deliver an expandable
Teflon balloon filled with sealant to plug the leak. In the other,
sealant would been pumped through a hollow tube to the leak.
   The tube testing is being done at the Materials and Processing
Laboratory at the Marshall Space Flight Center in Huntsville, Ala.
Lab director Bob Schwinghamer said Monday the balloon and hollow
tube approaches proved impractical.
   But he said another approach, in which a badminton-like
shuttlecock is attached to the end of the ``snake,'' showed promise
in reaching the leak.
   ``We have tested it eight times successfully and it looks very
attractive,'' Schwinghamer said. He suggested that if this method
didn't work, NASA then could consider cutting a hole in the cargo
bay.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880725-0111 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 1444EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     07-25 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0496</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAUSALITO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents are ready to greet the
humming toadfish in its yearly mating ritual with a comparable
human sound: They're going to play kazoos.
   Until the humming toadfish was identified as living in
Richardson Bay in 1985, residents were baffled by a strange humming
sound coming from the water.
   The July 31 celebration will include more than 25 environmental
groups, as well as ecological and historical exhibits, lectures and
boat tours _ all in honor of the fish.
   The humming toadfish used to be an irritating puzzle that awoke
Sausalito houseboat residents nightly, beginning toward the end of
July.
   ``The first time it happened, practically everybody in the
houseboats jumped out of bed and looked in their electrical
boxes,'' said Suzanne Simpson, a festival spokeswoman and one of
the many houseboat residents who had no idea what the eerie buzzing
sound was when it first occurred in 1984.
   In their search for mates, the male fish emit the humming noise
and other buzzing sounds through vibrating gas bladders.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Even though the two ``all-star'' softball
teams were playing in the Metrodome home of the Minnesota Twins,
there was no danger of mistaking them for baseball's 1987 world
champions.
   However, the benefit game Sunday between the Democratic Farmer
Labor and Independent Republican teams had some of the trappings of
major league baseball.
   There were at least four inside-the-park home runs and some
spectacular fielding plays during the game won by the IR team,
20-13.
   A pitcher suspected of scuffing the softball was even ejected
for allegedly concealing a huge wad of sandpaper while on the mound
in the manner of Twins pitcher Joe Niekro. Niekro was suspended for
10 days last year after being caught with an emery board and
sandpaper on the mound in Anaheim, Calif.
   The softball game was billed as a benefit between IR
politicians, led by former state Rep. David Jennings, chairman of
George Bush's Minnesota campaign, and DFLers, who were led by
co-captains U.S. Rep. Martin Sabo and state Rep. Phyllis Kahn. Each
group sold about 500 $12 tickets.
   About 400 of the 38,008 fans who attended the Twins-Orioles game
stayed to watch the slapstick game.
   Kahn, the DFL co-captain and starting pitcher, was resplendent
in iridescent purple, pink and green plaid shorts. She had some
trouble controlling her pitches and was replaced in the second
inning after yielding 11 runs.
   ``The most important thing, in politics as well as baseball, is
to know when it's time to move on,'' Kahn said.
   In the fifth inning, with the IRs leading 12-8, Sabo complained
about the IR pitcher, state Rep. Chris Tjornhom, and asked the
umpire to check for illegalities.
   Sabo accompanied the umpire to the mound, where a large piece of
sandpaper fell to the ground next to the pitcher. Tjornhom, looking
indignant, was ejected.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
