<HEAD>Government Introduces Bill To Set Up Federal Child Care Program</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: All dollar figures are U.S.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government introduced legislation
Monday to start implementing a $5.3 billion day care program that
would double the number of spaces across the country to 400,000 in
seven years.
   Conservative Prime Minister Brian Mulroney has said he will give
the bill priority ahead of an anticipated fall election.
   Health Minister Jake Epp promised the legislation in December
and is negotiating with Canada's 10 provincial governments to share
program costs.
   The bill introduced Monday would create a $3.3 billion fund to
help the provinces set up 200,000 new day care spaces by 1995.
Separate legislation will give tax breaks to all working parents
who enroll their children in day care facilities.
