<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 1458EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Burma     07-25 0657</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma,0679</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delegate Says Burmese Leader's Resignation Accepted</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burma's ruling political party on Monday
accepted the resignation of strongman Ne Win after 26 years as head
of the party, but opposed his call for a referendum on ending
one-party rule, a delegate said.
   At the final session of a three-day congress, the ruling Burma
Socialist Program Party also considered sweeping economic reforms
designed to cure the country's deepening economic woes.
   The 77-year-old Ne Win, who came to power in a 1962 military
coup, announced abruptly Saturday he was resigning. He cited bloody
anti-government rioting in March and June and his age as key
factors in his decision.
   Ne Win has been blamed for leading Burma into economic disaster
during 26 years of isolationist policies.
   Five veteran party leaders also submitted their resignations
Saturday.
   The party delegate, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
the 1,061 delegates at the congress voted to accept Ne Win's
resignation and that of party vice chairman San Yu, also the
country's president, but to retain them as ``inactive members.''
   Official Radio Rangoon did not announce the decision,
broadcasting only remarks by party General Secretary Aye Ko saying
some delegates to the congress had favored approving the
resignations.
   Political analysts speculated the official silence indicated
division within party ranks on the course of the country.
   Ko also said the delegates rejected the resignations submitted
by four of the party leaders because they were ``still young and
energetic.''
   The four included Aye Ko, party joint general secretary Sein
Lwin and central executive committee members Tun Tin and Kyaw Htin.
All hold senior government positions.
   In its broadcast, Radio Rangoon said the delegates had empowered
the party's central committee to consider sweeping proposals for
economic reform. Th radio did not say whether a decision had been
taken.
   In his remarks, Aye Ko said 15 delegates expressed opposition to
holding the proposed referendum on one-party rule on the grounds
that a 1973 referendum already had institutionalized it.
   The state radio announced Sunday that an emergency parliament
session would convene Wednesday, apparently to act on the
referendum proposal.
   According to Burmese law, the parliament is empowered to rule on
the referendum by majority vote. In the past, the parliament has
rubber-stamped most of the ruling party's decisions.
   The emergency session Wednesday could also deal with the
appointment of a new president to replace San Yu.
   Exactly when Ne Win will be replaced or by whom remains unclear.
Analysts have said a likely candidate would be Maung Maung Kha, the
prime minister since 1977. Maung Maung Kha has generally not been
regarded as an effective leader.
   Many western diplomats doubt that Ne Win, who has been in
undisputed control of the country for so long, will remain far
removed from policy decisions even after he leaves the government.
   The sudden and unexpected developments in Burma came in the wake
of bloody anti-government riots that have rocked Rangoon and other
cities three times since October. Martial law is still in effect in
Prome, 180 miles north of the capital, following riots there last
week.
   During his 26-year rule, Ne Win not only crushed anti-government
opposition but moved against leaders within his own ranks when they
exhibited what he saw as too much independence.
   He also is blamed for turning resource-rich Burma into one of
the nation's 10 poorest countries with an annual per capita income
of less than $200.
   In a speech Sunday, Aye Ko admitted economic production had
declined, working skills had deteriorated and ``losses and waste
cannot be controlled effectively.''
   ``Because of these weaknesses and as a result of adverse
repercussions from the world economic conditions today, the state
economic situation is declining,'' he said.
   He called for an end to state control of many sectors and for
allowing joint ventures between Burmese entrepreneurs and foreign
investors. Ne Win banned such ventures shortly after seizing power.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
