<1ST_LINE>r w AM-AngolaTalks 1stLd-Writethru a0574 07-25 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Angola Talks, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0574,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four-Way Military Talks Held Off African Coast</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 2nd graf pvs, bgng: The United, to CORRECT Woods' name
and title</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Military officials from Angola, Cuba, South
Africa and the United States met on an island off the coast of
Africa to discuss the next moves in an evolving peace accord in
southwestern Africa, the State Department confirmed Monday.
   The United States, which is acting as a mediator, was
represented at the July 22-23 meeting by a joint delegation from
the Defense and State departments headed by James L. Woods, the
deputy assistant secretary of defense for African affairs, State
Department spokesman Charles Redman said.
   Redman said the talks on the island of Cape Verde were
``complementary'' to the diplomatic negotiations under way for a
withdrawal of Cuban and South African troops from Angola and
independence for South-West Africa, also known as Namibia.
   A further round of political-level talks will be held between
the sides in Geneva next week. Although Cuba, Angola and South
Africa have accepted the principle of withdrawal, they are still
wrangling over timetables.
   Redman did not elaborate on what the military officials
discussed at the meeting, which was first disclosed over the
weekend by the Portuguese news agency, LUSA.
   One of the matters which probably was on the agenda is the
proximity of some of the estimated 50,000 Cuban troops to South
African forces in southern Angola.
   U.S. officials have voiced concern that the two sides might
clash, thereby escalating the conflict and scuttling the diplomatic
breakthrough.
</TEXT>
