<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 1500EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ContraArms     07-25 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Contra Arms,0506</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defendant Says Case Goes `All The Way To The Top'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man charged with illegally aiding
the Nicaraguan Contra rebels pleaded innocent Monday and said his
operations were approved ``all the way to the top'' of the White
House.
   Jack Terrell, 47, is one of seven men indicted on charges of
violating the U.S. Neutrality Act by secretly aiding the Contras in
1984 and 1985.
   ``This is a case of right and wrong,'' Terrell said after
appearing before a federal magistrate. ``The soldiers are going to
be hung and the generals will walk.''
   Terrell's attorney, John Mattes, questioned why former National
Security Council aide Oliver North and other Reagan administration
figures connected to the Iran-Contra arms deal were not charged in
the case, which covers a period when Congress had banned military
aid to the Contras.
   Knowledge and approval of the aid operation ``went all the way
to the top'' of the White House, said Terrell. Asked if he meant
the president, Terrell repeated his statement.
   The former mercenary, who used the code name ``Colonel Flaco,''
said he received about $100,000 for the operations and added: ``it
did not come from private sources.''
   Terrell's defense also showed a document declassified during the
congressional investigation into the Iran-Contra affair, saying it
supports their contention that North was aware of the secret
activities.
   The Jan. 27, 1985, memo to North, which is unsigned but which
the defense says came from North's aide Robert Owen, specifically
mentions Terrell's co-defendant Tom Posey, head of Civilian
Materiel Assistance of Alabama.
   The memo says ``Posey is sending 4 people to (censored) to help
with the training,'' and asks North's approval of their departure
date.
   It adds that Flaco ``is going to be working with the Indians,''
an apparent reference to the anti-Sandinista Miskito Indians on
Nicaragua's eastern coast.
   Terrell said it was that operation that led to his
disenchantment with the government's anti-Contra policies.
   ``They were not interested in getting Nicaragua back,'' Terrell
said. ``They were interested in creating a situation in which the
American military would have to come in.''
   He said North had him thrown out of his base in Honduras ``with
Uzi submachine guns pointed at our heads'' because his operations
were ``getting off the railroad track.''
   Terrell later began speaking out against Reagan administration
policy on Nicaragua, and in subsequent memos North wrote that he
had to be stopped.
   A Terrell co-defendant, Joe Adams, was sentenced Friday to one
day of probation and fined $50 by U.S. District Judge Norman
Roettger, who could have sentenced him to 33 years in prison.
   Terrell faces the same possible penalty as Adams, but said he
would not plead guilty despite Adams' lenient treatment.
   ``I won't take a felony,'' said Terrell.
   Mattes said the defense would subpoena witnesses and documents
from government agencies, including the CIA and the National
Security Council.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
