<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 1526EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Japan-Collision     07-25 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Collision,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official Says Captains of Sub, Fishing Boat Share Blame</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The captains of a Japanese submarine and a pleasure
fishing boat probably share blame for a weekend collision that
killed nine people and left 21 missing, a Maritime Safety Agency
official said Monday.
   A senior defense official said the submarine's crewmen should
have done more to save the people in the fishing boat and were slow
to notify rescue officials.
   The 2,200-ton sub Nadashio and the 154-ton No. 1 Fujimaru
collided head-on Saturday southwest of Tokyo while the submarine
was running on the surface.
   Some of the 48 people on the boat were thrown into the water and
the boat sank in two minutes. Those missing are presumed dead.
   No injuries were reported among the sub's 75 crewmen.
   ``The investigation isn't complete yet, but it looks like both
vessels were partly responsible for the accident,'' the MSA
official said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Divers recovered the bodies of three more victims Monday in the
waters near Yokosuka, about 30 miles southwest of Tokyo.
   Rescue officials said 200 divers were searching for the 21
people still missing and others were on the ocean floor, attaching
cables to the hull of the 154-ton No. 1 Fujimaru so it could be
raised.
   Seiki Nishihiro, vice minister of state for defense, said the
sub's crew was slow to tell rescue officials of the accident
because its communications equipment only allowed it to talk to
naval headquarters, not to the safety agency.
   Men on the sub should have ``grabbed three or four life
preservers, if they were available, and jumped into the water'' to
save people from the fishing boat, Nishihiro told reporters.
   Twenty-one minutes elapsed before the safety agency was told of
the collision, according to news reports.
   Sixteen of the 19 people rescued were picked up by passing
vessels and only three by the submarine, the reports said. One of
those rescued died later.
   The Nadashio was crossing a busy shipping lane to enter Yokosuka
naval base and was trying to avoid hitting a yacht when it collided
with the boat, which a company fishing club had chartered for the
weekend, Adm. Shuichiro Higashiyama said Sunday.
   He said the fishing boat had not made an unexpected turn.
   Japanese maritime rules require the ship approaching from the
left to take evasive action when two vessels appear to be on a
collision course, with the other maintaining its course unless an
accident is imminent.
   In Saturday's accident, the sub was approaching from the left
and took such action, but the fishing boat also turned and a
collision resulted.
   ``If the No. 1 Fujimaru had not turned to the left, there would
not have been a collision,'' a Defense Agency official quoted
Higashiyama as saying. ``I believe the submarine commander took the
most appropriate measures to avoid an accident.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880725-0117 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 1511EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CancerCauses Bjt   07-25 0576</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cancer Causes, Bjt,0591</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Researchers Identify Genetic Defects That Lead To Colon Cancer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAR HARBOR, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Researchers have identified genetic
mutations that lead to the development of colon cancer, a critical
step toward the development of better treatments for a form of
cancer that kills 53,500 Americans annually.
   ``You can look at these genetic alterations as the causes of
cancer _ just as you can look at bacteria as the causes of
infection,'' said Dr. Bert Vogelstein of the Johns Hopkins
University School of Medicine in Baltimore. ``Except it's more
complicated in cancer.''
   Just as the polio virus had to be discovered before the polio
vaccine could be developed, so these genetic changes must be found
before cancer can be prevented, Vogelstein said Monday in a
telephone interview.
   Research so far suggests that perhaps as many as seven genetic
mutations must occur for olon cancer tumors to appear, Vogelstein
said.
   Five of those changes have now been identified, said Ray White
of the Howard Hughes Medical Institute at the University of Utah in
Salt Lake City.
   Speaking Monday at The Jackson Laboratory here, White said that
colon cancer appears to be caused both by the activation of known
cancer genes and by the failure of certain anti-cancer genes.
   ``The steps in the pathway are starting to be filled in,'' White
said.
   Understanding how these genetic changes produce colon tumors may
allow doctors to distinguish between more severe and less severe
forms of colon cancer in individuals, White said, and could one day
lead to better cancer drugs.
   White has been one of the leaders in the study of the
anti-cancer genes that protect against cancer _ the so-called
recessive oncogenes.
   One such gene, identified in a rare form of eye cancer, has now
been linked to breast cancer and to a common form of lung cancer,
White said.
   Another such gene was found by White in families with a rare
kind of inherited colon cancer.
   Now, he said, failures of that anti-colon cancer gene have been
found to occur in about half of the much more common form of colon
cancer that is not inherited.
   Similarly, Vogelstein said he has found two specific genetic
variations in at least 75 percent of people with colon cancer.
   He has also found that a long-known cancer gene called the K-ras
gene is altered in about half of the colon cancer cases he has
studied.
   ``That kind of mutation is probably very important for the
development of colon cancer,'' Vogelstein said. ``And it suggests
some relationship between environmental influences and cancer.''
   Cancer is known to be caused, in part, by exposure to
carcinogens in the environment, he explained. Such carcinogens
could be triggering some of the genetic mutations that he and White
are finding, he said.
   White said that some of these changes may produce polyps in the
colon. These polyps, of the type that President Reagan has had
removed, are thought to represent tissue in which some _ but not
all _ of the colon cancer genetic mutations are present.
   Vogelstein said statistical studies of colon cancer suggest that
perhaps no more than seven genetic mutations are required to
produce colon cancer tumors.
   With five of those changes now identified, researchers may be
close to identifying all of the principal genetic causes of colon
cancer, he said, opening the way to research on new and better
treatments for this disease.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
