<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Forgery     07-25 0217</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Forgery,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>$3 Million Forgery Scam Uncovered</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WATERTOWN, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An owner of a printing plant faces
forgery charges in a scheme to print and sell $3 million in $50 and
$100 bills, a federal agent said Monday.
   ``We believe we got all of it, that none of it was put into
circulation,'' said Stewart Henry of the Secret Service's regional
office in Boston.
   Richard P. Edmands, a Watertown resident and co-owner of the
Reproprint Co., was to be arraigned Monday on charges of
manufacturing counterfeit U.S. currency and possession of forgery
plates and tools, Henry said.
   Edmands was arrested Sunday when an undercover Secret Service
agent went to Reproprint after arranging to pay $50,000 in cash for
the $3 million in counterfeit bills, Henry said.
   ``The quality was average to good. They were very passable,''
Henry said. The quality of a forged bill depends largely on the
quality of the camera that is used to produce a negative from which
the printing plates are made, he said.
   ``The paper did not contain the red and blue security fibers,
but it was a good rag paper,'' Henry said. The U.S. Treasury uses
special dies and fibers to make U.S. currency difficult to
duplicate.
   Henry said he could not comment on what led to the investigation.
</TEXT>
