<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AstronautHallOfFame     07-25 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Astronaut Hall Of Fame,0242</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Astronaut Hall of Fame Planned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Personal mementos of America's seven
original Mercury spacemen will be displayed in the U.S. Astronaut
Hall of Fame to be built near this spaceport, former astronaut Alan
B. Shepard announced Monday.
   Shepard, the first American to fly in space and president of the
Mercury Seven Foundation, told a news conference the Hall of Fame
``will explain space travel from the astronauts' point of view''
through photographs, displays of training equipment, personal log
books, clothing and souvenirs of the nation's first corps of
astronauts.
   He said the attraction, to be opened in 1990, will share an
18-acre complex with the permament location of the U.S. Space Camp
of Florida and a 200-room hotel. It will be in Titusville, just
outside the gates of the Kennedy Space Center.
   The Space Camp, nearing the end of its first season, has been in
a temporary leased building. About 3,600 youngsters in grades 4
through 7 signed up for 3- and 5-day classes during the first year.
   Besides Shepard, the Mercury astronauts, named in 1959, were
Scott Carpenter, Gordon Cooper, John Glenn, Gus Grissom, Wally
Schirra and Deke Slayton.
   Grissom, as a member of the Apollo 1 crew, died in a launch pad
fire in 1967. The others are active in the Mercury Seven
Foundation, which operates the Florida Space Camp and funds college
scholarships in science and technology.
</TEXT>
