<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Punjab     07-25 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Punjab,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sikh Extremists Kill Golden Temple Head Priest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARBAKSH SINGH NANDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHANDIGARH, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh extremists Monday opened fire at
three leaders of the Golden Temple, killing the head priest and a
second official, and seriously injuring a third, police said.
   Police identified the dead as head priest Sohan Singh and Bhan
Singh, secretary of the Shiromani Gurdwara Prabandhak Committee,
which manages Sikhism's holiest shrine in the city of Amritsar,
police said.
   The head of the committee, Mal Singh Ghuman, suffered four
bullet wounds and was hospitalized in critical condition, police
said.
   According to police, the Sikh extremists armed with a AK-47
Chinese rifle sprayed gunfire at the three men at noon on a street
in Ludhiana, about 55 miles west of the state capital of
Chandigarh. Police said the gunmen fled on a motorcycle.
   The three were shot as they emerged from a board meeting of an
engineering college, Indian news agencies said.
   There was no immediate claim of responsibility for the attack. A
statewide manhunt was launched for the killers, said a Ludhiana
police official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The temple committee appointed the 60-year-old Sohan Singh head
priest in May after police and troops forced more than 150 Sikh
extremists out of the Golden Temple, which the militants used as a
base to wage their guerrilla war for an independent homeland in the
northwestern state of Punjab. At least 42 people, most of them Sikh
radicals, were killed during the siege.
   The head priest's predecessor and four other Sikh high priests,
who were jailed during the operation, remain in custody.
   The appointment of Singh, a moderate, was opposed by the
militants, who also objected to the priest's efforts to exonerate
Surjit Singh Barnala, former chief minister of Punjab. Barnala had
been excommunicated from the Sikh faith by radical priests in
charge of the temple after he defied their order to merge his
moderate political party with the militants.
   Police reported four other deaths in extremist violence in
Punjab.
   The latest victims raised to 1,560 the number of people killed
by Sikh militants in Punjab this year. An estimated 690 of those
killed have been Sikhs.
   The Sikh religion was founded about 500 years ago as an
alternative to Hinduism and Islam. Sikhs make up less than 2
percent of India's population, but they are a majority in Punjab.
The Sikh militants claim they are being discriminated against by
India's majority Hindus.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
