<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDSDrugs     07-25 0579</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Drugs,0596</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FDA Ruling On Import Of AIDS Treatment Drugs Gives Hope To Victims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN VEGA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government's decision to allow those
who suffer from AIDS to import unproved drugs is a response to the
gay community's frustrations about the search for a cure to the
deadly disease, according to advocates for AIDS victims.
   Larry Gostin, an attorney with the Harvard School of Public
Health, called the new program ``a signal advance in recognizing
the gay and IV-drug constituencies that have been calling for
this'' and grants AIDS patients ``a little bit of hope and
reprieve.''
   The government last week officially began allowing AIDS patients
to import drugs not approved for sale in the United States, as long
as the drugs are for personal use.
   U.S. Food and Drug Administration Commissioner Frank E. Young
revealed the change Saturday to a hostile crowd at the Second
International Lesbian and Gay Health Conference and AIDS Forum in
Boston. He said the policy would also apply to drugs for other
diseases.
   ``It's almost a shock because it's so contrary to the character
and the tradition of the FDA,'' said
   ``It allows AIDS patients to make some choices about their own
treatment,'' said Ellen Ratner, president of the National Lesbian
and Gay Health Foundation, which is sponsoring the conference on
gay health issues.
   ``If you're dying, you don't have a lot of choices,'' Ratner
said.
   The FDA had been repeatedly criticized by advocates of AIDS
patients who say the government is not moving quickly enough to
develop and test new drugs to treat the fatal, incurable disease.
   Increasingly desperate patients have been eager to try
experimental treatment, and Young said the FDA was changing its
policy even though scientists believe many of the drugs have not
been proved safe and effective.
   ``From the AIDS person's point of view, they have nothing to
lose and what they need is just some little optimism in their life.
If there's a risk, I think that they should be able to make the
decision about whether to assume that risk,'' Gostin said Sunday.
   Winfield Scott, associate dean for education at George
Washington University Medical Center, said the change responds to
gay community's frustration ``that answers aren't coming more
quickly.''
   Scott cautioned that although activists focus on the bureaucracy
as if the bureaucracy was the problem, ``The real problem is that
nature is very slow and reluctant to yield up her secrets.''
   Young said the FDA had previously allowed unapproved drugs to be
imported on an informal basis. One such drug was dextran sulfate,
which the federal government is only now beginning to test in human
trials as a treatment for AIDS.
   The FDA's new policy will insure that people in need can import
a small supply, generally enough for three months of treatment. The
drugs must be only for personal use and not for sale.
   AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is caused by a
virus that damages the body's immune system, leaving victims
susceptible to infections and cancer. It is spread most often
through sexual contact, needles or syringes shared by drug abusers,
infected blood or blood products, and from pregnant women to their
offspring.
   Homosexual or bisexual males account for 62 percent of the
68,220 U.S. AIDS cases counted by the government since June 1981.
There have been 38,541 deaths, or 56 percent of the total cases,
the Centers for Disease Control reported last week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
