<2ND_LINE>AM-Switzerland-Crash,0133</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trains Crash; Eight Slightly Injured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AIGLE, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An express train from Italy crashed
head-on into a standing freight train Monday and eight people were
injured, although none seriously, authorities said.
   The Milan-Geneva express was traveling at more than 63 mph when
it rammed the other train in the station of this southwestern Swiss
town at 6:30 p.m., railway official Jean Dessous-L'Eglise said at
regional railway headquarters in Lausanne.
   All passengers were quickly evacuated from the coaches, a Swiss
television report from the scene said.
   Local police said eight passengers were injured, none of them
seriously.
   Most damage was to the two locomotives, but both engineers
escaped unhurt, Dessous-L'Eglise said.
   Officials suspected the accident was caused by a switching
error. The railways launched an investigation.
</TEXT>
