<1ST_LINE>r w AM-HomeSales     07-25 0664</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Home Sales,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Home Sales Jump As Buyers Try To Beat Higher Interest Rates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of existing homes rose in June to the
highest level in a year and a half as buyers tried to beat out
rising mortgage interest rates, a real estate trade group reported
Monday.
   The National Association of Realtors said existing single-family
homes were sold at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 3.78
million units last month, a 5.3 percent increase over May.
   It was the fifth consecutive monthly increase and the highest
level since homes sold at a rate of 4.06 million units in December
1986.
   In May, sales rose a revised 2.0 percent to a rate of 3.59
million units. An earlier estimate had put the gain at 3.1 percent.
   ``The anticipation of continued rising interest rates convinced
homebuyers to get into the market now, rather than waiting,'' said
John A. Tuccillo, the trade group's chief economist.
   ``But, in fact, rates did not increase as much as anticipated,
creating an added incentive for homebuyers,'' he said.
   Rates for fixed-rate, 30-year mortgages averaged 10.46 percent
last week, up only about a half of a percentage point from recent
lows in March, according to the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp.
The average does not include add-on fees known as points.
   However, many analysts are predicting rates will edge up by
another half or full percentage point by the end of the year,
curtailing sales.
   ``I would not be suprised if July gave us a level perhaps as
strong as June, but I think over the remainder of the year, we're
going to see those mortgage interest rates move upward and we're
going to see housing market activity trailing off as a result,''
said Richard Peach, an economist with the Mortgage Bankers
Association of America.
   June sales were 5.6 percent higher than a year ago, the first
time in 12 months that the sales pace beat the previous year's mark.
   For the first six months, existing homes sold at a seasonally
adjusted annual rate of 3.44 million units, up from 3.41 million in
the last half of 1987.
   There were 3.53 million homes sold for all of last year, down
slightly from 3.56 million in 1986, which was the best since 1979.
Most economists are expecting sales of about 3.40 million this year.
   ``There's been a clear tapering off, but we aren't in the
doldrums. We haven't had a housing bust by any means,'' said Mark
Obrinsky, an economist with the U.S. League of Savings Institutions.
   The strong sales came amid other indications of weakness in the
housing market. The annual rate of construction of new
single-family homes during the first half of 1988 was down 6.4
percent from the July-December rate of last year.
   Peach said much of the demand for new housing that built up when
interest rates soared early in the 1980s has been satisified. He
said existing homes sales are still relatively high in part because
of strong job growth and people moving to accept new and better
jobs.
   The June sales increase was led by a rise of 9.2 percent in the
South to 1.43 million units, followed by gains of 8.7 percent in
the Midwest to 1.00 million units and 7.8 percent in the West to
690,000 units.
   Sales declined 2.8 percent in the Northeast to an annual sales
pace of 700,000 units.
   The median price of an existing home rose $1,800 from May to
June, climbing to $90,600, up 2.0 percent. The median price was up
5.5 percent from $85,900 a year ago.
   Of the four regions, the West had the highest appreciation rate
over the past year, with a median sales price of $125,100, up 9.1
percent from June 1987. The Midwest posted a 7.3 percent gain to
$70,600, while in the Northeast the price rose 5.9 percent to
$146,300. In the South, home prices increased 4.3 percent in a year
to $84,100.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
