<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Ethiopians     07-25 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Ethiopians,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Legislator: Officials Preventing Ethiopian Jews From Emigrating</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel has denied visas to 150 Jews stranded in
Ethiopia, claiming they are not Jewish by Orthodox law, a
legislator said Monday.
   Mattityahu Peled, a retired general in the Israeli army and a
member of the left-wing Progressive Movement for Peace, said the
Ethiopians have relatives in Israel and have waited several months
in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia's capital, for visas to the Jewish state.
   He said U.S. Jewish leaders apparently assured the Ethiopians
the visas would be issued. The Ethiopians then abandoned their
homes and most of their belongings to assemble in Addis Ababa.
   But ultra-Orthodox Jewish officials at Israel's Interior
Ministry decided against issuing the visas, saying the Ethiopians
are not Jewish, Peled told The Associated Press.
   ``People are suffering because their families are divided,''
Peled said. ``Those who are mixed up in this have no way back. We
can't just leave them hanging in the air.''
   About 7,500 Ethiopian Jews were flown to Israel four years ago
in a secret rescue operation code-named ``Operation Moses,'' and
about 10,000 Jews remain in that African country, according to
official estimates.
   Immigration and Absorption Minister Yaacov Tsur denounced
Peled's remarks Monday as a ``blood libel.'' Israeli officials
consistently refuse to discuss emigration from Ethiopia, fearing
publicity could harm the effort.
   Peled said his information came from the San Francisco office of
the U.S.-based American Jewish Congress, an organization that has
been active in trying to help Ethiopian Jews emigrate. Part of the
information he received was published here by the respected daily
Haaretz.
   David Clayman, a spokesman for the American Jewish Congress in
Jerusalem, quoted AJC President Robert K. Lifton in New York as
saying the organization's head office was unaware of the matter
raised by Peled.
   But an official source, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
confirmed Peled's story.
   Tsur sent Clayman a telegram protesting the report, saying it
``shamed Israel's name,'' ministry spokesman Gad Ben-Ari said.
   ``I checked this matter with all the authorities involved and I
was assured unequivocally that there is no truth to this report,''
the telegram said.
   Many of the estimated 16,000 Ethiopian Jews in Israel have faced
discrimination from Israeli rabbis who often do not recognize them
as Jewish, claiming they cannot document their descendancy from the
ancient faith.
   The Ethiopians claim they are descendants of the biblical King
Solomon and the Queen of Sheba who lived in the 10th century B.C.
   Peled said many of the Jews left in Ethiopia could be brought to
Israel if not for Interior Ministry officials, who belong to the
ultra-Orthodox party Shas and have sole jurisdiction over visas.
   Ethiopia is allied with Israel's Arab enemies and thus reluctant
to permit Jews to come here.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
