<HEAD>F-16 Ditches Off Coast, Pilot Rescued</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 3rd graf to UPDATE that pilot treated and released.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An F-16 fighter jet on a training
mission from Shaw Air Force Base crashed Monday in the Atlantic
about 50 miles off the South Carolina coast, military officials
said.
   The pilot, who ejected safely, was plucked from the water by a
Marine rescue helicopter about 40 minutes after the 10:15 a.m.
crash, said Dave McMahon, a spokesman at Shaw, which is located in
Sumter.
   The pilot, identified as Capt. Paul Stone, 32, of Paintsville,
Ky., was examined at the hospital at Myrtle Beach Air Force Base
and released, said Staff Sgt. Brad Kadrich.
   The one-seat, $10.7 million F-16 was on a combat training
exercise with a second plane. The second aircraft made the initial
radio report to authorities, McMahon said.
   The cause of the accident may not be known for weeks, McMahon
said.
   Stone is assigned to the 19th Tactical Fighter Squadron at Shaw.
