<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 1650EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Police-Drugs     07-25 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Police-Drugs,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Chiefs Say Study Needed on Effectiveness of Anti-Drug
Spending</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A coalition of big-city police chiefs and
criminologists said Monday that Congress and President Reagan are
throwing money at anti-drug programs whose effectiveness never has
been tested.
   The coalition, in a letter sent to members of Congress and the
White House, urged that money be earmarked for research and
development in the war on drugs to find out which programs are most
effective.
   ``We are calling on the federal government to do what it is not
doing now ... to include money for research ... and bring
reflection and thought to our policy on drugs,'' Anthony V. Bouza,
chief of police in Minneapolis, said at a news conference where the
letter was released.
   The coalition said 5 percent of total federal anti-drug funds
should be set aside for research and development. Congress is
expected to approve at least $1 billion for the war against drugs
in the next fiscal year.
   Research could help determine how best to reduce demand for
drugs, which treatment programs are most effective in keeping drug
addicts from committing crimes and determine the costs and benefits
of massive police crackdowns on drug-dealing locations, the police
chiefs said in their letter.
   ``Throwing more money into existing programs will not answer
these and other critical questions,'' the group said. ``We urge you
to invest in better strategic knowledge for winning this war.''
   The current war on drugs ``is characterized by defeat,'' Bouza
said because of the lack of a coherent policy. Police need to know
whether massive roundups of suspected drug dealers and raids on
suspected drug operations are effective in deterring drug dealing,
he said.
   The letter was signed by 46 police chiefs, sheriffs, law
enforcement representatives and criminologists.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
