<1ST_LINE>r p AM-GOPDelegates     07-25 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-GOP Delegates,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Michigan Republicans Defuse Convention Credential Fight</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Backers of George Bush and Pat Robertson,
who feuded for months over the Michigan delegation to the
Republican National Convention, agreed Monday to greater
representation for Robertson's supporters in a show of unity that
officials hope will ensure a winning GOP ticket in November.
   The agreement, reached after weeks of negotiations between the
two factions, gives the former Republican presidential candidate 13
of the state's 77 delegate votes at next month's convention.
   Vice President George Bush, the virtual nominee, gets the
remainder of the delegates.
   ``Having this agreement behind us now really clears the deck,''
said state party Chair Spencer Abraham. ``It allows us to continue
on using the time until New Orleans to develop the Michigan
campaign.''
   Lori Packer, the Michigan director of Americans for Robertson,
said the Robertson camp was convinced a credentials fight over
delegates would hamper the party's mission: electing the Republican
ticket in November.
   ``Our differences are minimal compared to what we face in the
fall,'' Ms. Packer said. ``Proving we are right ... at the expense
of having Michael Dukakis as the leader of the free world is a
price that we're not willing to pay.''
   In the early stages of Michigan's two-year delegate-selection
process, the Robertson forces matched the Bush forces in recruiting
precinct delegates to the county conventions.
   That led to a temporary shift of party leadership, a series of
lawsuits and in January a dramatic split at the state convention.
Robertson-backing Republicans _ joined by some supporters of New
York Rep. Jack Kemp _ broke from the main GOP group, held their own
state convention and planned a credentials challenge in New Orleans.
   As part of the agreement announced Monday, the renegade
Rpublicans agreed to put the only remaining lawsuit on hold for
nine months and the national party agreed to give non-voting
``honorary delegate'' status to about 30 of the renegade delegates
who have made transportation and hotel arrangements for the
convention.
   Of the five delegates who relinquished seats, four were from the
Kemp camp and one was a Bush delegate _ former Gov. George Romney.
In addition, two delegates gave up their membership on convention
committees in favor of Robertson backers.
   Bush has amassed more than the 1,139 delegates needed to win the
nomination. But Robertson, who returned to his evangelical
television program since dropping out of the presidential race, has
not released his delegates.
   The 13 Michigan delegates remain bound to vote for Robertson
unless he says otherwise, according to Ms. Packer.
   ``It hasn't been made clear to me what his intentions are,'' she
said.

</TEXT>
