<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Coroner-Con 1stLd-Writethru a0626 07-25 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Coroner-Con, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0626,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Claiming Bodies Tougher Following Fake Death Scheme</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs penultimate graf to CORRECT that probation officer
ordered copy of autopsy report, sted ordered autopsy</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People who want to claim a body from the
coroner's office will first have to identify the corpse in a photo
lineup under guidelines established after a woman gained custody of
a body to fake her own death certificate.
   The Los Angeles County coroner now also requires people wishing
to claim a body to show a driver's license and have fingerprints
taken.
   Officials said that while they are sympathetic to grieving
families, the new rules are necessary to prevent a similar scam in
the future.
   The stricter standards came about after a woman trying to avoid
creditors and probation officers gained custody of an unidentified
body and tried to have her name registered as the deceased.
   Sharon Hall and her mother, Helene Tilch, were sentenced July 14
after pleading guilty to one count each of false personation, or
creating a non-existent person.
   Ms. Hall, 35, received a two-year sentence, and Ms. Tilch, who
is 58 and in a wheelchair, got 16 months.
   Ms. Hall used the name Sharon Agee, called the coroner's office
in December and said she was looking for her dead sister. The
investigator asked for a description of the dead woman and Ms. Hall
essentially described herself.
   Her height, hair color and general description _ a heavyset
white woman in her mid-30s _ matched that of an unidentified body
unclaimed since its discovery Oct. 25 alongside a highway. The
woman apparently died of a drug overdose.
   Ms. Hall and her mother were very emotional when shown the body.
   ``They were good at their craft,'' said Philip Spada, a
supervising coroner's investigator. ``And their craft was scamming
people.''
   The coroner's office, which handles 17,000 to 20,000 bodies a
year, released the body to the two women, who had it cremated and
mailed the death certificate to Ms. Hall's probation officers,
prosecutors said.
   Sacramento County probation officer Karen Raquel ordered a copy
of the autopsy report, and the results showed the dead woman had
undergone a hysterectomy and was covered with tattoos. Raquel knew
the two characteristics did not fit Ms. Hall and called police.
   The dead woman's ashes have been returned to the coroner's
office, where they will remain should the woman's real relatives
come forward.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
