<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CandidateMistakes     07-25 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Candidate Mistakes,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Schneider Relied On '86 Filing For '88 Mistake</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Lead planned with second hearing around 7 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FLIPPEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. Claudine C. Schneider told the
state Board of Elections on Monday that she signed her 1986
candidacy declaration with the same signature that has jeopardized
her 1988 candidacy.
   Schneider, R-R.I., signed both forms with her middle initial,
which is not on her voter registration card. And that was part of
the trouble.
   Schneider also listed her Narragansett address on the 1988 form
as 56 Central Ave., although, as her registration reflects, she
actually lives on Central Street.
   State law requires the two forms to match exactly, and three
minor candidates asked the board Monday to disqualify Schneider
because of the discrepancies.
   Two other candidates _ Sen. John H. Chafee, R-R.I., and
Democratic gubernatorial candidate Bruce G. Sundlun _ have been
challenged on similar grounds. Sundlun's hearing was scheduled
later Monday, and Chafee's for Tuesday.
   Decisions on all three cases were expected Wednesday.
   Schneider and her attorneys contend her 1988 candidacy can't be
challenged because her 1986 candidacy went uncontested despite the
signature discrepancy.
   ``As I was about to put my signature on there, I asked my staff,
`How did I sign in 1986?' and they said, `Claudine C. Schneider',''
she said.
   The 1986 form listed her address as Central Street, and the
congresswoman said she did not know how that error was made.
   ``The best I can guess is I had a staff member fill out the
form. Evidently, it's a typographical error,'' Schneider said.
   Mary Beck, clerk of the Narragansett Board of Canvassers,
testified the board refused to certify Schneider's candidacy
because the law does not allow discrepancies.
   But Beck said there was never any question of fraud.
   Earlier this year, the town and state board disqualified Denise
R. Felice, a would-be Jesse Jackson delegate, from the presidential
primary for the same middle-initial error Schneider made.
   ``What was good for Felice should be good for Mr. Chafee and
good for Claudine Schneider,'' argued John J. Staradumsky, one of
those objecting to Schneider's candidacy.
   Schneider's attorneys said the cases were different because
Schneider had relied on the earlier filing, and because the
objections to her candidacy were filed by three people who would
not be affected by the decision rather than by primary opponents.
   Staradumsky is seeking Chafee's seat; Vincent J. DuBreuil is
seeking a state Senate seat, and Stephen Robertson, who filed the
first objection to Schneider's candidacy, is running for her seat
as a write-in candidate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
