<DOCNO> AP880725-0142 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 1818EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DrugHouses     07-25 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Houses,0430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Philly Officials `Crack' Down On Suspected Drug Houses</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PX1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City officials cleaned out and sealed Monday
the first two of 500 houses identified by police as crack dens, and
neighbors plagued by drug traffic gave mixed reviews.
   ``I'm glad to see this happen because they would come to my
house by mistake,'' Lavinia Murray said from the front porch of her
southwest Philadelphia home, watching city workers haul junk out of
a neighboring house and begin sealing it.
   Another neighbor, Yvonne Hill, was not so impressed.
   ``They'll just move around the corner, or down the street.
They're everywhere,'' she said.
   A day before, Mayor W. Wilson Goode toured what police said was
a crack house in the neighborhood as he announced a campaign to
drive drug dealers out.
   ``We're going to harass them so much, arrest them so many times
that we'll drive them out of the neighborhoods and out of the
city,'' said Goode, whose announcement followed growing
drug-related violence in which children have been shot.
   Once houses have been identified as places where drug sales take
place and raided by police, Goode said the houses would be sealed
or demolished.
   Goode said southwest Philadelphia has about 150 of the estimated
500 to 600 houses in the city where the crack form of cocaine is
sold.
   Employees of the city Department of Licenses and Inspections
showed up Monday with dump trucks to clean out and shut down two of
the houses, taking out furniture and everything else inside and
tearing out gardens.
   ``What we're trying to do is close a couple of houses, to
stabilize the neighborhood,'' said L&I Commissioner John Plonski.
   ``Our department has made a determination that these houses are
not beyond repair and that they can be salvaged,'' he said.
   Neighbors said no drugs had been sold from either house for the
past three months. No one was in either house, and no arrests were
made.
   ``They (drug dealers) stopped (dealing) before this,'' said Joel
Walker, 25, sitting on the steps of his home a couple of doors
away. ``Them people ain't dumb. Doing houses ain't going to stop
it. It's a big street. If they lose them (houses), they're going to
get another.''
   Deborah Robinson, 31, a mother of two from the same block, said
the city's action would help ``a little.''
   ``It's a beginning, but still more has to be done,'' she said,
adding dealers had begun conducting business on a nearby corner.
</TEXT>
