<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PantherOperation     07-25 0207</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panther Operation,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Endangered Panther Undergoes Surgery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An endangered Florida panther, believed
to be one of only five surviving at Everglades National Park,
underwent surgery Monday to fix its mangled leg, state wildlife
experts said.
   ``She was hit by a vehicle. She lost a lot of blood,'' said
Florida Game and Fresh Water Fish Commission Lt. Jim Hoffstodt. The
60-pound female was spotted limping by a passer-by who called
officials Saturday.
   ``They found panther blood and hair and started to track the
cat,'' Hoffstodt said. They had her tranquilized and shipped her to
Gainesville on Sunday.
   Surgeons at the University of Florida's veterinary school
implanted a steel plate in the cat's left hind leg to stabilize its
broken thigh bone. The plate was to be anchored by grafted bone
from the panther's left front shoulder.
   An estimated 30 to 50 Florida panthers, shy and nocturnal brown
cats, remain in the state. The injured female is one of five in the
Everglades park that have been tagged with radio collars.
   ``That radio collar saved the panther's life. We never could
have found her if she wasn't wearing it,'' Roelke said.
   If the operation is a success, the panther will spend several
months recuperating.
</TEXT>
