<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Britain-Cabinet     07-25 0449</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Cabinet,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thatcher Revises Cabinet, Appointing New Health Secretary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher reorganized her
Cabinet on Monday, dividing the unwieldy Health and Social Services
Department and choosing a new health secretary from the left of her
Conservative Party.
   The new post went to Kenneth Clarke, 48, who has been trade and
industry minister, said an announcement from Mrs. Thatcher's office
at 10 Downing St. Her Cabinet now has 22 members.
   Clarke is one of a half-dozen politicians regarded as possible
successors to the 62-year-old prime minister. He will oversee the
National Health Service, whose uncertain future is among the most
sensitive issues of Mrs. Thatcher's third term.
   Tony Newton, a 50-year-old former deputy health minister, was
brought into the Cabinet to take Clarke's former job.
   In what was widely seen as a demotion, Mrs. Thatcher took
responsibility for the National Health Service away from John
Moore, the social services secretary. She also removed him from a
committee that is reviewing the future of the National Health and
is to report in September.
   Mrs. Thatcher changed 21 of about 90 ministerial posts outside
the Cabinet, dropping six officials. The most senior Cabinet posts,
foreign affairs and finance, were left in the hands of Sir Geoffrey
Howe and Nigel Lawson, ending speculation that Lawson might quit
because of policy differences with Mrs. Thatcher.
   Among the non-Cabinet changes, Foreign Office minister David
Mellor, a vocal critic of Israel, was moved to a job of equivalent
rank in the Health Department.
   Mellor, one of Howe's five deputies, was succeeded by William
Waldegrave, a minister in the Environment Department.
   The first shuffle of Mrs. Thatcher's Cabinet since she won a
third term in the June 1987 elections had not been expected until
September. Aides said she acted early because of the impending
report on the National Health, which was established 40 years ago
to provide Britons with cradle-to-grave care.
   National Health costs $35.4 billion a year and Social Services,
including welfare and state pensions, add another $83.4 billion.
The total is 44 percent of government spending.
   Clarke, whose views are generally more liberal than Mrs.
Thatcher's, was elected to Parliament for Rushcliffe, central
England, in 1970 and appointed to the Cabinet in 1985.
   As trade and industry minister he shared a portfolio with Lord
Young, the trade secretary and a member of the unelected House of
Lords. Clarke also was minister for inner cities, whose revival
Mrs. Thatcher considers a major task.
   He is a Cambridge-educated writer who describes himself as ``one
of the classless meritocracy of the 60s.'' Like Mrs. Thatcher, a
grocer's daughter, he is the son of a small-town shopkeeper.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
