<DOCNO> AP880725-0148 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 1856EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Military     07-25 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Military,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shevardnadze Says Legislature Should Oversee Defense Industry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze said
Monday the Soviet legislature should oversee the defense industry
and make decisions about how the armed forces are used abroad.
   His remarks to a Kremlin foreign policy conference, reported by
state television, were an elaboration of proposals Soviet officials
have mentioned for expanding the powers of the legislature, the
Supreme Soviet.
   Shevardnadze said last month's Communist Party conference set
the stage for strengthening civilian control of the military.
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev told the conference of 5,000
party members June 28 ``an effective constitutionally authorized
mechanism'' was needed for a ``businesslike and competent
discussion of international issues.''
   New legislative procedures would bring ``all departments
occupied with the military and military-industrial activity ...
under the control of the highest all-people's elected organ,'' said
a television announcer who paraphrased Shevardnadze's remarks. The
reference appeared to be to the Supreme Soviet.
   Supreme control over the military now is believed in the hands
of the Defense Council, which works in secret without revealing its
exact functions or membership. Official media have said Gorbachev
leads the council.
   Gorbachev proposed in his speech to the party conference that a
new, stronger president take over the Defense Council and make key
foreign policy decisions.
   Conference delegates supported his call for strengthening the
legislature by creating a 2,250-member Congress of People's
Deputies that would choose a smaller standing Supreme Soviet.
   Shevardnadze said the new legislature should supervise ``use of
military forces outside national borders of the country and plans
for defense construction and openness of military budgets,''
according to the television report.
   Bringing the legislature into decision-making on foreign
military activities may be an attempt to avoid repetition of what
some Soviet officials say was the mistake of sending troops into
Afghanistan in December 1979.
   They say only a few Soviet leaders approved the intervention and
did so without consulting specialists who would have advised
against it. The soldiers now are being withdrawn under an agreement
mediated by the United Nations.
   A Western military attache told The Associated Press the changes
Shevardnadze outlined reflect an effort to ``have more people have
a say'' in military decisions.
   Shevardnadze's remarks were reported only partially in the
television news program Vremya. A report of the foreign policy
meeting by the Tass news agency did not include Shevardanadze's
proposals for wider oversight of the military.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
