<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NavyDeath 1stLd-Writethru a0627 07-25 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Navy Death, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0627,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Instructor Pleads Innocent to Involuntary Manslaughter</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 3rd graf, `If the..', to restore dropped first name of
victim Mirecki.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PA1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The only one of five enlisted Navy
instructors charged with involuntary manslaughter in the training
death of a 19-year-old recruit pleaded innocent Monday.
   A military judge also set an Aug. 29 trial date in the
court-martial of Petty Officer 2nd Class Michael Combe, but said he
may delay it if a defense lawyer could not appear because of his
wife's illness.
   If the date stands, Combe's trial would start a week after that
of Lt. Thomas A. Torchia, officer in charge of the Navy Rescue
Swimmer School at Pensacola Naval Air Station when Lee Mirecki, of
Appleton, Wis., died March 2.
   Four other enlisted instructors were charged only with
conspiracy to commit battery and received nonjudicial punishments
including reductions in rank and loss of pay.
   Torchia also was offered nonjudicial punishment but chose a
court-martial in an effort to clear himself. Combe, however,
received no choice. His court-martial was ordered by Vice Adm. N.R.
Thunman, chief of naval education an training, following an
investigative hearing last month.
   The Navy has accused Combe of holding Mirecki's head under water
after he was pushed into the pool. Besides manslaughter, Combe is
charged with battery and conspiracy to commit battery.
   Instructors allegedly forced Mirecki into a pool after he had
panicked, climbed out, held on to an equipment rack and shouted
that he was quitting the course.
   At the investigative hearing, a pathologist testified that
Mirecki had a phobia about being dragged under water, which
triggered heart failure followed by drowning. Mirecki was taking
part in a practice rescue in which the instructors, playing the
role of panicked air crash victims, grasped recruits in a head-hold.
   Witnesses at the hearing gave conflicting testimony on whether
Mirecki was in Combe's grasp or had extricated himself from the
instructor's head-hold when he collapsed.
   The military judge, Cmdr. Gregory K. Radlinski, denied a request
by defense lawyers to delay the trial until late September.
Prosecutor Lt. David G. Smith had argued for starting the trial as
early as Monday.
</TEXT>
