<2ND_LINE>AM-Egg Output,110</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hens Work Harder But Egg Production Down From Last Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's hen flock worked a little harder
last month, but because of fewer birds the extra effort fell short
of the year-ago production mark, the Agriculture Department
reported Monday.
   June output was estimated at 5.52 billion eggs, down 2 percent
from June 1987, the department's Agricultural Statistics Board
said. Meanwhile, the number of hens in laying flocks declined 3
percent during the month to an average of 269 million birds.
   Individually, however, the fewer hens shelled out more eggs _ an
average of 2,054 eggs per 100 birds during June, up from 2,033 a
year earlier, the report said.
</TEXT>
