<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 1925EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-JournalDebunks     07-25 0578</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Journal Debunks,0594</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Angry Words Over Experiment with Inexplicable Results</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bitter words circulated in the scientific
community Monday over reports that this week's edition of a
respected science journal will debunk an experiment that defies
scientific theory.
   The experiment baffled researchers because it appeared to use
sound methods to prove the impossible: that natural proteins called
antibodies that react with certain blood cells will continue to
react when diluted far beyond the point where they should
theoretically be able to do so.
   Nature, a science weekly, published the antibody findings in its
June 30 edition, but in an unusual ``editorial reservation''
declared: ``There is no physical basis for such an activity.''
   It said experts it later chose to review the research did not
believe the result, but could not fault the conduct of the
experiments, and the journal promised to have independent
investigators observe repetitions of the experiments.
   The report of the investigation is to appear in this week's
edition of Nature and advance word, leaked to the French press, is
that it dismisses the experiment as fanciful, poorly conducted and
of no scientific value.
   Editors of Nature have refused comment, but sources at the
magazine confirmed privately that an article will appear that
discredits the experiment.
   They also confirmed reports that Nature's independent
investigators were James Randi, a professional magician from
Florida known for studying unusual scientific claims, and Walter
Stewart of the National Institutes of Health at Bethesda, Md., an
investigator of scientific fraud.
   ``Nature is going to produce a totally and completely negative
report on the experiment,'' said Dr. Jacques Benveniste of the
French medical institute INSERM, who produced the inexplicable
results at his Paris laboratory.
   Researchers in Canada, Israel and Italy say they have duplicated
Benveniste's results. Benveniste and the sources at Nature magazine
both said the report does not suggest cheating was involved.
   Benveniste said in a telephone interview he had seen Nature's
article and ``I don't consider it as serious. I think it will harm
Nature.''
   Randi and Stewart ``made an enormous amount of mistakes that I
will outline in my answer to Nature,'' Benveniste said, adding that
the controls the investigators used were inadequate. Controls are
special samples used in laboratories to check testing procedures.
   Quoting from the rebuttal he is sending to Nature, Beneviste
said: ``All in all, the judgment is based on one dilution series,
tested on two bloods, in awful technical and psychological
conditions. Outrageous.''
   He would not specify what Nature's article says because the
magazine has not yet released it publicly, but quoted a passage he
said would ``make their whole report auto-destruct.''
   As quoted by Beneviste, the passage says: ``Thus we believe that
many of the experiments whose results are regarded as significant
are artifacts of statistical noise. But plainly this doesn't apply
to all the data _ for example the fourth experiment in the series.''
   That means the investigators had failed to discredit all the
experiments, he said.
   Patricia Fortner, an immunology research associate at the
University of Toronto, which reported duplicating the experiment,
said last month: ``It's unbelievable and it breaks all rules.''
   She said in an interview at the time that the supposedly
impossible reaction occurs even at extreme levels of dilution when
theoretically no antibody molecules are left in the solution.
   ``This has really shaken up our world,'' she said. ``Even people
who have seen this phenomenon find it hard to believe.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
