<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Salvador-Attack     07-25 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador-Attack,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leftist Guerrillas Attack Bowling Alley In San Salvador</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Salvador</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guerrillas attacked and set
fire to a bowling alley in the capital Monday in response to the
police disruption of an anti-government march, the establishment's
manager said.
   No one was reported hurt. No group made independent claims of
responsibility for the attack.
   Guillermo Castro, manager of the Bolerama Jardin, said 10 to 12
masked men with pistols and at least one submachine gun burst into
the bowling alley and identified themselves as ``urban commandos''
of the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front.
   The front, a coalition of five guerrilla groups, has waged an
8-year-old war against the U.S.-backed government, but the fighting
in recent years has been largely restricted to the countryside.
   Castro said the guerrillas made the about 30 patrons ``lie face
down on the floor and took from them money they said was a
`contribution' to the cause. They said the attack was in reprisal
for the government's repression of Thursday's march.''
   The guerrillas then doused several pool tables in a room
adjoining the main bowling area with gasoline and set them afire,
and the flames spread, Castro said.
   Firefighters arrived within 15 minutes and extinguished the
blaze. Castro estimated damage at $20,000.
   Castro said none of the bowling alley owners has any connection
with the government, and that he did not understand why the
establishment was selected as a target.
   Last Thursday, police used tear gas and fired shots in the air
to break up an anti-government demonstration in San Salvador.
Protesters then burned at least nine vehicles.
   Human rights groups estimate more than 65,000 people have been
killed in El Salvador since the civil war began in October 1979.
</TEXT>
