<HEAD>Arson Investigators Return to Gutted Spielberg Home</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos LA3, LA4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MALIBU, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arson investigators returned to Steven
Spielberg's gutted beachfront home Monday to examine the blackened
second floor for clues on what started the fire that also heavily
damaged director Walter Hill's home.
   Damage to both homes from the Sunday night fire along the Broad
Beach celebrity enclave was placed at more than $330,000. While the
fire is believed to be accidental, the arson team went Monday for a
second look.
   ``The arson investigators have determined the fire at the home
of Steven Spielberg was accidental in nature,'' said Deputy Kathryn
Nielsen of the Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department. ``They were
out there late last night, but decided to go out again today to see
if they could find out how it started.''
   Spielberg; his actress-wife, Amy Irving; and their son, Max,
weren't in the house and there were no injuries, authorities said.
Hill also wasn't home, but arrived as firefighters were mopping up.
   One investigator said film stored at Spielberg's house may have
been a factor.
   Damage to the Spielberg home was estimated at $210,000, Reyna
said. Hill's residence next door sustained $120,000 in damage, with
about 30 percent of the home destroyed.
   It took 40 firefighters about 40 minutes to extinguish the
blaze, which broke out about 6:40 p.m.
   Other celebrity residents along the mile-long section of Broad
Beach Road include Sylvester Stallone, Robert Redford, Carroll
O'Connor and Goldie Hawn. The Broad Beach homes range between $3
million and $10 million in value.
   The fire, which could be seen for miles along Pacific Coast
Highway, attracted hundreds of onlookers and sheriff's deputies had
to be called to clear a path for emergency vehicles, authorities
said. Malibu is about 30 miles northwest of downtown Los Angeles.
   Among Spielberg's hit films as producer or director are
``Jaws,'' ``Close Encounters of the Third Kind,'' ``Raiders of the
Lost Ark,'' ``E.T. _ The Extra-Terrestrial,'' ``Empire of the
Sun,'' ``The Color Purple'' and the recently released ``Who Framed
Roger Rabbit.''
   Hill produced and directed ``Red Heat,'' the current hit
starring Arnold Schwarzenegger and Jim Belushi. His directing
credits include ``48 Hrs.,'' ``The Warriors,'' and ``Extreme
Prejudice,'' and he co-produced the popular science fiction
thrillers ``Alien'' and ``Aliens.''
