<1ST_LINE>r a AM-KoreaHelicopters CORRECTIVE   07-25 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea Helicopters, CORRECTIVE,0239</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Members who used a story slugged AM-Korea-Helicopters, sent
as a0444 early on July 6 under a Los Angeles dateline, are asked to
use the following story.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a July 5 story about a motion to reduce
the prison sentences of brothers Barry and Ronald Semler, The
Associated Press erroneously reported that the men were convicted
of illegally selling helicopters to North Korea.
   The Semlers initially were charged with 27 counts of export
violations, including illegal sale of helicopters to North Korea.
But in a plea-bargaining agreement, the Semlers pleaded guilty to
reduced charges. The charge relating to alleged illegal helicopter
sales was dropped.
   In addition, the article erroneously said a federal judge denied
the motion to reduce the Semlers' prison sentences.
   In fact, the judge postponed his decision until after the Summer
Olympic Games in Seoul, South Korea. If there are no serious
incidents at the Games, he said, he will consider reducing the
sentences in exchange for community service involving establishment
of a camp for underprivileged children at Ronald Semler's Malibu
ranch.
   The Associated Press also reported the judge said he would
``never let these guys out'' of prison if serious incidents
occurred at the Olympics. In fact, the judge said he would not let
them out early ``on my own prerogative.'' The judge does not have
authority in this case to extend the prison terms.
</TEXT>
