<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 1949EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Afghanistan     07-25 0519</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Afghanistan,0534</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Afghanistan Says Pakistan, U.S. `Fan Flames Of War'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghanistan lodged a strongly worded
protest with the U.N. Monday, accusing Pakistan and the United
States of violating peace accords and pleading with the U.N.
secretary-general to end this ``license to kill.''
   Afghanistan charged the two nations with fanning ``the flames of
war'' and engaging in ``blind terrorism.''
   A U.N.-sponsored political agreement was signed April 14 in
Geneva, providing for Soviet troop withdrawal over nine months,
non-interference in Afghan affairs and return of Afghan refugees
who have fled the civil war.
   The accords were signed by Afghanistan and by Pakistan, which
acted as spokesman for the anti-Marxist Afghan guerrillas, and were
guaranteed by the United States and the Soviet Union. The
guerrillas did not sign the accords.
   Foreign Minister Abdul Wakil of Afghanistan cited in his letter
to Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar ``the new wave of
ferocious and adventurist actions by extremists linked with the
Peshawar-based alliance of seven (guerrilla groups) who have
created appalling tragedies with missile barrages on Kabul and
other cities.''
   Major Afghan anti-government guerrillas are based in Peshawar,
Pakistan. Kabul is the Afghan capital.
   Wakil urged the U.N. chief to end the purported violations of
the Afghan accords by Pakistan and the United States, which has
been aiding the guerrillas.
   ``The people of Afghanistan expect that the means of
interference and the shipment of weapons will stop and the license
to kill shall no more be issued,'' said the letter, the latest in a
series of U.N. protests by Afghanistan and the Soviet Union.
   ``Is it not high time for Pakistan, principal signatory of the
accords, and the United States of America, the state guarantor,
which still fan the flames of war, to understand the futility of
blind terrorism?'' Wakil's letter said.
   His letter complained that on July 15, 17, 19 and 20, Kabul
residents were killed in bomb blasts by guerrillas based in
Pakistan. In the past 1{ months, it said, 177 missiles were fired
into Kabul, killing 75 people and injuring 98.
   The letter said the guerrillas want to disrupt the government
policy of reconciliation, create panic among the civilian
population, frighten refugees from returning to Afghanistan and
jeopardize the future of peace.
   It said Afghanistan is carrying out the Geneva accords and
Soviet troops are withdrawing on schedule, ``but brazen violations
are being carried out by the other side.''
   The United States has been supplying the guerrillas with an
estimated $500 million annually in arms and military supplies
channeled through Pakistan. It vowed to continue the supplies as
long as Moscow keeps up its military support of the Afghan
government.
   The Afghan accords prohibit Pakistan's interference in
Afghanistan's affairs. But weapons supply from the Soviet Union is
not banned. A separate agreement signed by Moscow and Washington
allows them to continue supplying their respective sides.
   Soviet troops entered Afghanistan at the end of 1979 to prop up
the pro-Soviet government and stayed on to help fight the
guerrillas. The estimated 115,000 Soviet troops began withdrawing
May 15 and are to complete the pullout by Feb. 15.
</TEXT>
