<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 1917EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Fahd-Iran     07-25 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fahd-Iran,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Saudi King Looks To `Amicable' Way Of Ending Rift With Iran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MECCA, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   King Fahd said Monday that he
regretted the absence of Iranians at the annual Moslem pilgrimage
to Mecca and expressed hope of an amicable settlement of the rift
between his country and Iran.
   Fahd, speaking to leaders of Moslem delegations in a speech
broadcast on Saudi radio, said: ``I regret not having seen the
pilgrims of the Iranian nation participating with their Moslem
brothers at these sacred spots.''
   The Saudi king said Iranian pilgrims still were welcomed to
``the land of Islam'' and blamed Iran for decisions that led to
their absence this year.
   ``What we hope is that these matters be settled in an amicable
manner and that the Moslems be gathered together in one frame,'' he
added.
   Saudi official figures released Monday said 1,379,556 Moslems _
including 762,755 from abroad and 616,801 from within the kingdom _
gathered this year for the pilgrimage, or hajj, which culminated
Sunday with the start of the four-day Eid al-Adha or Feast of
Sacrifice.
   About 145,000 pilgrims from Iran went to Mecca for the 1987 hajj.
   Iranian pilgrims held demonstrations last year in Mecca, despite
a ban on political protests, and 402 people died, including 275
Iranians. Saudi Arabia said they died in a stampede, but Iran
accused Saudi police of shooting at the pilgrims.
   Citing terrorism and subversion, Saudi Arabia last April broke
diplomatic relations with Iran, which has advocated taking away
from the Saudi royal family custodianship of Mecca and Medina,
Islam's holiest sites.
   Saudi authorities earlier announced that the number of pilgrims
would be restricted this year to one for every 1,000 residents of
each Moslem country.
   Iran boycotted the hajj to protest the cuts, and its
government-controlled news media said demonstrations occurred again
this year. The Saudis have denied those reports.
   Fahd made no reference to the Iranian reports of protests and
referred only indirectly to the 1987 riots.
   What happened last year, he said, was ``over ... and thanks be
to God, wisdom and logic prevailed and matters were put in their
perspective,'' he said.
   All of the world's 850 million Moslems are expected to make at
least one pilgrimage to Mecca if they can afford it.
   Mecca is the birthplace of Mohammed, the founder of Islam. Its
Grand Mosque houses the Kaaba, Islam's holiest shrine.
   Pilgrims also made journeys this week to shrines in Medina,
Mohammed's base for his 7th Century conquest of Arabia and the
spread of the religion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
