<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Rabbis     07-25 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Rabbis,0397</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peres Supports Conservative Jews In Struggle Against Orthodox</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Shimon Peres told Conservative
Jews on Monday he feels control of the faith by Orthodox rabbis
would harm Jewish unity.
   In an emotional speech frequently interrupted by applause, Peres
told representatives of the U.S.-based Rabbinical Assembly that his
Labor Party has ``decided to keep Jewish life together as a matter
of principle.''
   ``We have decided profoundly, seriously and permanently not to
discriminate Jewish people within the Jewish life and not to divide
the Jewish people,'' he said.
   The Rabbinical Assembly represents 1,200 Conservative Jewish
leaders worldwide. It began a six-day 88th annual convention Monday.
   Conservatives are struggling against what they contend is
discrimination by Orthodox rabbis, who dominate Israel's state
religious offices.
   More than 100 rabbis demonstrated against alleged discrimination
Sunday outside the seat of the Chief Rabbinate, which is Israel's
highest state religious body and is controlled by Orthodox Jews.
   Peres pledged to defend Conservative Jews against Orthodox
attempts to pass a ``Who's a Jew'' law that would change the status
of the non-Orthodox.
   ``Who is a Jew?,'' Peres asked. ``I can answer it very simply.
There is no Jew who can exclude another Jew from the Jewish life.''
His statements deviated from past Labor Party policy of cultivating
religious parties as political allies.
   Israeli analysts recently suggested Peres has abandoned hope of
forming a coalition with religious parties after parliamentary
elections in November.
   Labor faces a tough campaign against Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir's right-wing Likud bloc, with religious parties leaning
toward Likud.
   Ismar Schorsch, chancellor of the Jewish Theological Seminary of
America in New York, recalled a meeting with Peres at which the
foreign minister ``told us with gravity that the elections to come
would be the most important in the 40-year history of Israel.''
   ``Last week, Mr. Peres enlarged the nature of his campaign. He
entered the lions' den,'' Schorsch said, referring to the foreign
minister's criticism of the Orthodox establishment in a speech
Wednesday to 500 Orthodox rabbis from 30 countries.
   ``Mr. Peres raised the issue of religious discrimination within
that assembly,'' Schorsch said. ``By that exercise of courage he
enlarged the campaign to include the issue of pluralism and the
termination of religious terrorism within the state of Israel.''
</TEXT>
