<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Police     07-25 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Police,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Police Fire On Mobs In Three Cities After State Police
Disarmed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal paramilitary police fired on
mobs in Gujarat state Monday, an Indian news agency reported, a day
after the state's 59,000 police were ordered disarmed in a union
dispute.
   No reports of casualties were issued.
   Paramilitary forces opened fire in the state capital at
Gandhinagr and in Ahmedabad, the state's largest city, ``to
disperse violent mobs,'' the United News of India news agency
reported.
   Both army and paramilitary troops intervened in Ahmedabad to end
a stone-throwing fight, the Press Trust of India news agency
reported. It did not elaborate.
   In Ahmedabad, 18 miles south of Gandhinagar, the mobs also set
fire to four houses, eight shops and three-owned buses, the news
agencies said.
   The trouble began Sunday, when state officials accused police
unions of fostering a revolt, dismissed 55 policemen for ``high
indiscipline,'' ordered the state's police disarmed and called in
the army and the federal paramilitary troops.
   Police unions called a strike Monday, but the news agencies said
it was only partially successful.
   Paramilitary troops were reported patrolling most towns, and
army troops marched in four cities, the agencies said.
   Police Inspector Ashok Bhatt, a key union leader, has been taken
into custody under the National Security Act, which allows a
suspect to be held for up to two years without trial.
   Bhatt was one of 55 policemen dismissed, and Chief Minister
Amarsinh Chaudhary told UNI Monday that more policemen may be
dismissed in the next few days.
   The police unions have been demanding higher wages and better
working conditions.
   But state officials said Bhatt and his associates encouraged
indiscipline by police, even urging them to refuse temporary duty
in the strife-torn state of Punjab.
   On Sunday, paramilitary troops took control of police armories
in the state and the government ordered four of seven police unions
disbanded, government television reported.
</TEXT>
