<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Anglicans     07-25 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Anglicans,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pakistani Bishop Denounces Debate Over Biblical Miracles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANTERBURY, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Debates over biblical accounts of the
virgin birth of Jesus Christ and his resurrection have done more
damage to the spread of Christianity in the East than have
non-Christians, a Pakistani bishop said Monday.
   ``The theological controversies in the West can strike a fatal
blow to the spread of the Gospel,'' Bashir Jiwan, bishop of
Hyderabad, said. He addressed other Anglican bishops on the ninth
day of the three-week Lambeth Conference.
   Among those in the audience was England's Bishop of Durham David
Jenkins. In 1984, Jenkins aroused controversy by suggesting the
virgin birth, the resurrection and other miracles reported in the
New Testament were symbolic stories and did not actually happen.
   The Lambeth Conference of 525 bishops representing the world's
70 million Anglicans, including members of the Church of England
and U.S. Episcopalians, meets every 10 years.
   Jiwan said ``disbelief in the bodily resurrection of Jesus
Christ and the claim that it was only a spiritual experience of
resurrection in the minds of the disciples raises the question of
the authority of the Bible.
   ``The Bible is the divine source of revelation and the
touchstone of Christian doctrine.''
   He added it appeared Moslems believe more of Christianity than
Western Christian theologians who have ``laid down'' their
spiritual weapons.
   Jiwan and Jenkins were among three speakers discussing
evangelization and culture, but their subjects were not linked.
   Jenkins said Christian churches destroyed the credibility of the
Gospel by competing to recruit new members.
   Evangelization must be wide-ranging, not mutually exclusive, and
confront social, political and economic issues, he said.
   Christians should consider how their social structures,
political policies and ``economic exploitations'' diminished them
in God's image, Jenkins said.
   Bishop David Gitari of Kenya, the first African bishop to
address the full conference, criticized church laws for allowing
tolerance and pastoral care to divorcees while disciplining
polygamists.
   ``We see no contradiction in extending pastoral care to
divorcees, despite Jesus' strictures against divorce,'' he said.
``Yet we maintain a rigid disciplinary stance againmst polygamy
despite Jesus' silence on the subject.''
</TEXT>
