<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Egypt-Escapee     07-25 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Egypt-Escapee,0456</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prison Escapee Convicted in Sadat Assassination Killed by Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police stormed the hideout Monday of a
former army major who broke prison while serving life for the
assassination of President Anwar Sadat and killed the fugitive in a
gunfight, the government announced.
   It said Essam el-Kemary, 37, died in a shootout with police and
two policemen were wounded but are in satisfactory condition.
   El-Kemary was holed up in a Cairo apartment with two other
prison escapees, according to an Interior Ministry statement. It
said they also were serving life sentences after being convicted of
conspiracy in Sadat's murder.
   A ministry spokesman, who was not identified in line with
regulations, said security forces were searching for the two. He
did not spell out whether they escaped during the raid or were away
from the building when police attacked.
   Police called el-Kemary, a former officer in the armored corps,
``by far the most dangerous'' of the three.
   El-Kemary; Mohammed Khamis, 40, and Ahmed el-Aswani, 31, escaped
from Cairo's maximum-security Tura prison on July 17. They pried
open the cell door with an iron bar, overpowered their guards and
fled in a waiting car.
   They were convicted of conspiracy in the Oct. 6, 1981,
assassination of Sadat, but not of actually firing at him. Sadat
was killed by men in army uniforms while reviewing a military
parade.
   The ministry statement said: ``State securuty inquiries showed
that the escapees used an apartment in Cairo's el-Sharabiya
district as a hideout.
   ``At dawn today, the hideout was attacked. Its occupants met
security forces with bullets and explosive charges, but the forces
succeeded in seizing the apartment. The storming resulted in the
death of fugitive Essam el-Kemary and the wounding of two
policemen.''
   It said police found ``a number of plastic bombs and the prison
uniforms the three men used in their escape.''
   The government has said all three men were members of the Moslem
fundamentalist organization Jihad, or holy war. Jihad was blamed
for Sadat's assassination and an attempted coup.
   In the turmoil following Sadat's murder, Jihad militants took
over some government installations in the southern city of Assiut.
Officials said at the time that 87 people, including 66 policemen,
were killed in gun battles between Jihad members and security
forces.
   After trials, three convicted assassins were executed by firing
squad, two were hanged and more than 120 men were given prison
terms up to life.
   President Hosni Mubarak, who succeeded Sadat, has maintained
emergency laws since the 1981 assassination.
   The laws ban strikes, unauthorized public meetings and
demonstrations, and give the government wide powers of search and
arrest without warrant.
</TEXT>
