<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-25 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0496</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Storms Bring Hail, Strong Winds To Parts of Mid-Mississippi Valley</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Intense thunderstorms, which developed ahead of a cold front
pushing through the middle Mississippi Valley, produced heavy rains
and hail Monday in portions of Illinois and Missouri, and strong
storms also were reported in Florida.
   Three hangers and two small airplanes were destroyed and seven
were damaged at the Morgan County Airport in central Missouri. Two
cars and three boats were severely damaged and one airplane was
thrown into a trailer home. No injuries were reported.
   Three-quarter-inch hail fell near Bloomington, Ill., and hail
accumulated 1{ to 2 inches deep near Cooksville, Ill.
   Strong thunderstorm winds felled power lines near Eldon, Mo.,
and hail with winds up to 65 mph were reported near Sedalia, Mo.
   These thunderstorms extended along the cold front into Indiana,
Ohio and lower Michigan, where pea-size hail was reported.
   Elsewhere, thunderstorms produced pea-size hail, brief heavy
rains and gusty winds in western Maine and Vermont.
   Strong thunderstorms also hit parts of Florida. A home near St.
Petersburg sustained severe wind damage, the National Weather
Service reported.
   In the South, marble-size hail fell in Marshall County, Miss.,
prompted by thunderstorms extending from southern Arkansas to
western Alabama.
   Other showers and thunderstorms were scattered in the Carolinas,
north-central Texas, central Arizona and along the front range of
the Rocky Mountains.
   Temperatures were in the 70s in the Great Lakes states and the
northern half of New England, and even dipped into the 60s in
portions of the California coast. But much of the nation had
temperatures in the 90s, and in the desert Southwest, temperatures
climbed up to 110.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT
included nearly 1\ inches at Decatur, Ill., 1.05 inches at Terre
Haute, Ind., and about two-thirds an inch at Springfield, Mo., and
Memphis, Tenn.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 60
degrees at Arcata, Calif., and Crescent City, Calif., to 110
degrees at Needles, Calif. The early morning low for the nation was
35 at Gunnison, Colo.
   The forecast for Tuesday is for scattered showers and
thunderstorms in the lower Mississippi Valley, the Ohio and
Tennessee valleys and the northern Atlantic coast states. Scattered
showers and thunderstorms also are predicted in Florida, Alabama
and Georgia and in northern Wisconsin, the front range of the
Rockies, western Utah and northern Arizona.
   Highs in the 70s were forecast along the Pacific Coast and
northwestern Washington state, as well as the upper Great Lakes and
northern Maine; in the 80s in the upper and middle Mississippi
valley, the Ohio and Tennessee valleys and from the Appalachians to
New England; above 100 degrees in north central Texas, parts of the
Rio Grande Valley, in the desert Southwest and the valleys of
California, and from northeastern Oregon to southwestern Montana;
and in the 90s elsewhere.
</TEXT>
