<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-LouiseBrown     07-25 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Louise Brown,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>World's First Test-Tube Baby Celebrates 10th Birthday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Louise Joy Brown, the world's first test-tube
baby, celebrated her 10th birthday Monday with her parents and
six-year-old sister Natalie, also conceived through in vitro
fertilization.
   The birthday party was held at the family home in Whitchurch, a
suburb of the seaport of Bristol, according to the Daily Mail
newspaper.
   It quoted Louise's mother, Lesley Brown, as saying: ``One of the
things we were most frightened of when she was born was that she'd
play on the fact that she was the first test-tube baby. But
fortunately she seems pretty stable and level-headed.''
   Louise's father, John Brown, is a truck driver, and the couple
volunteered for in vitro fertilization after they had been unable
to have children during nine years of marriage.
   Professor Robert Edwards, who pioneered in vitro fertilization
with the late gynecologist Patrick Steptoe, said research in the
past decade was making the technique of conception outside the womb
more available and less expensive for childless couples.
   In an interview on British Broadcasting Corp. television,
Edwards said:
   ``The birth of Louise Brown was the first time that science and
medicine had really come into human conception and clarified all
the problems and all the mysteries of human conception.
   ``Now we have a lot of information.... Success rates are going
up with the use of frozen embryos together with better fertility
drugs ... and the cost is going down because newer, simpler
techiques of collecting eggs ... are making the approach far more
simple.''
   Steptoe died earlier this year. He and Edwards, a physiologist,
devised the technique originally to treat women with blocked
Fallopian tubes.
   In vitro fertilization has helped produce thousands of babies
worldwide, but the technique remains costly and uncertain of
success and is available to only about 5 percent of childless
couples.
   ``Most people do not get pregnant (with the technique),''
Edwards said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
