<2ND_LINE>AM-Convention-Rooms, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0565,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GOP Requests 3,000 More Rooms than Number Available</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with convention official saying
cancellations allowed most requests to be met; picks up 6th graf
pvs, bgng: ``We're matching, DELETES last four grafs pvs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JANET McCONNAUGHEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican National Convention organizers
said Monday it looks as if most of the requests for hotel rooms
during next month's gathering can be met _ although initially, the
demand was far greater than the supply.
   Monday was the deadline for state delegations and other groups
which made their reservations through the GOP to send their
deposits to hotels. By the day's end, it looked as if all those
delegates, staffers and journalists would have a place to call home
during the gathering, which begins Aug. 15.
   ``We've been able to accomodate pretty much everyone,'' said
Mary Mead, a convention spokeswoman.
   Earlier, organizers had been swamped with requests. In fact,
there were about 3,000 more rooms asked for than there were rooms _
and that had organizers nervous.
   But some delegations and news organizations apparently decided
they didn't quite need as much space as they had originally sought.
   ``It's so hard to tell these things until it gets time for the
deposits,'' said Mead. ``Mostly everything has evened out. Groups
adjust their numbers, mostly downward.''
   Monday was a busy day for hoteliers trying to sort out the new
numbers.
   ``We're matching names to deposit checks, making sure the monies
match up with the names,'' said Tom Rosepink, manager of the
Marriott Hotel, where all-but-certain Republican nominee George
Bush and the delegations from Texas, New Hampshire, Connecticut and
Maine will stay.
   He said 1,125 of his hotel's 1,290 rooms are assigned to the
convention through the RNC. Virtually all of the remaining 175
rooms, including a bloc taken by CBS, are for news organizations
and other groups attending the convention, he said.
   The only exceptions are eight rooms rented year-round by Delta
Air Lines. ``And even they are going to drop people off to attend
the convention one day and then continue on their route to L.A.,''
he said.
   Rosepink said he had been asked for more rooms for the vice
president and his entourage, and would give Bush any rooms assigned
to the delegations but not ultimately used by them.
   ``My gut feeling is that there may be one or two rooms
available,'' he said.
   Many hotels couldn't meet the demand without adding a wing or
cleaning out a storeroom. The Hyatt, which will be Media Central,
has booked every one of its 1,193 rooms to the convention.
   The Pallas Suites Hotel, which has 800 of its 1,000 rooms set
aside, may be able to provide 30 to 50 more if renovations are
completed in time, said Joan Caldwell, president and general
manager of Oak Development Corp., which operates the hotel.
   She said the remaining rooms are taken by permanent guests,
tours which made reservations before the GOP decided to come to New
Orleans, and the Secret Service, which booked the rooms on its own
rather than through the convention.
   There are 25,500 hotel rooms in and around New Orleans _ 19,500
within city limits and 6,000 in neighboring Jefferson Parish, said
Bill Langkopp of the Greater New Orleans Hotel-Motel Association.
   ``The Republicans blocked 17,500. Anything else, I'd think,
would be just a normal transient movement. The businessman who
comes here all the time,'' Langkopp said.
</TEXT>
