<2ND_LINE>AM-China Boat, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0620,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>71 Reported Missing in Second Boat Disaster</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout with second boat accident. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A boat sank after colliding with a barge on the
Yangtze River and 71 people are missing and feared drowned in the
second major boat disaster in Sichuan province in four days, it was
reported Tuesday.
   The official Xinhua News Agency said the Yunhang No. 24,
carrying a geological prospecting team from the Sichuan Petroleum
Administration, capsized quickly after the collision with the
barge. The crash happened in Yunyang county in southwestern China
on Monday.
   It said 25 people were rescued from the wooden, motor-driven
boat. The accident occurred at 10:42 a.m., Xinhua reported, but it
did not describe weather conditions or give further details.
   Last Thursday, a passenger boat carrying about 250 people sank
after hitting a rock in the Min River, a tributary of the Yangtze,
in Sichuan province.
   There have been differing figures on the number of casualties,
but Xinhua said late Monday 72 bodies have been recovered, about 30
people are missing and presumed drowned, and 152 people had been
rescued.
   An official of the Chongqing Shipping Co. in Sichuan said
earlier that the bodies of eight men 11 women had been found, but
she had little information about the accident because of poor
communications with the remote area.
   She said the company still does not know how many people were on
board when the boat hit a rock in rain-swollen waters and sank. The
vessel was carrying passengers between the towns of Yibin and
Leshan.
   Xinhua said Sunday authorities had located the sunken ship,
which had been carried downstream, and divers had arrived.
   China has been plagued by disasters on its overcrowded
transportation system this year. Four train accidents have left 169
dead, while the crash of a Chinese airliner, also in Sichuan in
January, killed 108.
</TEXT>
