<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Japan-Apology     07-25 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Apology,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Politician Apologizes For Remarks About American Blacks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior official of Japan's governing party
apologized Monday for remarks he made that implied that American
blacks do not care if they go bankrupt.
   Michio Watanabe, chief of the Liberal Democratic Party's Policy
Affairs Research Council and considered a possible future prime
minister, said his remarks over the weekend were ``misleading and
inadvertent.''
   In his speech Saturday at the party's annual summer retreat,
Watanabe said:
   ``They (Americans) use credit cards a lot. They have no savings,
so they go bankrupt.
   ``If Japanese go bankrupt, they would think it serious enough to
escape into the night or commit family suicide, but among those
guys over there (in the United States) are a lot of blacks and so
on who would think without concern, `We're bankrupt. Now we don't
have to pay anything back,''' he said.
   On Monday, Watanabe issued a statement apologizing for his
comments.
   ``In speaking of U.S. personal consumption on July 23, I made
misleading and inadvertent remarks, though in no sense did I ever
imply any racial discrimination,'' he said in the statement.
   ``I very much regret that the remarks may have hurt the feelings
of American friends and withdraw those words with apologies,'' he
said.
   Watanabe, a former Cabinet minister who held the finance and
trade portfolios, is a powerful political figure known to aspire to
be Japan's premier.
   In February, he drew fire from China when he said in a campaign
speech that people in China's Shanxi province ``have dug themselves
into pits and are still living there.'' He later apologized for the
statement.
   Watanabe's comments were the latest in a series of controversial
statements by Japanese politicians that have offended foreign
countries.
   Two years ago, former Premier Yasuhiro Nakasone told a Liberal
Democratic Party meeting that the large number of blacks, Puerto
Ricans and Mexicans in the United States brought down America's
intelligence level.
   That comment prompted widespread criticism of Nakasone in the
United States, and he issued an apology.
</TEXT>
