<1ST_LINE>u a AM-HijackingSuspect     07-25 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hijacking Suspect,0479</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Wanted in 1969 Hijacking to Cuba Arrested</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Haziine is cq in 2nd graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>BY DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman wanted in the 1969 hijacking of an
airliner to Cuba was arrested Monday by FBI agents who said she'd
been living here under an assumed name.
   Linda Joyce Grinage, 39, had been living with her husband as
Haziine Eytina when FBI agents arrested her Monday morning, said
Michael O'Brien, an FBI spokesman.
   Grinage was wanted for the hijacking of an Eastern Airlines DC8
plane en route from New York's Kennedy Airport to Miami on Jan. 2,
1969.
   Authorities said Grinage and her then-husband, Tyrone Ellington
Austin, took a 2-year-old boy hostage on the flight and forced the
pilot at gunpoint to fly everybody on board to Havana.
   No one was injured. The plane carried 138 passengers and a crew
of eight.
   During the alleged hijacking, authorities said, Austin ran up
the aisle of the plane shouting ``Black power!'' and ``Havana!''
Barbara Cottrell, an assistant U.S. attorney, declined comment
Monday when asked if Grinage was involved with any terrorist
organizations.
   Authorities received an anonymous tip last year that Grinage was
in Albany, but held off arresting her until Monday because they
needed more time to firmly establish her identity, Cottrell said.
   The couple remained in Havana when the passengers and crew
returned to the United States, and were indicted on air piracy
charges later that year.
   Austin died in 1971 from wounds he received during a shootout
with New York City police while fleeing a bank robbery. Authorities
did not release information on how the couple re-entered the United
States.
   A hearing to establish Grinage's identity was put off until
Tuesday morning after lawyer Milo Eytina, Grinage's husband,
requested the time to get a more experienced attorney. She was to
be jailed overnight.
   Grinage had no comment to reporters Monday.
   ``She is unable to respond in her present state to questions
addressed to her,'' Eytina told acting U.S. Magistrate Joseph
Scully, describing his wife as ``distraught.''
   If convicted on an air piracy charge, she could be jailed for 20
years to life.
   Grinage has lived in the Albany area since 1983 and has had at
least six different addresses, said Cottrell.
   Speaking to Scully, Eytina said his wife had lived in the
community for 10 years and was gainfully employed. But Cottrell
said Grinage, who has five children, did not have a job outside the
home.
   The FBI has 14 aliases listed for Grinage, according to an
affadavit filed in support of a search warrant. Authorities have
further established her identity through samples of her writing and
telephone records of a phone call made to her grandfather, the Rev.
Walter Staten of Brooklyn.
</TEXT>
