<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChernobylChild     07-25 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chernobyl Child,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ukrainian Girl's Brain Tumor Is Cancerous</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The brain tumor removed from a 2-year-old
Ukrainian girl is cancerous, and her prognosis is guarded, doctors
said Monday.
   Hanna Andrievna Sverstiuk had the tumor removed from the base of
her brain stem last Friday at Children's Hospital of Philadelphia.
   ``The outlook for her future is guarded, depending on her
response to therapy,'' said Dr. Roger J. Packer. ``While there's a
high likelihood of the tumor recurring, we're hoping this new form
of treatment can keep her in remission.''
   Hanna's mother, Maria Sverstiuk, has said she believes the
walnut-sized tumor resulted from radiation from the Chernobyl
nuclear disaster, 50 miles from Kiev in the Soviet Union.
   Hanna was born in Kiev five days after the April 26, 1986,
explosion and fire that killed at least 31 people and released a
cloud of radioactive material. She was diagnosed as having a brain
tumor two months ago.
   Doctors, however, say a solid tumor like Hanna's would have
taken 10 to 20 years to develop if it were caused by radiation.
   ``She is recovering extremely well, considering the type of
brain surgery she had,'' Packer said.
   Her mother has maintained a bedside vigil, reading stories and
singing Ukrainian songs, according to the hospital. Hanna is to
begin her radiation program and physical therapy later this week,
the hospital said.
   The toddler's trip to the United States followed efforts of
Ukrainian communities on both sides of the Atlantic and
negotiations between Washington and Moscow.
</TEXT>
