<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 2233EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-Iran-Iraq 1stLd-Writethru a0669 07-25 0788</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Iran-Iraq, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0669,0813</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Chief Says Iran-Iraq Truce Date Could Be Set Within 10 Days</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-14 UPDATE with upbeat comments by Perez de
Cuellar. U.S. envoy Walters. Picks up 6th graf pvs, Iran has ...
Edits to TRIM.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
said Monday night he is optimistic a truce date in the Iran-Iraq
war can be set within 10 days. Iraq said it would be out of all
newly won Iranian territory by Tuesday.
   The U.N. chief spoke on ``The MacNeil@Lehrer Newshour'' TV
program after saying earlier that he scheduled separate talks for
Wednesday with the foreign ministers of Iran and Iraq to pave the
way for a U.N.-supervised cease-fire in their 8-year-old war.
   The official Tanjug news agency in Belgrade reported Monday that
Yugoslavia accepted a U.N. call to contribute military officers to
monitor such a truce. Tanjug said about 250 U.N. truce observers
from throughout the world will be sent to Iran and Iraq once a
cease-fire was declared, but gave no specifics.
   Foreign Minister Tariq Aziz of Iraq asked to meet this week to
discuss a cease-fire, troop withdrawal, prisoner exchange and
formal peace negotiations. Iraq had sought face-to-face talks with
Iran.
   Perez de Cuellar said Monday he would not impose direct talks
between Iran and Iraq, but hoped both sides would agree to such
negotiations later.
   Aziz was expected at U.N. headquarters Tuesday.
   Appearing on the same broadcast as Perez de Cuellar were the
Iraqi U.N. ambassador, Ismat Kittani; the Iranian envoy, Mohammad
Ja'Afar Mahallati, and the U.S. ambassador to the United Nations,
Vernon Walters.
   Kittani said that by Monday midnight, ``all Iraqi forces will
have completed their withdrawal to our side of the internationally
recognized border. ... We have no intention of occupying and
holding Iranian territory for bargaining.''
   Mahallati said Iran ``is ready to immediately observe a
cease-fire'' and that he does not object to direct talks between
Iran and Iraq.
   He again charged that Iraq used chemical weapons in its latest
military offensive and Kittani refused to deny it.
   Walters said he viewed Kittani's announcement about withdrawing
from Iranian territory as a ``positive sign.''
   ``I think they (Iran and Iraq) both made a decision to go for
peace,'' the U.S. envoy said. ``Eight yars is a long time, you get
weary.''
   Walters said he was optimistic peace would result. The Iran-Iraq
war began in September 1980.
   ``I'm an old soldier. I know what war involves. I have seen the
bodies being put into body bags and that's when you really know
what war is about. And there have been almost a million bodies put
into body bags (in the Persian Gulf war) and that has an impact on
nations,'' Walters said.
   ``It's their coming generation that they're going to be losing
and I think that's why they have both come to the conclusion that
this is the time to stop.''
   Iran has said peace efforts could be jeopardized by Iraq's
latest offensive, intended to strengthen its position at the
bargaining table.
   Iran's foreign minister, Ali Akbar Velayati, arrived in New York
Monday and the Iranian Mission said he would meet Tuesday with the
president of the Security Council, Paulo Nogueira-Batista of Brazil.
   Perez de Cuellar said last week that ``the Iranians are not yet
prepared to have direct talks,'' so he would conduct shuttle
diplomacy, meeting each delegation separately as they go to his
38th-floor office.
   The new impetus to the peace process came July 18 when Iran
suddenly announced it would accept Security Council Resolution 598,
which demands an immediate cease-fire in the Persian Gulf war. Iran
had resisted for one year.
   But Iraq, which accepted the resolution a year ago, abruptly
called for immediate, face-to-face talks in New York before a truce
goes into effect.
   U.N. officials meanwhile warned that plans for U.N. truce
supervision could be jeopardized by the world body's financial
crisis, largely caused by U.S. arrears of $467 million _ two-thirds
of the total U.N. debt. The United States has been withholding its
legal U.N. contribution for years to compel the organization to
institute reforms.
   A U.N. technical team of military experts was bound for Tehran
to start working out details of a truce. It later will visit
Baghdad. A separate team arrived in Tehran to look into the
prisoners of war situation and later will visit Baghdad.
   At the State Department in Washington Monday, spokesman Charles
Redman reaffirmed U.S. willingness to talk with Iran, but said he
knew of no contacts planned with Velayati.
   The Security Council held closed-door consultations Monday on
Iran's protest against Iraq's latest alleged use of chemical
weapons. It adjourned without taking action.
</TEXT>
