<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-OilRig     07-25 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Oil Rig,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Rig Explosion Cuts Into Britain's Balance Of Payments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The offshore oil platform explosion that killed
167 people will cost Britain more than $500 million in lost energy
sales, the government announced Monday.
   In Aberdeen, Scotland, police said the body of one more worker
had been pulled from the North Sea on Monday, bringing the total
bodies recovered to 42.
   Energy Secretary Cecil Parkinson told Parliament that the fiery
blast that tore apart the Piper Alpha oil rig June 6 also knocked
five related platforms out of production.
   The shutdown of all six North Sea platforms cut Britain's oil
production 12 percent and natural gas production 1 percent,
Parkinson said.
   He said the five associated platforms could be back in service
in a few months, but Britain was not producing 180,000 barrels of
oil per day as the rigs stood idle. He estimated the cost in lost
energy sales at $516 million.
   Piper Alpha, 120 miles off Scotland's eastern coast, produced
120,000 to 130,000 barrels a day before it exploded in the worst
disaster in oilfield history.
   Parkinson told the 650-member House of Commons that the
government would accept any safety recommendations stemming from
investigations into the tragedy.
   The Los Angeles-based Occidental Petroleum Corp., which is the
operator and main owner of the platform, said four workers remain
hospitalized. The company said 125 men are still missing.
   Winds gusting to more that 40 mph Monday prevented Texas
troubleshooter Red Adair and his oil-fire experts from boarding the
stricken platform.
   They were still trying to tame two burning wellheads. Fires at
two other wells are being controlled by injecting sea water to
dampen the flames, Occidental said, and three other wells have been
plugged with cement.
</TEXT>
