<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Greece-US     07-25 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-US,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Negotiators Start Another Round of Bases Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KERIN HOPE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greek and American negotiators started
another round of talks Monday for a new U.S. bases agreement, just
12 days after the socialist government announced it was ending the
current accord.
   Government spokesman Sotiris Kostopoulos stressed that ``we're
not negotiating an extension of the existing agreement, but a new
one.''
   He also repeated Premier Andreas Papandreou's pledge that a new
agreement must be approved by a referendum before it can take
effect.
   The current five-year agreement expires in December this year.
On July 13, Greece formally notified the United States in writing
that the 1983 pact was ending and that the bases should be
dismantled by 1990.
   Western diplomats said the notification is considered a
formality that will not affect this week's talks.
   Negotiations have been slowed by Athens' insistence that a new
accord should express support for Greece in its dispute with Turkey
over the Aegean region.
   The American position is that an agreement on military bases
should not be broadened to include political backing for Greece.
   Papandreou and the governing Panhellenic Socialist Movement came
to power in 1981 on a platform that called for closure of the four
main American bases and 20 smaller installations, but later
modified its positions.
   The party indicated in a document published last week that the
bases may be allowed to stay. It said the party maintains a
long-term goal of shutting down the bases, but ``with a decisive
contribution to our national defense, a continuation of defense
cooperation is possible.''
   Greece receives $343 million yearly in U.S. military credits as
a form of rent for the bases.
   About 3,500 U.S. servicemen are stationed in Greece, mostly at a
U.S. Air Force support base next to Athens airport and at another
Air Force facility on the island of Crete.
</TEXT>
