<2ND_LINE>AM-Skyscraper Fire,0187</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>^Hundreds Evacuated from Skyscraper; Sprinklers Quickly Douse Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of people were evacuated from lower
floors of the West Coast's tallest building Monday when an
electrical fire filled two floors and the atrium area with smoke,
officials said. The fire was quickly doused.
   There were no injuries in the blaze in the 76-story Columbia
Seafirst Center. Fire Department Lt. Herb Brooks said the fire was
reported about 12:15 p.m. and controlled 10 minutes later.
   Firefighters helped put out the blaze, but sprinklers did most
of the work, said Deputy Chief Rod Bower.
   A lack of sprinklers was cited as a factor in a fatal fire May 4
in another West Coast skyscraper, the 62-story First Interstate
Bank building in Los Angeles. One person died and 40 were injured
in that blaze.
   Bower said Monday's fire was believed to have been started by an
electrical short.
   Damage hadn't been estimated yet, but would be substantial,
Bower said. There was extensive damage to wiring between the third
and fourth floors as well as smoke damage, he said.
