<2ND_LINE>AM-Puerto Rico,0532</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Puerto Ricans Mark Anniversaries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VILLALBA, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dozens of people gathered on a
mountaintop in central Puerto Rico Monday for a quiet ceremony
marking the 10th anniversary of the police killing of two young
supporters of independence for Puerto Rico.
   Two other commemorative dates fell on Monday _ the 36th
anniversary of the signing of the constitution that established
Puerto Rico as a semi-autonomous U.. Commonwealth, and the 90th
anniversary of the U.S. military occupation of Puerto Rico in 1898.
   Young girls laid flowers and Puerto Rican flags on the spot
where Carlos Soto Arrivi, 18, and Arnaldo Dario Rosado, 24, were
shot on July 25, 1978, and speakers demanded that those responsible
for the deaths be brought to justice.
   ``We're here to demand that the Popular Democratic Party
government fulfill its promises to jail those officials of (former
Gov.) Carlos Romero Barcelo's government who covered up these
murders,'' said Carlos Gallisa, secretary-general of the Socialist
Party.
   Romero Barcelo of the pro-statehood New Progressive Party was
governor at the time of the killings. The Popular Democrats are now
in control.
   About 70 miles away, in the capital city of San Juan, an
estimated 50,000 people gathered in front of the seaside capitol
building for speeches, singing and dancing to mark the
constitution's 36th anniversary.
   A jubilant Gov. Rafael Hernandez Colon, who is seeking
re-election in November, spoke for 30 minutes about his
administration's achievements. Then he rolled up his shirt-sleeves
and leaped off the 12-foot-high stage into the waiting arms of
supporters and circulated through the crowd pressed around him.
   Four Air National Guard jets roared overhead in formation as
dozens of people stood on a hill across from the capitol, holding
up red, white and blue placards to form a Puerto Rican flag.
   Spain ceded Puerto Rico to the United States in 1898 after the
Spanish American War. Puerto Ricans are U.S. citizens with most of
the rights of their mainland counterparts except that in Puerto
Rico they cannot vote for president.
   Most islanders are divided between supporting the current
commonwealth status or statehood. About 5 percent voted in the last
election for the party that supports independence from the United
States.
   Rosado and Soto Arrivi were killed in a police ambush when they
went up to a remote mountain called Cerro Maravilla (Marvel
Mountain), purportedly to gain publicity for independence by
blowing up a transmitter.
   They were led there by a police informant, who has since been
assassinated by an underground group that said it was avenging the
two deaths.
   Police first said they killed the two in an exchange of gunfire,
but a Senate investigation later revealed that Rosado and Soto
Arrivi were shot at close range while on their knees after having
surrendered.
   Six policemen are serving long prison sentences for murder in
the killings and eight officers in all have been convicted of
perjury for lying to two federal grand juries.
   The killings are still under investigation. The Senate and a
specially appointed independent prosecutor are trying to find out
if government officials were involved in the cover-up.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
