<1ST_LINE>a i PM-Venice-Floods Adv02   07-25 0702</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Venice-Floods, Adv 02,0722</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tues PMs Aug. 2 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Venice Preparing to Test System to Protect It from Sea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRY LEONARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VENICE, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the sirroco blows up the Adriatic from
the deserts of Libya, Venice's lagoon swells up and spills into the
city. Sirens sound a mournful reminder: Venice is losing its
struggle with the environment.
   Even at the height of summer, gondoliers ply their trade over
murky green and often foul-smelling canals alive with algae
thriving on tons of raw sewage.
   But a group of scientists and engineers are finally preparing to
test the prototype of a system to protect Venice from the sea that
once protected it.
   After nearly four years of work and $700 million in costs, the
engineers in the fall will install at the Lido entrance to the
Venice lagoon the prototype of a mobile dike designed to stem the
flood tides that have troubled the city's past and threaten its
future.
   ``The goal of the project is to save Venice, to save the life of
the lagoon, to save the port, to save the historic city and the
economic life of its people,'' said Maurio Fabris, director of
public relations for the Venezia Nuova (New Venice) consortium.
   He said the consortium of 26 Italian companies is executing the
10-year, $4.4 billion-project to build a line of mobile dikes
across the lagoon's three entrances, shore up the sea walls and
islands, preserve the canals and restore the ecological balance in
the polluted lagoon.
   Venetians built their island city along 150 winding canals to
protect themselves from invaders. Now the threat comes from the sea
that once guarded them.
   High tides flood the city about 100 times a year, corroding
magnificent churches, monuments and the marble walls of elegant
villas.
   The consortium intends to stem the tides with the mobile dikes
strung across the bottom of the lagoon entrances. During flood
tides, Fabris said, engineers will raise the dikes, effectively
sealing the lagoon. Ships will be able to sail in and out through a
series of locks at the entrances.
   ``With the mobile system we will be able to decide at what point
and at what time we want to intervene,'' said Fabris.
   Flood tides are triggered by differences in atmospheric pressure
at either end of the Adriatic or by the sirocco wind blowing across
the Mediterranean and up the Adriatic, driving the sea water
northward toward Venice.
   Great flood tides were heavily destructive to Venice in 789, in
1268 and in 1280. In 1410, they killed close to 1,000 people. In
this century, the worst floods came in 1916, 1936, 1951 and in
1966, when high water caused an estimated $85 million damage.
   Venetians have struggled for centuries to protect the city from
its surroundings. These efforts have included building sea walls to
guard the littoral islands and several anti-silting projects.
   More recently they succeeded in stopping Venice from sinking,
after it had settled 4{ inches from 1926 to 1970, by banning
industrial use of underground water.
   Critics say the government and the new consortium have reacted
slowly to Venice's problems, that the city has been drowning in a
sea of bureacracy and empty talk.
   The consortium's Fabris responds that the law creating the
project requires that all the work be ``experimentally tested,
reversible if necessary and done in stages.''
   Scientists used satellite analysis and computer models to study
how their work will effect the problems of stagnation and erosion.
Scale models of the entire lagoon and the three entrances were
built at Italy's hydraulic experimental center in nearby Padua.
   In September, workers will install the prototype of one of the
56-foot-high, 66-foot-long mobile dikes for six to eight months of
tests.
   Fabris said the consortium will be ready to put the entire line
of dikes in place by 1992.
   He added that the tests indicate that engineers will be able to
help wash pollutants out of the lagoon.
   As part of the project, the government is also supposed to enact
laws restricting the dumping of industrial pollutants and the use
of agricultural pesticides that seep into the lagoon.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Tues PMs Aug. 2</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880725-0198 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 0741EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i PM-OldDamascus Adv03   07-25 0791</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Old Damascus, Adv 03,0818</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv03</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed PMs Aug. 3 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Syrians Seek to Save Damascus' Old City</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coppersmiths and carpenters still clatter
today at their ancient crafts along the ``Street called Straight,''
where the Bible says St. Paul was cured of blindness.
   Venders peddle vials of perfume beneath Roman columns near the
great 8th century Omayyed mosque. Stalls in the narrow market
streets still dazzle with spices, silver and silk in the city that
Saladin, scourge of the Crusaders, called home.
   Some of Damascus's old city survives, but it is in danger of
being swallowed by the sprawl of modern Syria.
   ``You can't imagine how important Damascus is, and how rich,''
said Afif Bahnassi, Syria's Director of Antiquities.
   He's one of about a dozen officials and experts named this year
to a committee charged with saving the flavor and heritage of this
ancient city, termed ``the Paradise of the Orient'' by the 12th
century Spanish traveller Ibn Jubayer.
   Busy streets now flank the old Roman walls, and mud-sided 19th
century neighborhoods nearby have fallen to highways and modern
housing needed for a growing metropolis of 3 million people.
   Even within the old walled city, ``we're afraid ... there's now
some opinion to remove the old houses,'' Bahnassi said in an
interview.
   The committee has set conditions on development and is working
to restore old neighborhoods. Bahnassi said it has asked owners to
restore their own buildings, and offers financial assistance for
those who need help.
   But he said it is difficult to find craftsmen skilled in the old
buildings' styles.
   ``We'd like to encourage the workers to be more interested in
the old systems,'' he said.
   Damascenes often refer to their city as the oldest still
inhabited, but its age is uncertain. Settlements excavated nearby
date to about 10,000 B.C.
   Damascus itself is referred to in Egyptian and other documents
dating back about 4,000 years, Bahnassi said.
   Arameans who migrated to the city from the deserts built a
temple to the god Haddad in about 1,000 B.C. The Romans used the
same site for their temple to Jupiter.
   Early Christians built a cathedral on the Roman foundations, and
elements of both remain in in the richly decorated Omayyed mosque,
Islam's oldest surviving monumental mosque.
   Among its shrines is one holding the head of John the Baptist,
revered by Moslems as well as Christians.
   According to Acts 9 in the New Testament, St. Paul, then Saul,
was stricken blind as he made his way to Damascus to persecute the
followers of Christ. He was taken to a house on the ``Street called
Straight,'' the account goes on. It says Ananias, a follower of
Christ, was instructed by a voice from Heaven to find Saul there
and cure him of his blindness.
   Nearly all the great empires of Middle Eastern history fought
over and conquered Damascus, whose oasis straddles three enduring
trade routes connecting Egypt, Arabia, Mesopotamia and Europe.
   Early Islamic authorities referred to Damascus' oasis as the
site of the Garden of Eden.
   ``The Gardens encircle it like the halo round the moon,'' Ibn
Jubayer wrote in the 12th century.
   Some say Cain slew Abel on the slopes of Mount Kassioun on the
city's Western edge, and placed Abraham's birthplace there.
   At the height of its glory under the Islamic Omayyed dynasty,
Damascus was the capital of an Arab empire that reached from Spain
to the edges of India.
   Yet despite its many wars, ``nobody in its history destroyed it
completely,'' said Harb Farzat, an historian at the University of
Damascus.
   The crowded streets and bazaars of the old city still conjure
images of medieval times. Upper stories project over the narrow
lanes, often nearly touching.
   Crumbling walls on some reveal the mud, wattle and wood
construction Ibn Jubayer noted in 1184, when Saladin used the city
as his capital during his successful campaign against the Crusaders
of Jerusalem.
   Ornate stone doorways open onto the luxurious marble floors and
fountains of restored Turkish baths, some dating to the 13th
century and still in use.
   Coffee houses hundreds of years old still serve thick, heavily
sugared Turkish coffee to men in Arab garb who puff at waterpipes
over games of backgammon.
   But Farzat, who was born in the city, said: ``When you've seen
Damascus a generation before, you can see how it has changed.''
   From a high-rise hotel window, he pointed at the sprawl of
concrete now covering the ghouta, the oasis gardens that led many
ancient authors to liken Damascus to paradise.
   The greatest loss, he said, was ``to destroy the ghouta, the
Paradise of Damascus. Now it's covered with buildings.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Wed PMs Aug. 3</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880725-0199 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 0745EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i PM-StalematedRefugees Adv04   07-25 0821</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stalemated Refugees, Adv 04,0846</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv04</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thurs PMs Aug. 4 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Refugees Await Outcome of Stalemated Polisario War</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NEJLA SAMMAKIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TINDOUF, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sea of faded-green tents has become
home for 165,000 refugees _ mostly women, children and old men _ of
a stalemated war in the desert of nearby Western Sahara.
   Four-color flags of the self-proclaimed Sahrawi Arab Democratic
Republic flutter in the hot wind, over banners and grafitti
proclaiming the republic's slogan: ``The Entire Homeland or
Martyrdom.''
   The United Nations and international relief organizations have
been feeding and housing the refugees for more than a decade.
   The refugees wait here in Algeria for something to happen in the
war between Morocco and the Marxist-led Polisario guerrilla
movement for control of the Western Sahara, formerly Spanish Sahara.
   The Algeria-backed Polisario movement set up the Sahrawi
republic in 1976 after Spain turned Western Sahara over to Morocco
and Mauritania _ the latter has since withdrawn.
   Although the Sahrawi republic won diplomatic recognition from
more than 70 countries, mostly in the Third World, it has been
unable to gain a permanent foothold in the mineral-rich territory.
   The war has reached a stalemate and the guerrillas now talk of a
compromise settlement, but prospects seem distant and sporadic
fighting continues.
   Polisario officials contend the refugees in camps near this
Algerian oasis represent virtually the entire population of the
disputed territory.
   Spain held the Western Sahara until 1975, mainly to protect the
nearby Spanish Canary Islands. Little effort was made to develop
the wilderness, an area about the size of Colorado. Spanish
colonial records indicate the territory had a population of only
75,000 when Spain pulled out.
   At least 50,000 now live under Moroccan rule, frequently
proclaiming their loyalty to Morocco's King Hassan II.
   Morocco maintains that more than three-fourths of the Tindouf
refugees are not from Western Sahara but from neighboring
Mauritania, Niger, Mali and other impoverished countries on the
fringes of the Sahara Desert.
   Arabic-speaking Moslems, they originally were nomads, herding
goats and camels over unmarked boundaries, often not even aware
which country they were in.
   Mahmoud Hussein, a high-school pupil studying in Algiers, spoke
of the culture shock he experiences in traveling between the dual
worlds of modern Algiers and his family tent near Tindouf.
   ``I live in Algiers nine months of the year and I hate it and
long for my family,'' he said, sitting recently in the brightly
decorated tent beside his younger sister, Habiba. ``Then when I
come here for the three months of the summer, I'm dying to return.''
   He shares his perplexity with hundreds of young people who
travel to universities in Cuba or Spain.
   Polisario officials have set up a system to prevent loss of a
national and cultural identity among the young and to reinforce
their motivation to fight.
   ``The young teach the old how to read and write,'' said Mohammed
Mahmoud, a school teacher. ``The old teach them history and
tradition so as to enforce their sense of identity.''
   From age 9, the children also receive basic military training in
preparation for automatic conscription after high school of boys
who don't go on to university.
   Tindouf, a military zone, is 1,000 miles southwest of Algiers.
   The refugee camps begin about two miles west of Tindouf, their
rows of canvas tents and adjacent stone kitchens spread in clusters
over the stark landscape.
   At a camp hospital, Dr. Khadigetto Alawi said she had just
returned from five years of medical training in Havana, Cuba. She
said she and the other hospital staff receive no salaries.
   Polisario officials said no one receives any pay, including the
16,000-man guerrilla army and 70,000 officials. A few raise goats
and sheep for their own use, they said.
   A woman who identified herself as Humayed welcomed a group of
visiting reporters into the tent she shares with six women and
children of her family. She said their menfolk were ``at the
front'' 120 miles away.
   ``The women have an important role while the men are away at
war,'' said a Roman Catholic priest who goes by the name Father
Gonzales and works for the Caritas relief organization.
   ``They marry young, so as to have many children. And they also
undergo military training themselves. We try to teach them the
importance of mother-child care. They concentrate a lot on
preventive medicine.''
   A Polisario official said it is expected that young war widows
remarry quickly in order to maintain population growth. Ghalouha
el-Salm, a war widow-bride, said she has spent the nine years since
she lost her husband rearing a daughter but now is marrying again.
   ``I have to continue having children,'' she said, explaining
that it was a ``national'' requirement.
   Most of the women said they long to return to the Western Sahara
and its cool Atlantic breezes when the war is over.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Thurs PMs Aug. 4</NOTE>
</DOC>
