<1ST_LINE>a i PM-Jamaica-Caribbean Adv05   07-25 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jamaica-Caribbean, Adv 05,0490</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv05</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs Aug. 5 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>U.S. Drug Policy Angers Caribbean Allies</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Jamaica-Marijuana, b0281</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting to CORRECT release date at end</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HELEN J. SIMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. JOHN'S, Antigua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration's crackdown
on drug trafficking is upsetting U.S. allies in the Caribbean. They
complain the United States is maligning their leaders and
encroaching on their sovereignty.
   ``It's just unsettling to people to hear that their leaders have
been charged in a court in America when anyone who knows anything
about justice knows these cases will never come up for a hearing,''
said Prime Minister Eugenia Charles of Dominica. ``It's not only
wrong, its incomprehensible.''
   The issue came up at a recent meeting of the leaders of 13
former and current British colonies in the Caribbean Community
(Caricom), in Antigua-Barbuda.
   The young parliamentary democracies, most of which gained
independence over the past 25 years, drafted a letter to President
Reagan protesting U.S. drug policy in the region.
   The contents of the letter were not disclosed, but it was
believed to have focused on U.S. investigations of government
leaders in the Caribbean, as well as Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega,
the Panamanian strongman.
   Sir Lynden Pindling, prime minister of the Bahamas, is under
investigation by a Florida grand jury for alleged drug-related
offenses. He has denied any connection with the drug trade.
   At the Caricom summit, Pindling assailed the United States for
what he called its ``ideologically motivated, interventionist''
policies.
   In March, Col. Jean-Claude Paul of Haiti was indicted by a
federal grand jury for allegedly conspiring to import cocaine into
the United States. Paul, a key figure in Haiti's army, denied any
involvement.
   In May, a U.S. Senate subcommittee heard testimony by a
convicted drug trafficker that linked Prime Minister Edward Seaga
of Jamaica with payoffs. An incensed Seaga, whose marijuana
eradication program is the most comprehensive in Jamaica's history,
filed a formal complaint with the State Department, which later
said the testimony was unsubstantiated and baseless.
   ``People are concerned with the reputation of individuals,''
said Prime Minister Manuel Esquivel of Belize. ``I'm referring to
Senate witnesses that are free to commit libel ... and those people
who are libeled have no protection or recourse.''
   Deputy Prime Minister Lester Bird of Antigua accused the Reagan
administration of exporting its battle against drugs to win votes
for Republicans in November.
   ``The domestic imperatives of an election year in America have
forced certain people ... to step beyond what is acceptable in
terms of ... the sovereignty of a country,'' he said.
   Prime Minister A.N.R. Robinson of Trinidad-Tabago suggested that
countries work out ways to bring offenders to justice and ensure
that ``individuals are not just slandered and characters
assassinated ... or that countries should use the judicial process
for political ends.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Friday August 5</NOTE>
</DOC>
