<NOTE>$Adv31</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, July 31</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Sunday, July 31, the 213th day of 1988. There are 153
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On July 31, 1777, the Marquis de Lafayette, a 19-year-old French
nobleman, was made a major-general in the Continental Army after
offering his help to the rebelling American colonies. Lafayette
later played a rle in the British defeat at Yorktown.
   On this date:
   In 1498, Christopher Columbus discovered the island of Trinidad.
   In 1556, St. Ignatius of Loyola, the founder of the Society of
Jesus, died in Rome.
   In 1875, the 17th president of the United States, Andrew
Johnson, died in Carter Station, Tenn., at the age of 66.
   In 1948, President Harry S. Truman helped dedicate New York
International Airport at Idlewild Field. (The airport was later
renamed John F. Kennedy International Airport.)
   In 1953, Sen. Robert A. Taft of Ohio, known as ``Mr.
Republican'' for his conservative philosophy, died in New York at
the age of 63.
   In 1964, the American space probe Ranger VII transmitted
pictures of the moon's surface.
   In 1972, Democratic vice-presidential candidate Thomas Eagleton
withdrew from the ticket with George McGovern following disclosures
that Eagleton had once undergone psychiatric treatment.
   In 1981, a 7-week-old major league baseball strike ended.
   In 1981, the leader of Panama, Gen. Omar Torrijos, was killed in
a plane crash.
   In 1982, 46 children and seven adults were killed when two buses
and several cars collided on a highway near Beaune, France.
   In 1984, the U.S. men's gymnastics team won the team gold medal
at the Los Angeles Summer Olympics in a major upset over the
Chinese team.
   Ten years ago: A gunman shot his way into the Iraqi Embassy in
Paris, holding eight hostages for several hours before
surrendering. As the gunman was being led away by French police,
embassy guards opened fire, killing a policeman. The police
returned fire, killing one of the guards.
   Five years ago: President Reagan's special envoy to Central
America, Richard Stone, met in Bogota, Colombia, with a leader of
El Salvador's left-wing rebels, then flew to El Salvador to brief
President Alvaro Magana.
   One year ago: Iranian pilgrims and riot police clashed in the
Moslem holy city of Mecca in Saudi Arabia, resulting in the deaths
of some 400 people, according to the Saudi government, which blamed
the Iranians for the violence.
   Today's birthdays: Economist Milton Friedman is 76. Sportscaster
Curt Gowdy is 69. Actor Don Murray is 59. Actress France Nuyen is
49. Actress Susan Flannery is 45. Actress Geraldine Chaplin is 44.
Tennis player Evonne Goolagong Cawley is 37.
   Thought for today: ``The true meaning of religion is ... not
simply morality, but morality touched by emotion.'' _ Matthew
Arnold, English author, poet and critic (1822-1888).
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
