<2ND_LINE>BC-History, Adv01,0553</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv01</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday, Aug. 1</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eds: ``Tempestt'' in 22nd graf is cq.
^Today in History</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Monday, Aug. 1, the 214th day of 1988. There are 152
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On Aug. 1, 1873, inventor Andrew S. Hallidie successfully tested
a cable car he had designed for the city of San Francisco. The car,
pulled along by an underground cable, traveled down Clay Street
between Jones and Kearny, first in a private test, then in a public
demonstration.
   On this date:
   In 1774, British scientist Joseph Priestley succeeded in
isolating oxygen from air.
   In 1790, the first United States census was completed, showing a
population of nearly 4 million people in 13 states that included
the regions of four future states.
   In 1834, an Emancipation Bill outlawed slavery throughout the
British empire.
   In 1876, Colorado was admitted to the union as the 38th state.
   In 1907, the forerunner of the U.S. Air Force was established by
the Army as an Aeronautical Division.
   In 1914, Germany declared war on Russia at the onset of World
War I.
   In 1944, an uprising broke out in Warsaw, Poland, against Nazi
occupation forces. (The revolt collapsed after two months.)
   In 1946, the Atomic Energy Commission was created.
   In 1957, the United States and Canada reached an agreement to
create the North American Air Defense Command (NORAD).
   In 1966, 25-year-old Charles Joseph Whitman shot and killed 15
people at the University of Texas before he was slain by police.
   In 1975, the 35-nation summit in Helsinki, Finland, concluded
with the signing of an accord dealing with European security, human
rights and East-West contacts.
   In 1976, the Summer Olympics in Montreal ended.
   In 1977, Francis Gary Powers, the former U-2 reconnaisance pilot
captured by the Soviet Union in 1960, was killed in the crash of a
helicopter he flew for Los Angeles television station KNBC.
   In 1981, the rock music cable TV channel MTV made its debut.
   Ten years ago: Pete Rose of the Cincinnati Reds, who had tied
the National League record of hitting in 44 consecutive games, saw
his streak end in a game against the Atlanta Braves.
   Five years ago: Responding to criticism from feminists and
minority groups, President Reagan defended his record on women's
and civil rights issues before the American Bar Association in
Atlanta, and denounced as ``hogwash'' charges he had compromised
the Civil Rights Commission.
   One year ago: Iranians attacked the Saudi Arabian and Kuwaiti
embassies in Tehran as word spread of the rioting in Mecca, Saudi
Arabia, the day before that had claimed the lives of some 400
people, most of them Iranian pilgrims.
   Today's birthdays: Actor Arthur Hill is 66. Actor-director
Geoffrey Holder is 58. Composer-lyricist Lionel Bart is 58.
Actor-comedian Dom DeLuise is 55. Fashion designer Yves St. Laurent
is 52. Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., is 51. Rock musician Jerry
Garcia is 46. Actor Giancarlo Giannini is 46. Actress Tempestt
Bledsoe is 15.
   Thought for today: ``The only things that evolve by themselves
in an organization are disorder, friction and malperformance.'' _
Peter Drucker, Austrian-born American writer, consultant and
educator.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
