<NOTE>$Adv02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tuesday, Aug. 2</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Tuesday, August 2, the 215th day of 1988. There are 151
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On August 2, 1876, frontiersman ``Wild Bill'' Hickok was shot
from behind and killed while playing poker at a saloon in Deadwood,
S.D. The man who shot Hickok, Jack McCall, was later hanged. (When
he died, Hickok was clutching two aces and two eights _ a
combination now known as the ``Dead Man's Hand.'')
   On this date:
   In 1776, members of the Continental Congress began to attach
their signatures to the Declaration of Independence.
   In 1921, opera singer Enrico Caruso died in Naples, Italy.
   In 1923, the 29th U.S. president, Warren G. Harding, died in San
Francisco.
   In 1927, President Calvin Coolidge issued a statement to
reporters: ``I do not choose to run for president in 1928.''
   In 1934, German President Paul von Hindenburg died, paving the
way for Adolf Hitler's complete takeover.
   In 1939, Albert Einstein signed a letter to President Franklin
D. Roosevelt that urged the United States to begin an atomic
weapons research program.
   In 1939, the Hatch Act was passed, forbidding federal civil
service employees from taking an active part in political campaigns.
   In 1943, Navy Lt. John F. Kennedy became a war hero by rescuing
members of his crew after their PT boat was sheared in two by a
Japanese destroyer.
   In 1945, leaders of the United States, Soviet Union and Britain
concluded the Allied conference at Potsdam.
   In 1985, 137 people were killed when a Delta Air Lines jumbo jet
crashed as it attempted to land at Dallas-Fort Worth International
Airport.
   In 1986, Roy M. Cohn, the controversial New York City trial
attorney, died at Bethesda Naval Hospital of cardiac arrest and
complications from the AIDS virus.
   Ten years ago: France expelled three Iraqi embassy guards
accused of killing a French police officer during a gunfight that
erupted as officers were leading away a gunman who had held
hostages at the embassy two days earlier.
   Five years ago: The U.S. House of Representatives voted 338-90
to designate the third Monday in January a federal holiday in honor
of civil rights leader Martin Luther King Jr.
   One year ago: More than a million people gathered in Tehran,
joining in calls for the overthrow of the sheiks of Saudi Arabia,
where hundreds of Iranian pilgrims died two days earlier in rioting
in the Moslem holy city of Mecca.
   Today's birthdays: Actress Myrna Loy is 83. Actor Gary Merrill
is 74. Actress Beatrice Straight is 70. Former Sen. Paul Laxalt,
R.-Nev., is 66. Actor Carroll O'Connor is 64. Actor Peter O'Toole
is 56. Actress Joanna Cassidy is 44.
   Thought for today: ``Everyone is necessarily the hero of his own
life story.'' _ John Barth, American author.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
