<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 1350EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv26   07-25 0584</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 26,0597</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 26</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Tuesday July 26</NOTE>
<HEAD>Only the Numbers Add Up</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Like good comedians, certain investment analysts
never run out of material.
   As one respected member of that fraternity observed earlier this
month, they followed the monetarists in the early 1980s, switched
to oil-watching in 1985 and jumped to commodities last year.
   ``And now _ drumroll please _ it is the meteorologists,''
observes Lucinda Mezy, director of equity research PNC Financial
Corp., a bank-holding company based in Philadelphia.
   The drought, that is, has developed brand new commentaries on
where the economy is headed. Billions of words have come from
brokerage houses on what the drought means for food prices, and
therefore for stocks.
   The political activities of 1988 provide myriad variations for
commentaries on interest rates, inflation, stock prices and
investor confidence. Each poll, whether or not it shows changes, is
reason again for further commentary.
   The Iran-Iraq affair already has been worked into forecasts by
analysts who could not think of anything more to say about
Nicarauga and the rest of Central America, and by bulls who had run
out of things to say about glasnost.
   Fallback resources include the emergence of China as an
industrial power, the amount of money in circulation, the budget
and trade deficits, the dollar, the possibility of inflation or
higher interest rates and Third World debt.
   Increasingly, analysts analyze analysts, producing one of the
oddest of all analyses, one that states the stock market is about
to rise when the majority of analysts are bearish, and is set to
fall when they turn bullish.
   There is an open pit mine, ready to be worked at any time, in
analyzing the disposition of investors. Do they have confidence? Do
they have money? Will they buy cars and appliances? Will they save?
Will they buy junk bonds?
   Government provides enough material, often in controversial
form, to keep armies of analysts computing and dissecting. Lists of
upcoming government economic announcements has become a regular
feature of brokers' letters.
   A rise or fall in housing starts is good for hundreds of words
on the consequences to securities. Inflation and interest rates,
jobless statistics, factory capacity, imports, exports, debt,
deficits all go into the mix.
   Still, without these events, institutions and subjects there
would hardly be a drought of material on which to comment. Always,
there is the mine of statistical material that can be dug up and
massaged by computer.
   That resource was well used and thoroughly abused in the weeks
and months immediately following the securities crash of last
October, the most common of the analyses producing statistics
likening it to the Great Crash of 1929.
   It mattered little that events failed to prove that 1987 was
1929 all over again; it simply provided more material for analysis
on why the two years differed. In themselves, differences of
opinion are fodder for analysis.
   How all this helps investors is difficult to perceive, but it is
easy enough to see how it helps those who sell securities. It keeps
customers talking. It maintains interest. It provides material for
sales calls.
   But almost if not utterly lost in the mountain of commentary is
the matter of accuracy. It is then that the words are seen for what
they are worth. In investing, those words just do not add up. Only
the numbers do.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Tues July 26</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880725-0210 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 1454EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i AM-Chile-Journalist Adv01   07-25 0903</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile-Journalist, Adv 01,0929</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv01</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday AMs, Aug. 1, or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Prize-Winning Chilean Journalist Lives with Fear and Harassment</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Before Monica Gonzalez goes to the United
States in September to receive a prize for courageous reporting
she'll have to get permission from a Chilean court.
   Pending against her are charges of criminally slandering
President Augusto Pinochet and the armed forces he commands.
   By law she must get approval to go abroad, but she brushes that
aside as just a minor annoyance compared to periodic arrests, two
stints in prison and daily death threats in the four years since
she took on what she calls ``the holy trinity'' _ Pinochet, his
family and the military.
   Her articles accusing Pinochet and his right-wing government of
abuse of power were cited by Harvard University's Nieman Foundation
in awarding her this year's Louis M. Lyon Prize. It praised her
``courage in reporting objectively and honestly ... despite the
government's efforts to silence her.''
   She plans to travel to Boston to accept the award Sept. 15, but
with a certain chagrin.
   ``There are lots of (Chilean) journalists who are facing legal
charges, but most aren't as famous as I,'' Mrs. Gonzalez, 38, said
in an interview. ``This bothers me a lot sometimes.''
   According to the local Roman Catholic Church's human rights
office, more than 30 journalists face criminal slander charges
lodged by the government.
   They include Mrs. Gonzalez' boss, Juan Pablo Cardenas, director
of the leftist magazine Analisis. He was convicted of offending the
armed forces and is serving 541 nights in a jail cell. He is at
liberty during the daytime.
   Pinochet cites the existence of Analisis and several other
opposition publications as proof that Chile has freedom of the
press. But according to Mrs. Gonzalez, ``There's a very high cost.
It's a cost you pay every day.''
   She said her telephone rings constantly with death threats, that
cars full of armed men regularly park outside her home, that a dead
cat was once tossed into her yard.
   ``Certainly I'm afraid.'' she said. ``I'm afraid they'll kill
me. But I've made a choice. I've taken a path of no return.''
   The choice was made in late 1983, she said, when she began
working for another opposition magazine, Cauce. At the time, a wave
of anti-Pinochet protests obliged the government to somewhat relax
its strict control of the news media.
   In early 1984, the magazine published the first of a series of
investigative reports by Mrs. Gonzalez alleging corruption by
Pinochet and members of his family and brutal human rights abuse by
the military. The articles, which presented documentation and
detail, established her reputation as one of the country's best
opposition journalists and shattered a powerful taboo.
   ``We broke a sacrosanct rule that existed in the opposition
press: don't mention Pinochet, his family or the armed forces. This
is the holy trinity,'' she said.
   In the years since, Mrs. Gonzalez has been arrested 10 times and
imprisoned twice in connection with her reporting.
   Her first imprisonment was in July 1984. She said she was put in
a small, exposed cell in a maximum-security punishment block
occupied by about 20 common criminals who had led a prison riot
three months earlier. Many still wore bandages on their wounds.
   She was the first woman they had seen since being isolated, and
regularly beaten, after the riot, she said. They filled the hall
outside her cell, screaming and pressing against the bars while
they exposed themselves and performed obscene acts.
   The bars were thin, and she feared they would cave in.
   ``It went on all night long,'' she said. ``I didn't think I was
going to be able to stand it. It was very terrible.''
   The next morning, at her tearful insistence, she was moved to a
section for woman political prisoners. She spent six days there
before being released.
   She would return in October 1987, for 22 days, after publishing
an interview with an opposition leader, Andres Zaldivar, who
sharply criticized Pinochet.
   The case sent chills through the Chilean jouralistic community
and prompted denunciations from press organizations around the
world. Although the interview was published in textual,
question-and-answer form, Mrs. Gonzalez _ and not Zaldivar _ was
charged with slandering the president. Government prosecutors said
she was responsible because she served as the vehicle for his
remarks.
   The case remains pending, as do two others, in which she is
accused of slandering a military prosecutor and the armed forces in
general. Five previous cases against her have ended in acquittal.
   She said she considers her most important story a series of
interviews in late 1984 with a deserter from the secret police who
recounted the torture and killing of 15 leftists. Some were old
friends of hers, she said.
   In seeking confirmation of the deserter's tale, she sought the
help of a human rights activist, Jose Parrada, and a Communist who
survived detention by the secret police, Manuel Guerrero.
   Parrada and Guerrero, along with a third man, Santiago Nattino,
were found dead with their throats slashed in March 1985.
   ``Why they let me live, I don't know,'' Mrs. Gonzalez said.
   ``Here they punish journalists who make terrible denunciations:
murders, torture, disappearances, corruption. But they don't
investigate the actions being denounced. That's hard for me to
accept.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Mon AMs Aug. 1</NOTE>
</DOC>
