<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 1340EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--TVWeek Adv07   07-25 0933</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--TV Week, Adv07,0950</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 07</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Aug. 7</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carroll O'Connor is quick to point out that
much has changed in the South since the filming of the 1967 movie,
``In the Heat of the Night,'' starring Rod Steiger and Sidney
Poitier.
   In the new NBC series based on the movie, O'Connor stars as Bill
Gillespie, police chief of the small Mississippi town of Sparta,
the role which earned Steiger an Academy Award as best actor. On
TV, Howard Rollins co-stars as Virgil Tibbs, whose appointment as
Sparta's black chief of detectives causes a stir in the Deep South
town.
   ``I'm playing this different from Rod,'' says O'Connor, the man
best remembered as Archie Bunker in ``All in the Family.'' ``Rod
played it as Southern police chiefs were in 1967. He deserved his
Oscar. Remember the news pictures coming out of the South at that
time, with the dogs and the fire hoses. But this is 1988. A lot has
happened in the South since then. The old attitude no longer works.
   ``So the chief is fundamentally still the same, but he knows he
has to make accommodations. It's against the law to discriminate
against black people and Bill Gillespie is going to make sure the
law is obeyed. He's a man in conflict. He learned racism at his
mother's knee, but he lives by the law and he respects the law.''
   O'Connor is holding court at a table designated by a brass
plaque as ``Carroll's Corner,'' in the Ginger Man, the Beverly
Hills restaurant he has owned for the past 11 years in partnership
with actor Patrick O'Neal. There's a telephone nearby and people
stop by to speak to him. Some wave from the sidewalk outside.
   He's wearing a light-colored summer suit and a bow tie. His hair
is snow white, and his eyes, behind his glasses, are a piercing
blue. He picks up a pipe and lights up before continuing:
   ``In the future we're not going to concentrate so much on the
crime. You can find that on every police show. We want to show what
crime does to the community and what it does to the policemen, and
how two men from very different backgrounds feel about it. The
white police chief and the black detective have fundamental
differences. They have different sentiments, and although crime
affects them in different ways they can work together.
   ``I think that eluded us in the first outing, but I think we'll
get it this time. People will say it's right on, which is what they
said about `All in the Family.'''
   The first season of the show was filmed entirely on location in
Hammond, La. But there is talk that the company may go to Northern
California for the fall season to save money.
   O'Connor says he found the people of Hammond cooperative and the
city seemed to him to be fully integrated. Nancy, and their son,
Hugh, joined him there. Hugh also works in his father's restaurant.
   He says that when he completed ``All in the Family'' in 1983 he
wasn't looking for a new series.
   ``I wanted to go to New York and do another play,'' he says. ``I
did one called `Brothers' and it was a miserable flop. Then I did
another, `Homefront,' and it was a flop, but not a miserable flop.
Both plays appealed to the audience but if you don't get the critic
for The New York Times your show folds. What you do is end up
putting on a play for just one man.''
   He also starred in a CBS movie called ``Brass,'' in which he
played the chief of detectives in New York City. He says it was not
a pilot, but concedes that any TV movie with a star is a de facto
pilot. He also starred in the NBC movie ``The Father Clements
Story.''
   ``I didn't do any pilots,'' he says, ``although we talked about
some. I was all set to do a show with ABC. I was going to be a kind
of old-time OSS or CIA man who's put in charge of a Russian
defector. We were to have various adventures together. But they
gave me a producer who'd had five flops in a row. I said no and
they gave me a month to find someone we'd all be satisfied with. I
suggested a couple of guys. That was the last I ever heard from
them.''
   O'Connor is surprised at how fast his latest series came
together.
   His first series, ``All in the Family,'' bounced from network to
network and went through several pilots before CBS finally put it
on the air in January 1971. It lasted for 12 years.
   This time, he says, ``I got a call from Freddie Silverman and he
asked me to meet him.'' Silverman was head of programming at CBS
when ``All in the Family'' went on the air. He later became
president of ABC Entertainment, then NBC, and currently is a
successful independent producer. His other shows include NBC's
``Matlock,'' ``Jake and the Fatman,'' now on standby at CBS, and
the ``Perry Mason'' movie series.
   ``We met right here, at this table,'' says O'Connor. ``He said
NBC is ready to do it. `If you'll do it, they'll do it.' I've had a
lot of people talk to me about series. It usually takes years.
Talk, talk, talk. So here is a producer who can put a deal together
in two weeks.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>END ADV</NOTE>
