<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--RecordReview Adv00   07-25 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Record Review, Adv 00,0340</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Review</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Temple of Low Men'' (Capitol) _ Crowded House
   
   Crowded House's ``Temple of Low Men'' may be the catchiest
depressing album you'll ever hear.
   The New Zealand trio, behind Neil Finn's sprightly Paul
McCartney-like melodies and some killer hooks, became one of pop
music's most gratifying success stories in 1987 with such hits as
``Something So Strong'' and ``Don't Dream It's Over.''
   But don't look for any silly love songs on the follow-up
``Temple of Low Men.'' Finn's a brooder, worrying about everything
from doomed relationships to his own success.
   Finn seems especially wary of love on this album's bookends. ``I
Feel Possessed'' describes a lover's spellbinding hold on him, but
the narrator is as much scared by the power as consumed by it. And
``Better Be Home Soon,'' addressed to an absent lover, is more a
threat than a plea.
   On ``Mansion in the Slums,'' Finn tells everyone who covets his
kind of success that it's not worth it.
   ``The taste of success only lasts you half an hour or less,''
Finn sings. He declares that he'd much rather have a trampoline
than an isolation tank in an obvious jibe at the music business's
most tortured success, Michael Jackson.
   Why bother listening to another rock star complaining his life's
a mess? Because's the music's almost unerringly pretty. ``Better Be
Home Soon'' is the kind of lovely ballad McCartney used to be able
to toss off in his sleep, and the acoustic guitar-based tune will
probably benefit commercially from the current singer-songwriter
boom.
   ``Never Be the Same'' and ``I Feel Possessed'' are also
particularly strong. There's nothing as instantly accessible as the
hits from the first album, but ``Temple of Low Men'' rewards
repeated listening.
   Imagine what Crowded House could do if Neil Finn were happy.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
</DOC>
