<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Glass, Adv 5-7,0896</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 5-7</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Aug 5-7 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Artists: Minimalism Triumphs for Philip Glass</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM KLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Minimalist composer Philip Glass says his
astonishing success in opera over the past decade heralds a return
to the spirit of the 1960s.
   ``I think idealism is something that is becoming acceptable
again, if I can put it that way, after a decade of materialism,''
he said.
   ``The idealism of the '60s, I believe that we're coming back to
that,'' he said. ``I think that young people are not all going to
be stockbrokers and lawyers.
   ``I think there's a reaction setting in against that kind of
materialism and lack of idealism. And in a way I think that's why
we're getting good audiences for these pieces.''
   Glass is probably ``the leading contemporary (opera) composer of
the day,'' said Rheinhard G. Pauly, a music professor and opera
historian at Lewis & Clark College in Portland, Ore.
   ``He is one of the few contemporary opera composers who has
really developed a strong following. It's unusual for contemporary
opera to be really successful.''
   Casting simple themes in shimmering repetition and gradual
change that fans find entrancing and detractors find stupefying,
Glass also has won acclaim in film, theater, dance and other
musical modes.
   In recent years the 51-year-old Baltimore native has
collaborated with singer Linda Ronstadt, songwriters Paul Simon and
Suzanne Vega, dance choreographer Twyla Tharp and stage
director-designer Robert Wilson.
   His recent film scores include ``Koyanisqatsi,'' ``Mishima'' and
the recently released ``Powaqqatsi.''
   Glass was 39 when his first opera, ``Einstein on the Beach,''
was performed at the Avignon Festival in France in 1976.
   His second, ``Satyagraha,'' an account of Mahatma Gandhi's
development of the tactic of passive resistance as a young lawyer
in South Africa, was commissioned by the Netherlands Opera and
performed in Rotterdam in 1980.
   ``Akhnaten,'' based on an ancient Egyptian pharaoh and first
performed in Stuttgart, Germany, in 1984, completed a trilogy on
``historical figures who changed the world through the power of
their ideas,'' Glass said.
   All have been sell-outs in U.S. performances and have been
recorded on the CBS Masterworks label.
   ``Philip Glass operas always sell well,'' said Speight Jenkins,
general director of the Seattle Opera.
   ``I have found it (`Satyagraha') to be the most satisfying of
the works,'' Jenkins said. ``I think Philip Glass may be writing
better music now, but I also think I have never heard a better text
with one of his operas.''
   In a recent interview during a visit to promote the Seattle
Opera production of ``Satyagraha'' in July, Glass said Gandhi's
``stark idealism ... is one of the reasons why I think younger
people are very drawn to this work. I think younger people tend to
be more idealistic than the older folks.
   ``Gandhi was a man who was an idealist to the end of his days.
He proved ... that idealism isn't something you outgrow. You don't
have to. It can be something you can carry with you all your life.
That, in itself, is an inspiration.''
   The Stuttgart Opera has scheduled performances of ``Einstein,''
``Satyagraha'' and ``Akhnaten'' on successive nights in 1990.
   ``I think of `Einstein' as being the modern, kind of
psychokinetic opera, the one that's amplified and full of energy,''
Glass said. ``It kind of goes with the idea of nuclear energy and
progressive ideas in science, right?
   ``I think of `Satyagraha' as the lyrical opera, which is all
flowing, melodic lines and choruses. There's something very gentle
about `Satyagraha.' It's a lyrical opera.
   ``I think of `Akhnaten' as the tragic opera of the three, a very
dark one, the one that, at a certain moment, you realize no one
gets out of here alive.'' His fourth opera, ``The Making of the
Representative From Planet 8'' with a libretto by Doris Lessing,
premiered in Houston on July 8. Performances are scheduled later
this year in England and the Netherlands. In the script,
civilization on another planet is threatened by an ice age.
   His next, ``The Palace of the Arabian Nights,'' is set for a
premiere next year in France and is based ``loosely on the stories
of the stories of the Arabian nights,'' Glass said.
   Last March the Metropolitan Opera gave him a commission for
``The Voyage,'' a three-part allegory based on the exploration of
Christopher Columbus. The premiere is set for October 1992, the
500th anniversary of the sailing of the Pinta, Nina and Santa Maria
in America.
   Opera ``is the medium of choice for me ... the one in which the
composer plays a primary function,'' Glass said.
   ``The theater is the director's house. The ballet is the
choreographer's house. The opera is the composer's house,'' he
said. ``I like that.''
   From commissioning to staging typically takes three years, he
said.
   ``It takes a year to plan it, a year to write it and a year to
build it,'' he said. ``You spend a lot of time involved with your
subject, so I am very careful about my subject matter ... they do
become part of your life.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Aug 5-7 and Thereafter</NOTE>
