<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Segal, Adv 5-7,1069</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 5-7</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Aug 5-7 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Books and Authors: ``Love Story'' Author Finds Acclaim With
``Doctors''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Erich Segal, the Brooklyn boy who went to Harvard,
taught classics at Yale and wrote ``Love Story,'' is still juggling
serious and popular writing in a leafy corner of London.
   He looks back on ``Love Story'' as a youthful Camelot, and
senses that with his latest novel, ``Doctors,'' he may finally
achieve the critical acclaim that has so far eluded him.
   At 51, he has temporarily given up the rigors of full-time
university teaching but remains a fellow at Oxford University's
Wolfson College. An occasional sports commentator, he dreams of
winning the over-60 category in the 1997 Boston marathon.
   ``I am today a writer who is lucky enough to have academic
privileges at Oxford,'' he says.
   Segal's fifth and most ambitious novel, ``Doctors,'' is the
first that did not draw on his own life. Instead it chronicles
members of the Harvard Medical School class of 1962, which included
several of his friends.
   He said he tried to tackle the subject of doctors and the
pressures they face with the passion of ``Love Story,'' his first
novel, and the scope of his last novel, ``The Class,'' a 25-year
fictional follow-up of his fellow Harvard graduates of 1958.
   ``For a long while I lived in gossip columns as Eric `Love
Story' Segal,'' he said in an interview.
   ``People would run up to me in airports and sing the first few
bars of the tune from the movie version. It's not such a bad thing.
If it had stopped there, I would have looked back on life as an
athlete looks back ... and say I was there once.''
   Instead, he moved on to such works as ``The Class'' and
``Doctors'' which, at 679 pages, is five times the length of ``Love
Story.'' Segal remarks: ``Publishers used to worry that my books
were too short. Now they're worrying that they're too long.''
   He doesn't feel he is an expatriate American writer. The
academic world is the same everywhere, he said, and with satellite
television and $168 fares to New York, America is never far away.
   ``In this day and age, if I need something from the Carnegie
Delicatessen, there's always the Concorde,'' he said, ``and it
never gets that bad.''.
   Segal's wife, Karen, is English and when Francesca, their
musically gifted 8-year-old daughter, started school, he decided it
was unfair to keep commuting between Yale and Oxford.
   But he hates Britain's weather and hopes to spend winters in
southern California and teach there when Francesca becomes a
teen-ager.
   Academics who have achieved popular success as writers include
British philosopher Iris Murdoch, American astronomer Carl Sagan
and Italy's Umberto Eco, a professor of semiotics.
   ``I only hope some day I'll reach the level of scholarship or
literary respectability that they've achieved,'' Segal said. ``It
gives me a goal to shoot for.''
   Segal speaks nine languages and has written a book on Roman
comedy and more than 50 articles on Greek tragedy, Latin poetry and
ancient athletics. But he has always found time to indulge his love
of pop literature.
   He wrote the Harvard Hasty Pudding Club show in 1958 and has
written or co-written several screenplays including The Beatles'
``Yellow Submarine'' in 1968.
   ``Love Story,'' his bittersweet tale of youthful love and death
which has sold more than 20 million copies in 33 languages since
publication in 1970, turned the unknown professor into an
international celebrity. The sequel, ``Oliver's Story,'' a 1977
best seller, was followed by ``Man, Woman and Child.''
   Although he was refused tenure at Yale in 1971 _ some say
jealous colleagues disdained his success _ Segal kept teaching and
writing. In 1981, he returned to Yale as a full professor, though
still without tenure, and retired in 1987.
   To critics who dismissed ``Love Story'' as fluff, he replies:
``Eighteen years later, when I find myself feeling guilty for all
that success and thinking `Love Story' was overrated, I pull out my
Encyclopedia Britannica and see myself listed as writing in the
tradition of the classic sentimental novelists, and then my ego
relights.
   ``It was my little Camelot and it can't be taken away. It was my
idyll.
   ``But fortunately, I got my second wind or second chance with
`The Class.' I had exhausted the possibilities of the sentimental
novel and I got into the saga business, which has vastly more raw
material.''
   ``The Class,'' a 1985 best seller, was Segal's first novel to
receive modest critical acclaim, winning literary prizes in France
and Italy. ``I actually thought `The Class' was the end, because
I'd written my life story into it, split apart,'' he said.
   He had qualms about writing ``Doctors,'' doubting his ability to
enter their world. He spent two years attending medical congresses,
talking to doctors and wandering through University College
Hospital in London weaing a white coat and a badge identifying him
as Dr. Segal.
   ``It says in little letters `professor of Latin,' so I could
walk the halls,'' said Segal, who has a doctorate in comparative
literature.
   Why doctors?
   ``Because they're very special,'' he said. ``They're the people
we fear, need, love and hate the most. ... And they are answerable,
so they think, only to God.''
   He says he set out to write a diatribe against unscrupulous
doctors, but met so many dedicated ones that he had to stop himself
from going the other way.
   An insomniac, Segal normally works from 4 a.m. to 5 p.m. without
leaving his desk. Then the slightly built athlete, who has
completed over 40 marathons, goes for a swim or a run.
   Segal says he is writing one more academic book, a history of
classical comedy, but his next novel depends on what happens to
``Doctors.''
   The first review, in Publishers Weekly, says the book addresses
``the gravest, most pressing issues facing doctors today and is
Segal's most skillfully written novel.''
   Segal, elated, says: ``That means I may be entering a phase of
respectability which I've always dreamed of.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Aug 5-7 and Thereafter</NOTE>
