<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--Newbury Adv5-7   07-25 0620</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Newbury, Adv 5-7,0636</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 5-7</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Aug 5-7 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Hit Songs Hurt His Career</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Songwriter Mickey Newbury says his
career suffered because of two of his best-known compositions:
``American Trilogy'' and ``Just Dropped In (To See What Condition
My Condition Was In).''
   Both songs, the 48-year-old writer-performer says, boxed him
into uncomfortable stereotypes, either as a patriot or a rocker.
   ``American Trilogy'' was a hit by Elvis Presley in 1973, and
``Just Dropped In'' was recorded by Kenny Rogers and the First
Edition in 1968.
   ``American Trilogy,'' a medley of ``Dixie,'' ``Battle Hymn of
the Republic'' and ``All My Trials,'' has been recorded or
performed by dozens of artists.
   ``It stopped me in my tracks for a few years,'' Newbury said in
an interview. ``The only thing I was getting asked to do was sing
the national anthem at football games and I didn't like it.''
   ``I did Bob Hope's Fourth of July show. You get a tag and it
stuck.''
   He says some people still come to his concerts to hear him
perform it.
   ``Hopefully, if I can get them in to see me because of that
song, they'll listen to something else I've done. It's the same
problem everybody has. For Jerry Reed and Ray Stevens, audiences
come in to hear their funny stuff but they have a serious side.''
   His reputation as a country music songwriter was undermined when
``Just Dropped In'' was taken as a song glorifying drug abuse.
   ``I was not taken seriously as a country songwriter for a
while,'' he recalled. ``It hurt me because of the insanity of the
music business. Everyone wanted to put you in a little pigeonhole.
   ``It was one of the first obvious anti-drug songs, yet it was so
controversial that some said it was detrimental. It was about a bad
acid trip. All the songs at that time were cloaked in metaphors
espousing the glory of hallucinogens. They talked about how
wonderful it was and how they open up your mind. It caused me to
write it. I knew it was not that way for everyone. It put some
people in the toilet.''
   Newbury, who now lives in Vida, Ore., has just released his 14th
album, ``Mickey Newbury in a New Age.''
   It's his first LP since 1981 and a kind of greatest hits album.
Yes, ``American Trilogy'' is on the disc, along with ``All My
Trials,'' ``San Francisco Mabel Joy'' and others.
   During his career he's also written ``Sweet Memories,'' a hit by
Andy Williams, and ``She Even Woke Me Up to Say Goodbye,'' which
has been recorded by dozens of performers. Joan Baez and Ray
Charles are just two of the other singers who have recorded his
songs.
   Newbury describes a good song as ``a good story. Something
someone can relate to. A lot of songwriters get better as they get
older, but they've already written about most of the interesting
things in their life that happened when they were young and it was
new.
   ``The whole process that drives you to write is to write that
perfect song. No songwriter ever feels he's written that perfect
song. Stephen Foster did it already with `Beautiful Dreamer' and
yet when he died, he had a piece of paper in his pocket that said
`dear hearts and gentle people.' He had already started on another
song.
   ``I think Don McLean's song `Vincent' is a perfect song and I
have not heard many perfect songs: ones so finely crafted that you
say, `I can't make a change.'''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Aug 5-7 and Thereafter</NOTE>
