<1ST_LINE>a a BC-EXP--How-FamilyDiseases Adv28   07-25 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EXP--How-Family Diseases, Adv 28,0323</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv28</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Thursday, July 28, and thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Get Family History of Diseases to Assess Future Risk</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People should be nosy about what Aunt Minnie
died of or what chronic diseases other relatives have had because
it may reveal inherited hazards in the family, a genetics expert
says.
   Questions about diseases in the family are not offensive if they
are framed as requests to help future generations, and ``you really
have an obligation to ask because it may be something that somebody
other than you is at risk for,'' said Judith Hall, professor of
medical genetics at the University of British Columbia in Vancouver.
   ``Older members have an obligation to pass along the information
they have,'' Hall said after a recent science writers conference
sponsored by the American Academy of Pediatrics.
   ``I think it's absolutely legitimate to ask for an autopsy
report,'' which can reveal inherited conditions such as
hemochromatosis, a buildup of iron in the tissues that can
complicate other diseases, she added.
   For the family history, questions should focus on causes of
death, chronic illnesses, reasons for hospitalization, long-term
medication or chronic medical care before age 50, cancer before age
60, cancer in both breasts, diseases that killed more than one
family member, and heart attacks or strokes before age 50.
   The information should be passed on to relatives and the family
doctor.
   Every person carries five to eight genes that can increase the
risk of disease in offspring if the other parent has a
corresponding genetic defect, Hall said. For example, one in 20
Caucasians carries the defective gene that causes cystic fibrosis;
one in 10 blacks carries the sickle cell anemia gene.
   She also said half of all admissions to pediatric hospitals
involve conditions with an inherited predisposition, such as kidney
disease, cancer, diabetes and heart abnormalities.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for July 28</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880725-0240 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 0731EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   07-25 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0512</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines says it will cut 4,000 jobs, or 12
percent of its work force, and eliminate service to 14 cities Aug.
31 in a continuing effort to cut costs and streamline its
operations.
   The announcement came Friday in the seventh month of bitter
contract talks between Eastern and the machinists' union, which is
seeking raises for 10,000 workers at Eastern. The carrier is
seeking $161 million in pay cuts and other concessions.
   The Miami-based airline also is seeking $69 million in
concessions from its pilots union, which began formal contract
talks with the company Friday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer prices rose at a moderate annual rate
of 4.2 percent in June, with the effects of the Farm Belt drought
showing up clearly only in poultry and egg prices.
   The Labor Department said Friday retail prices overall rose just
0.3 percent last month.
   Offsetting increases on grocery shelves were slight declines in
energy and clothing costs.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A surge in quarterly income tax payments by
businesses and individuals gave the federal government a rare $9.5
billion surplus in June, leaving the cumulative red ink for the
first nine months of the fiscal year below last year's levels, the
government said.
   In its report Friday, the Treasury Department said federal
spending last month totaled $89.9 billion, a 7.7 percent increase
over June 1987. However, revenue surged 19.8 percent above last
year's level to $99.3 billion.
   It was only the third surplus posted since the fiscal year began
in October.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan has moved to
impose trade sanctions on Brazil for denying patent protection to
U.S. and other foreign pharmaceutical firms.
   The president's action Friday means the United States will hold
hearings to determine what penalties to impose for Brazil's alleged
trade infractions.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the hearings would
determine what products would be subject to sanctions.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The drought in the United States
is turning into a multibillion-dollar boon for farmers in
economically distressed Argentina and Brazil, agricultural experts
say.
   While U.S. crops wilt under the worst drought conditions since
the Dust Bowl, recently harvested crops of soybeans and winter
wheat in Argentina and Brazil are fetching the highest export
prices in years.
   Many of Argentina's 450,000 farmers are planting as much as
possible to cash in on record prices for soybeans.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar-strapped government of Peru ordered
state mines to sell their silver to the Central Bank and offered
private miners more money for the metal in an effort to boost the
nation's faltering economy.
   Agriculture Minister Remigio Morales Bermudez said Friday the
government may use the silver to build up a $750 million reserve to
import food.
   The government's decree said the silver is earmarked to boost
Peru's foreign reserves, which have declined dramatically.
</TEXT>
