<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   07-25 0538</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0559</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polaroid Corp.'s stock jumped in heavy trading
amid speculation that a ``white knight'' may emerge to compete with
a bid that values the instant camera company at more than $2
billion.
   Polaroid rose 87{ cents a share Friday to finish at $40.75 in
composite New York Stock Exchange trading, which was slightly above
the $40-a-share Roy E. Disney offered on Wednesday through Shmrock
Holdings Inc.
   Nearly 2.6 million shares traded hands, more than three times
Polaroid's normal daily volume.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cadbury Schweppes PLC said it would sell its U.S.
operations to Hershey Foods Corp. in a deal that will allow the
Pennsylvania company to make and market the popular Peter Paul
Mounds and Almond Joy candy bars and other confectionery products.
   Under terms of their agreement Friday, Hershey will acquire
Cadbury's three U.S. plants for $300 million, including the
assumption of debt. The plants are located in Hazleton and York,
Pa., and in Naugatuck, Conn.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McGraw-Hill Inc. has a good chance of tracking
down the culprit if someone leaked advance information on stocks
spotlighted in its widely read Business Week magazine, experts say.
   The publisher said its legal counsel is investigating suspicious
price movements and heavy trading in stocks mentioned in the
``Inside Wall Street'' column before Business Week was available to
the public.
   In order to trace the leak, McGraw-Hill is likely to team up
with the enforcement operations of the stock exchanges and the
Securities and Exchange Commission, experts said Friday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former E.F. Hutton & Co. Inc. broker
has been sentenced to three months in prison and fined $3,000 for
his part in a money-laundering scheme at the firm's local branch.
   Brian J. Lareau, 46, could have been sentenced to six years in
prison and fined $6,000. Under a plea bargain, prosecutors had
recommended no more than six months in prison.
   The sentence imposed Friday also calls for Lareau to perform 200
hours of public service.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Irving Bank Corp. urged Bank of New York Co. to
abandon its protracted takeover attempt, saying the battle was
``effectively at an end'' since the hostile suitor gave no
indication it planned to wage another proxy battle.
   But Bank of New York spokesman Owen Brady said Friday the
company had no intention of ending its merger plans, which began
last September. He said Bank of New York could, based on a court
ruling, seek another proxy vote on its nominees to Irving's board
of directors.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market closed out its worst week in more than three
months with another broad decline Friday. The Dow Jones average of
30 industrials fell 25.60 points to 2,060.99, stretching its loss
for the week to 68.46 points.
   The dollar lost more ground, while the strong British pound
continued to take the spotlight. Gold prices rose after falling
overseas.
   Bond prices rose in a technical rally to finish at the highs of
the day.
   Most crop futures prices declined; silver futures were sharply
higher; livestock and meat were mostly higher; oil futures prices
were little changed; and stock-index futures retreated.
</TEXT>
