<DOCNO> AP880725-0244 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 0740EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     07-25 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0284</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Holds Steady After Strong Opening; Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar held steady against most major
currencies in European trading today after intervention by West
Germany's central bank dulled its strong opening, dealers said.
Gold prices were mixed.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the dollar rose in thin early
dealings, with players in Frankfurt taking profits on the pound.
   But later they said intervention by the Deutsche Bundesbank
halted the dollar's rise, and at midmorning the market appeared to
be taking a wait-and-see attitude.
   ``The market is rather indecisive right now,'' said one senior
trader with a bank in Milan.
   In London, the British pound was quoted at $1.7358, compared
with $1.7405 Friday.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Friday's
rates, included: 1.8360 West German marks, up from 1.8265; 1.5266
Swiss francs, up from 1.5175; 6.1920 French francs, up from 6.1630;
2.0710 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0615; 1,357.50 Italian lire, up
from 1,353.75; and 1.2030 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1983.
   In Tokyo, the dollar fell 0.28 yen to a closing 131.80. Later,
in London, it was quoted at 131.65 yen.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $442.60 a troy ounce,
compared with late Friday's $442. At midmorning today, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $442.20.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $442.50, unchanged from $442.50
late Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold closed at a bid price of $444.28,
compared to Saturday's $444.62 and late Friday's $444.86 closing.
   Later, silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $7.56 a
troy ounce, down from Friday's $7.76.
</TEXT>
