<HEAD>London Stock Prices Steady After Sharp Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices fell Monday amid bargain-hunting in
light trading.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index was down 9.5
points, or 0.5 percent, at 1,835.3 at midday, after having fallen
18 points in early trading. Volume was 169.1 million shares,
compared to 233.1 million shares at the same time Friday.
   The early declines came on the back of a strong pound and poor
performances in New York on Friday and in Tokyo earlier Monday.
   Some traders said they were encouraged that the market found the
energy to recover some ground.
   ``It hasn't been all that bad,'' said one trader. The lows
created ``a good buying opportunity'' in some stocks, he said.
   But the buying enthusiasm which lifted stocks wasn't expected to
carry into the afternoon, traders said. They said they expected the
market to drift.
   ``I don't think there's any great excitement,'' a trader said.
</TEXT>
