<1ST_LINE>r f BC-MN--PillsburyMoves     07-25 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-MN--Pillsbury Moves,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pillsbury To Buy Bumble Bee Seafoods, Divest Grain Division</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pillsbury Co. said Monday it has signed a
definitive agreement to buy Bumble Bee Seafoods, Inc., a privately
held producer of canned tuna and other seafood.
   Terms of the agreement were not announced, Pillsbury said in a
prepared statement.
   Pillsbury's announcement came three days after H.J. Heinz Co.
said its agreement to acquire Bumble Bee had been terminated
because the federal government was trying to block the deal on
antitrust grounds.
   Pillsbury also said Monday it intends to divest its
Minneapolis-based grain merchandising division, which operates
grain handling and storage facilities primarily in the upper
Midwest. The company said it expects to identify a buyer within the
next few months.
   Proceeds from the sale of the grain merchandising division and
other sources of internal funding are expected to cover a major
portion of the costs associated with the Bumble Bee acquisition,
Pillsbury's statement said.
   Although grain merchandising has been quite profitable, the
company has indicated the division is not part of Pillsbury's
long-term strategic plans, according to the statement.
   ``Today's announcements represent a continuation of our
commitment to quality, branded products with unique strengths that
provide new growth opportunities for the future,'' said John L.
Morrison, chairman of Pillsbury's Consumer Foods Group.
   ``We expect Bumble Bee to be a positive contributor to
Pillsbury's earnings in the first year of operation,'' Morrison
added.
   Bumble Bee will continue to operate under its current management
as a wholly owned subsidiary with headquarters in San Diego,
according to Pillsbury's statement.
   Bumble Bee, with 1987 sales of $265 million, is a top seller of
white meat, or albacore, tuna and canned salmon.
   Pillsbury, an international food and restaurant organization
with fiscal 1988 sales of $6.2 billion, includes the Van de Kamp's
frozen seafood line which it acquired in 1984. Among the company's
other brand names are Pillsbury, Green Giant, Haagen-Dazs, Burger
King, Steak and Ale, and Bennigan's.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
