<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 1031EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-FarmScene 1stLd-Writethru   07-25 0902</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene, 1st Ld-Writethru,0925</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>EDS: Subs 22nd graf pvs, In 1988, to CORRECT 1988 sugar import
tonnage.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Price Supports, Import Quotas Keep U.S. Sugar Costs High</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government sugar policy can be sweet for
domestic producers who enjoy high price supports, or bitter for
foreign sugar-producing countries whose access to the American
market is limited by strict quotas, an Agriculture Department
report says.
   ``Although fewer than 1 percent of American farmers grow sugar
cane or sugar beets, the commodity is one of the most heavily
protected by price supports and import quotas,'' the report said.
   Those in favor of current policy say federal protection is
necessary for the survival of the U.S. sugar industry. Without it,
they say it would be impossible for American growers to compete
with cheaper sugar from countries that have much lower production
costs.
   Another argument is that the U.S. corn industry also benefits
from higher sugar prices by boosting demand for HFCS, or high
fructose corn syrup, in soft drinks and many other food products.
   But USDA analysts say the other side of the coin includes higher
retail prices for American sugar consumers and lost sales _ because
of import quotas _ for some U.S. allies who depend greatly on sugar
as an export commodity.
   Sugar crops are supported at the equivalent of 18 cents per
pound of raw sugar equivalent through ``non-recourse'' loans made
by the department's Commodity Credit Corp. It means that if market
prices fall below the loan rate, sugar processors can forfeit their
collateral without penalty.
   In that case, the loan obligation is canceled and the CCC takes
over ownership of the foreclosed sugar and holds it as surplus.
   To minimize the risk of forfeiture and to head off large rises
in CCC holdings, the market price must be high enough to cover the
loan rate, plus interest, plus marketing charges. The desired price
is called the Market Stabilization Price, or MSP. For 1987-88, the
MSP is 21.76 cents per pound.
   In the first quarter of this year, the duty-paid price of raw
sugar delivered to New York averaged 22.03 cents per pound, well
above the MSP. Comparatively, the ``world price'' of sugar, based
on Caribbean shipping points, was less than 10 cents per pound.
   To prevent lower-priced foreign sugar from pulling down the U.S.
domestic price, import quotas allocated to specific countries have
been set each year since 1982. The quotas keep the supply tight
enough to maintain prices near the MSP, says economist Robert Barry
of the department's Economic Research Service.
   ``If the estimates of supply and demand are accurate, domestic
sugar prices stay high enough to prevent loan forfeitures,'' Barry
writes in the forthcoming August issue of Farmline magazine. ``A
loan forfeiture presents a surplus and storage problem for the
CCC.''
   Federal law stipulates that the sugar price support program is
to be operated at no net cost to the taxpayers.
   The cost of the program is basically paid for by American
consumers through higher prices for table sugar and products that
contain sugar, Barry said.
   Who benefits? Growers and processing companies, who are
guaranteed the support price. Also, indirectly, the corn sweetener
industry, which has seen HFCS become the dominant sweetener for
soft drink manufacturers, Barry said.
   Glucose and dextrose, also made from corn, for many years had
held about 17 percent of the calorie-type sweetener market. But
when the new liquid HFCS came along, it became the major caloric
sweetener used in soft drinks.
   In 1988, per capita consumption of HFCS is forecast at 69.5
pounds per American, 10 percent more than the average for sugar.
   Foreign manufacturers of products containing sugar, and American
consumers of certain imported gourmet food items made from
lower-cost foreign sugar, also benefit from the U.S. policy.
   Meanwhile, Barry said, the price support program has encouraged
greater U.S. domestic sugar production, thereby reducing import
requirements, adding to the world export surplus and keeping world
prices low.
   Sugar-importing nations also benefit, he said. By encouraging
surpluses and low world sugar prices, the support program of the
United States and some other countries ``create a windfall'' for
the Soviet Union, Japan and China, the major sugar importers.
   Barry said the program also has an effect on U.S. employment.
When import quotas shrink, refineries close because they have less
foreign raw sugar to process. Since 1982, eight plants have closed,
eliminating more than 7,000 jobs, he said. And additional jobs are
lost when U.S. manufacturers of sugar-containing products reduce
output.
   The highest cost of the sugar program is paid indirectly by
sugar exporters, Barry said. For years, the United States was the
largest importer, with foreign shipments reaching a peak of 6.1
million tons in 1977 and averaging 4.2 million tons a year from
1975 to 1981.
   In 1988, the U.S. sugar import quota initially was about 750,000
tons but was increased Friday to 1.06 million tons.
   Several bills in Congress would alter the sugar program. One
would reduce the support price to 12 cents per pound from the
current level of 18 cents over a period of four crop years. Also,
the import quota would be increased by 500,000 tons a year for four
years, beginning in 1989.
   Barry said that the lower support ``should lower market prices,
and this would probably discourage production in the United States
and increase the demand for imported sugar.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880725-0253 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 1055EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Earns-Exxon     07-25 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Earns-Exxon,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Exxon Reports Second-Quarter Earnings Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exxon Corp., the nation's largest oil company,
today reported a 4 percent increase in second-quarter net income as
higher refining and chemicals earnings offset lower exploration and
production results.
   Exxon said it earned $1.2 billion, or 90 cents a share, up from
net income of $1.15 billion, or 81 cents a share in the second
quarter of 1987.
   Revenue for the quarter rose 7 percent to $21.63 billion from
$20.16 billion a year ago.
   Exxon Chairman L.G. Rawl noted that ``margins were stronger as
supply costs dropped and product prices firmed'' during the
quarter. He also said increased demand for petroleum products
boosted sales volume in both the United States and abroad.
   Earnings from exploration and production operations totaled $703
million, $183 million less than the year-ago period. The company
noted that lower crude oil sales to its own refineries as well as
to outside customers coupled with higher expenses to offset
increased crude production from new and expanded oil fields.
   The company's chemicals operation reported an $89 million
increase in earnings to $314 million, while higher copper prices
helped the coal and minerals unit report net income of $8 million,
compared with a $14 million loss a year ago.
   Exxon reported corporate and financing charges of $172 million,
up from $24 million a year go.
   For the first six months, Exxon reported net income of $2.66
billion, or $1.96 a share, up 20 percent from $2.22 billion, or
$1.56 a share in the first half of 1987.
   Revenue during the period totaled $43.63 billion, up 10 percent
from revenue of $39.6 billion in the year-ago period.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
