<1ST_LINE>r f BC-OPEC     07-25 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-OPEC,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>OPEC Pricing Committee To Meet Aug. 3, Report Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subroto, one name, is cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The five-member OPEC pricing committee
has decided in principle to meet Aug. 3 in Lausanne, Switzerland,
primarily to deal with a decision by the United Arab Emirates to
increase its oil production, a newsletter reported Monday.
   The respected Middle East Economic Survey said the committee of
the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries is ``expected to
go through the formal motions of reviewing the market situation.''
   But it said ``the main topic on the agenda will be the U.A.E.'s
unilateral decision to allocate itself an `official' quota of 1.5
million barrels a day'' and the impact of this on OPEC's production
quota and the market.
   There has been no official announcement of the meeting of the
committee, comprisng oil ministers of Nigeria, Algeria, Indonesia,
Saudi Arabia and Venezuela.
   A final decision on the meeting may depend on the visit of OPEC
Secretary-General Subroto, of Indonesia, to the U.A.E., the
newsletter said. He is expected there later this week after
finishing the Moslem pilgrimage to Mecca in Saudi Arabia.
   The Middle East Economic Survey said Dr. Subroto faces a
difficult task because the U.A.E.'s Supreme Petroleum Council
decided July 18 to increase production to 1.5 million barrels a
day. The U.A.E.'s OPEC-set production quota is 948,000 barrels a
day.
   Crude oil prices have fallen below the OPEC benchmark price of
$18 a barrel, even without the increase in production by the
U.A.E., largely because of increased non-OPEC production and
above-quota production by OPEC members.
   To enforce the $18 price, OPEC alloted each of its members a
quota with total OPEC production set at 15 million barrels a day.
   This excludes Iraq which refused its allotted quota of 1.54
million barrels a day and has insisted on a quota equal to that of
Iran, its Persian Gulf war opponent, or 2.37 million barrels a day.
Meanwhile, Iraq has been producing at a level of about 2.7 million
barrels a day.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
