<2ND_LINE>BC-Amfac Bid,0384</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Amfac Negotiating With Other Bidders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amfac Inc., which two months ago unveiled
an $800 million leveraged buyout plan, announced Monday that it is
negotiating the sale of the company with several unidentified
bidders.
   Amfac said in a statement that it received bids over the weekend
that were ``in the high $40s per share.'' The company did not
elaborate and warned investors ``that no assurances can be given as
to the probable outcome of the negotiations.''
   Amfac Chairman Henry Walker Jr. said the company has instructed
its financial advisors ``to work to finalize the best transaction
for the company and its shareholders.''
   In late May, Amfac management proposed to acquire the company
for $41 a share, or $807.7 million.
   Amfac's shares consistently have traded above management's
offering price, indicating Wall Street expected the bid to be
improved. In early trading on the New York Stock Exchange Monday,
Amfac jumped $1.12{ to $47.87{.
   Analysts have speculated that Amfac's management-led buyout was
a move designed to stave off a takeover threat by Castle & Cook
Inc., a Los Angeles-based concern that holds a large block of Amfac
stock.
   Two months ago Castle & Cooke held 7.3 percent of Amfac's
roughly 17.2 million oustanding common shares and had received
federal clearance to increase its holdings to 15 percent.
   In addition, Castle & Cooke Chairman David H. Murdock at the
time owned another 2.6 percent of Amfac's outstanding shares.
   Analysts have said Castle & Cooke was most interested in Amfac's
valuable real estate holdings in Hawaii, which total about 56,400
acres. While Amfac is Hawaii's largest landowner, the No. 2 slot is
held by Castle & Cooke, which through its Dole food company is the
world's largest pineapple producer.
   Some analysts said that Amfac's buyout offer does not adequately
take into account the value of the company's Hawaiian property.
   Amfac spokeswoman Deborah Demer had no comment on whether Castle
& Cooke was among the bidders for the company.
   Amfac is a diversified services company with main lines of
business in food processing, hotels and resorts, retail,
agriculture and property. It reported revenue of $2.2 billion last
year. The company's principal executive offices are located in
Honolulu.
</TEXT>
