<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Goodyear     07-25 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Goodyear,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>2nd-Qtr Profit Fell 4.3 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Goodyear Tire & Rubber Co. said Monday its
second-quarter profit slipped 4.3 percent from a year ago when it
reported a gain on the sale of facilities.
   The tire-maker said it earned $134.9 million, or $2.35 a share,
in the three months ended June 30, compared with a profit of $141
million, or $2.47 a share, a year earlier.
   Second-quarter revenue rose 10.3 percent to $2.79 billion from
$2.53 billion a year earlier.
   Goodyear's 1987 results included $13.6 million from the sale of
its plant in Zaire and some properties in Arizona along with the
abandonment of a joint venture with Toyobo of Japan, said Goodyear
spokesman John Perduyn.
   The company sold the properties to raise capital to fend off a
hostile takeover bid by Sir James Goldsmith in late 1986, he said.
   Without income from the facilities sales, Goodyear's net
earnings would have risen 5.9 percent over the second quarter last
year, said Goodyear Chairman Robert E. Mercer.
   Goodyear said its operating income in its tires and related
transportation products business rose 3.6 percent on a sales gain
of 9.8 percent.
   The company said its industrial rubber, chemical and plastic
products segment also reported improved results.
   For the first six months of the year, Goodyear reported its net
income fell 45.9 percent to $230.2 million, or $4.02 a share,
compared with $425.2 million, or $6.63 a share, a year earlier. The
1987 results included $201.1 million from discontinued operations
and the $13.6 million from sales of facilities.
   Six-month revenue rose 11 percent to $5.33 billion from $4.80
billion a year earlier.
</TEXT>
