<HEAD>Soybeans, Corn Futures Plummet In Early Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn and soybean futures plunged their permitted
limits in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade in
reaction to scattered showers over the weekend and forecasts for
rain today in the eastern Midwest.
   Crop futures opened slightly lower, then plummeted after the
November soybean contract slipped below last week's low of $8.15 a
bushel, analysts said.
   The limit losses of 10 cents a bushel for corn and 30 cents a
bushel for soybeans suggested soybean futures may extend to six
days the sharp decline that began a week ago.
   Crop experts say the recent Midwestern rains have been too
spotty to cause great improvement in the drought-damaged corn and
soybean crops ``but the market's perception is that the situation
is much better than it was,'' said Ted Mao, grain specialist with
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   ``Certainly, the markets are reflecting a concern that the crop
is making a major recovery,'' he said.
   In early trading, wheat was 7 cents to 13} cents lower with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.71 a bushel; corn was 8}
cents to 10 cents lower with September at $3.02{ a bushel; oats
were unchanged to the limit 10 cents lower with September at $2.50{
a bushel; soybeans were 11{ cents to 30 cents lower with August at
$8.00{ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .17 cent lower to .45 cent higher with August
at 65.95 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .37 cent lower to .18
cent higher with August at 77.00 cents a pound; hogs were .62 cent
lower to .20 cent higher with August at 45.50 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were 1 cent lower to .03 cent higher with August at
37.80 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled higher on Friday while pork futures were
mixed.
</TEXT>
