<1ST_LINE>a f BC-ToyCars-Collectors Adv30-31   07-25 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Toy Cars-Collectors, Adv 30-31,0307</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 30</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 31</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions July 30-31 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Never Too Old To Collect Toy Cars</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Toy Cars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When he was about 12 years old, James Gibbons
figured he was too old to play with toy cars. When he turned 28, he
realized maybe he wasn't.
   The 38-year-old Gibbons is one of about 6,000 members worldwide
of Matchbox toy car collectors groups. The members trade, buy and
sell the small-scale replicas of vehicles ranging from the Ferrari
Testarossa to a Caterpillar earth mover.
   ``If you do it right, you can probably accumulate a little bit
of wealth,'' said Gibbons, a high school teacher.
   ``My mom and my wife are working for me at rummage sales. I have
a network of people working for me,'' he said.
   Gibbons figures the most valuable piece in the 700-vehicle
collection is worth about $50.
   ``I'd categorize (the collection) in the infant stages based on
what I've seen at the shows,'' he said.
   The smallest Matchbox cars sell for about $1.10 in hobby stores.
Each year, Gibbons says he acquires Matchbox's new line of cars,
usually about 12, and a few older models missing from his
collection.
   Gibbons is a member of the Matchbox International Collectors
Association of North America, based in Waterloo, Ontario. The 900
club members receive the organization magazine every two months and
meet annually.
   ``You get all types. They come from all walks of life,'' said
Rita Schneider, membership secretary. ``A lot of the gentlemen are
older and maybe they remember (the cars) from childhood.''
   The other North America collectors organization, Matchbox
U.S.A., based in Durham, Conn., has about 1,400 members who receive
a monthly magazine and meet annually.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions July 30-31</NOTE>
</DOC>
