<1ST_LINE>a f BC-FamilyWineries Adv30-31   07-25 0990</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Family Wineries, Adv 30-31,1028</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 30</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 31</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions July 30-31 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Small Wineries A Labor Of Love</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ZILLAH, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For Shirley Puryear, the road to joining
the Rothschilds and the Gallos began with a batch of homemade plum
wine.
   The home brew _ made with directions from a $1.99 book, a
five-gallon jug and some plastic tubing _ was terrible, said the
co-owner of the award-winning Bonair Winery.
   Things have improved quite a bit since then, and the Puryears
are among several small family winemakers in Washington who compete
for shelf space and medals with corporate giants like Chateau Ste.
Michelle, the state's largest.
   ``It's so much fun and so romantic,'' Mrs. Puryear, a former
social worker in California, said recently. ``This has surpassed my
wildest dreams.''
   Some of the family winemakers are hobbyists that barely break
even, but others are trying hard to make a living at it.
   ``The glamour fades fast once you get into the business,''
admitted Tom Campbell, owner of Horizon's Edge Winery in Zillah,
nestled in the rolling countryside near Yakima, Wash.
   Start-up costs for small wineries average about $270,000, and
competition is fierce for supermarket and wine list space.
   About seven of the state's 70 wineries produce under 2,083
cases, or 5,000 gallons, per year, according to the Washington Wine
Institute.Most of those under 5,000 gallons are family wineries,
said Simon Siegl, director of the trade group.
   By contrast, giants like Chateau Ste. Michelle produce about
500,000 cases per year and enjoy national distribution.
   Washington is the nation's third largest winemaker, after
California and New York, but is far behind California's 700
wineries.
   Washington winemakers have a history of cooperation, spurring a
growth from 11 wineries in 1977 to the present 70. The roots of
many wineries are intertwined.
   For instance, Mike Conway, owner of Latah Creek Wine Cellars in
Spokane, originally moved up from California to help open Worden's
Washington Winery. Then he helped start Hogue Cellars of Prosser
before securing financial help from the Hogues to launch Latah
Creek in 1983.
   ``The financial help was in exchange for my winemaking at Hogue
Cellars,'' said Conway, whose winery produces 15,000 cases a year.
   There are many similar stories, because it's an expensive
business to get into.
   ``It's a good way to make a small fortune out of a large one,''
said Campbell, who also owns Montana's Mission Mountain Winery, the
only one in that state.
   ``If your total end is to make money, this is not the business
to be in,'' said Campbell, one of several alumni of the winemaking
program at the University of California-Davis who operate in the
state.
   Horizon's Edge, which opened in 1985 and produces 2,500 cases a
year, is approaching $100,000 in annual sales, he said.
   ``I could make more money on the capital in CDs,'' he said.
   Campbell has also worked for Chateau Ste. Michelle, Stewart
Vineyards and Tucker Cellars in Sunnyside and Blackwood Canyon in
Benton City.
   ``I decided I better carve a niche for myself while I still
could,'' said Campbell, a native of Missoula, Mont.
   Like most of the small wineries, his major market is in state,
with many of the sales to visitors in the tasting room.
   ``Everyone who comes through is having fun,'' said Mrs. Puryear
of the often raucous mix of visitors to Bonair's tiny tasting room.
``It's not like buying asparagus at Safeway.''
   The tasting room is an important fixture in the small wineries,
because up to 80 percent of the product is sold there _ especially
by those that do not have wide distribution.
   ``We get hundreds of people per week here in the summer,'' Mrs.
Puryear said, even though the room can hold less than a dozen at
one time.
   ``We get people in here who own wineries in France or a local
who drops by carrying a can of beer,'' she said.
   Her tasting room has maps of the United States and the world,
with pins showing the states and countries of visitors. Delaware is
the only state without a pin.
   ``The first person from Delaware will get a bottle of free
wine,'' she said. ``Our choice.''
   Owners of Washington's family wineries, some of which produce
considerably more than 5,000 gallons, come from a variety of
backgrounds. For instance:
   _John Williams and Jim Holmes, owners of Kiona Vineyards in
Benton City, are engineers on the Hanford nuclear reservation, a
federal plutonium-making facility.
   _Dave Staton, owner of Staton Hills and a pioneer in wine
exports to Japan and Taiwan, founded the Wapato winery a decade ago
after working as an attorney and as an executive for TWA.
   _Michael and Patricia Manz, a child psychiatrist and teacher,
respectively, began Mountain Dome Winery in Spokane four years ago.
They make champagne exclusively and don't plan to market any of
their product until 1992.
   _Dr. George Stewart of Sunnyside established Stewart Vineyards
in 1983.
   Ray Small of Walla Walla, half owner of the highly-regarded
Woodward Canyon Winery, says winemaking is more profitable than
raising hogs.
   Small put up the money when his son, Rick, wanted to go into
winemaking in 1981 and they produce up to 8,000 gallons per year.
The winery is actually a metal building on their farm that
originally served as a truck garage and paint shop, he said.
   ``We've got four or five operations here and some of them are
hurting pretty good, like the wheat business and the hog
business,'' Ray said. But the winery is ``in the black.''
   Winemaking has an attractive, sophisticated image, but
Washington owners say the life isn't quite like ``Falcon Crest,''
the television series about intrigues in California's wine country.
   ``Everybody asks about (Falcon Crest),'' said Mrs. Puryear. ``I
watched one episode and they stuck a body in a wine tank.
   ``It's not like Falcon Crest,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions July 30-31</NOTE>
