<1ST_LINE>r f PM-PA-Mellon     07-25 0193</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PA-Mellon,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mellon Announces Refinancing Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mellon Bank Corp. today announced a
refinancing program of approximately $1 billion, including $525
million in new equity capital and the sale of lower-quality assets
to a new, limited-purpose national bank.
   Mellon said its lower-quality assets will be reduced by about $1
billion. After the sale, Mellon said its exposure to the assets
will be limited to its $100 million investment in the new bank.
   Mellon said its plan calls for creation of a liquidating
national bank, independent of Mellon Bank Corp., to be called Grant
Street National Bank. The bank will not take deposits.
   Mellon Bank's headquarters is on Grant Street, Pittsburgh.
   Mellon said it will create the new bank by distributing common
shares of Grant Street National Bank to its common shareholders. It
said the new bank will acquire Mellon's low-quality assets from
public sale of up to $450 million of bonds to be underwritten by
the investment firm Drexel Burnham Lambert.
   Mellon said the sale of assets and the financing for the new
bank are expected to occur in the third quarter and are dependent
upon approvals from bank regulators.
</TEXT>
