<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-Reuters     07-25 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Reuters,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reuters Posts 24.3 Percent Profit Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reuters Holdings PLC, the information services
group, said Monday its half-year net profit rose 24.3 percent over
a year ago as its financial information and dealing services
continued to grow vigorously.
   However, revenue from trading room systems fell sharply as
investment companies implemented sharp cutbacks, Reuters said.
   Reuters said its net profit for the six months ended June 30
came to 63.4 million pounds, or $108.4 million, or 15.1 pence a
share, compared with 51 million pounds, or 12.2 pence a share, in
the same period a year ago.
   Reuters said its revenue rose 17.7 percent to 471.4 million
pounds from 400.4 million pounds.
   The company did not give out quarterly results. It is not
required to release them under British law.
   The company, which owns the Reuters news agency, said revenue
growth was curbed by the strength of the pound and a decline in
contributions from trading room systems.
   Glen Renfrew, Reuters' managing director and chief executive,
said a slowdown in orders for trading room systems was mostly the
result of cutbacks in investment firms in New York and London.
   But orders from Japan were excellent and orders from continental
Europe were good, he said.
</TEXT>
