<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreetNoon     07-25 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Noon,0295</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market gave ground today, extending
last week's decline.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which fell 68.46 points
last week, lost another 3.56 to 2,057.43 by noontime on Wall Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 3 to 2 in the overall tally
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 515 up, 749 down and
502 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 140.57 million shares at
noontime, against 82.44 million at the same point Friday.
   More than half that activity came in just two issues _ Southern
Co., up \ at 22}, and Pinnacle West, unchanged at 25.
   Analysts said both were the targets of large-scale trading
strategies based on the companies' impending dividend payments.
   Otherwise, brokers said traders were still put off by worries
over inflation and fears of a continuing rise in interest rates.
   The government is due to report Wednesday on the gross national
product for the second quarter. If the figures show persistent
strong growth in business activity, as many analysts expect, they
could raise fresh fears of upward pressure on interest rates.
   In addition, brokers said, morale on Wall Street was generally
low after the market's weak performance last week.
   Losers among the blue chips included Ford Motor, down | at 50{;
General Electric, down [ at 41[, and Philip Morris, down [ at 88.
   Compaq Computer rose | to 59] in active trading. The company
reported higher profits for the second quarter.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell
.22 to 149.03. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down .61 at 305.50.
</TEXT>
