<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 1253EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Chrysler-Kenosha     07-25 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Chrysler-Kenosha,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chrysler, UAW Local 72 Sign Contract</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KENOSHA, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chrysler Corp. and the United Auto
Workers signed a contract Monday covering workers affected by the
scheduled end of auto production in Kenosha and the closing of the
stamping plant in Milwaukee.
   Marc Stepp, UAW vice president and director of its Chrysler
department, said he hoped there would be ``life after current
production'' which is scheduled to end in December at the former
American Motors Co. plant in Kenosha.
   ``We hope this will not be the end of this operation. It is our
hope that it does continue,'' Stepp said.
   The agreement covers 5,500 workers in Kenosha and 450 at the
stamping plant, which already has closed.
   Stepp said he was particularly happy about the commitment in the
contract calling for Chrysler to pay back AMC profit-sharing that
AMC had promised members of UAW locals 72 and 75 in exchange for
concessions.
   Chrysler acquired the Kenosha car-making plant and the Milwaukee
stamping operation when it bought AMC last year. Chrysler initially
planned to keep the plant open for several years, but then
announced it did not need the production capability.
   Anthony St. John, vice president for human resources at
Chrysler, also cited provisions in the pact calling for worker
benefits to continue for up to two years after the layoffs and to
allow special early retirements for some senior workers.
   St. John said the decision to stop building cars in Kenosha as
of December stands.
   When asked if there was any chance of it continuing into 1989,
St. John said, ``I would suggest that the answer is no to that.''
   St. John said the company projects that the produced in Kenosha
at a separate plant that employs about 800 workers will be needed
through 1992. But he said it is possible that plant could close
before that.
   ``However, it certainly is not likely,'' he said.
</TEXT>
