<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 1327EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-StickierStamps Bjt   07-25 0618</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stickier Stamps, Bjt,0637</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conference To Debate Philatelic Problem: Why Won't Stamps Stick?</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BETH GRACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A think tank has been given 10 months to
answer a question that has concerned consumers and plagued
philatelists since the dawn of postal automation: Why won't stamps
stick?
   Battelle Memorial Institute, which recently received a $700,000
contract from the U.S. Postal Service, convenes a meeting here
Thursday in hopes of making a sticky situation stickier, said Don
McDowell, general manager of the stamp division of the U.S. Postal
Service in Washington.
   About 100 representatives of adhesive manufacturers and paper
companies expected to attend the one-day meeting will be asked to
share their thoughts and, in some cases, their secret formulas.
   ``I don't think $700,000 is too much to pay for a stamp that
sticks,'' he said in a telephone interview. ``Compare that to the
fact that stamps are an $8 billion-a-year business.''
   The Columbus-based institute is trying to find a perfect stamp
glue _ one that not only will keep stamp and envelope together from
the point of origin to destination, but will taste a little better,
McDowell said.
   ``The public insists that it at least, if it can't stick, not
taste so bad,'' he said. ``The problem is finding a consensus on
what tastes good. Some people like liver, others don't. So it's got
to be something that may not taste great, and may not taste like
anything at all.''
   He said consumers have repeatedly suggested more flavorful glues
that taste like cherry, vanilla and vodka.
   ``Oh, they have suggested it, but I hardly think vodka would be
appropriate,'' he said, laughing. ``No, Jerry Falwell, we're not
planning on that at all.''
   Neither McDowell nor Battelle consider the issue a laughing
matter.
   ``Sure, people giggle. But it's not very funny to us. It's very
important to us, and to the people who want their letters to reach
their destinations,'' McDowell said.
   He said Battelle's task will not be easy.
   ``Do you have any idea how many adhesives there are in the
world?'' he said. The Postal Service uses three kinds of adhesives
now, which McDowell describes as ``shiny, not shiny and halfway in
between.''
   He could not estimate how many stamps are lost in transit every
year, but said the problem has gotten worse since the Postal
Service began to automate in the early 1970s.
   ``Before then, when it was manual, the impact to a stamp was
like a car hitting a brick wall at 5 mph. Now, it's like a car
hitting a brick wall at 60 mph. Because these machines accelerate
and decelerate so fast, when the envelope stops, the stamp doesn't
want to,'' he said.
   Slowing the machines won't fix the problem, he said. The rising
volume of mailed items means the system will have to speed up.
About 35 million stamped items move through the system every year.
   The American Philatelic Society, an organization of stamp
collectors, has argued that not only is the adhesive not sticky
enough, it also eats through the paper, which decreases a stamp's
value.
   One philatelist does not agree that a new glue is needed.
   M.W. Martin of the Topical Philatelic House in Columbus says the
glue is not the culprit. He blames the disappearing stamp dilemma
on human error and sorting machines that are not stamp-friendly.
   ``I'm in this business 40 years and I just don't see the
non-sticky problem. If they fall off sometimes, it's not the glue.
People aren't licking them enough, the envelope maybe has some dust
on it. I think the real problem is the machines at the post
office,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
