<DOCNO> AP880725-0268 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 1352EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f AM-Japan-BuyingLuxury Adv28   07-25 0613</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Buying Luxury, Adv 28,0630</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 28</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thursday AMs July 28 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Japanese Beginning to Spend their Yen on Luxury Goods</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KOZO MIZOGUCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Japanese are breaking with a tradition of
frugality to bring some luxury into their lives _ big cars,
European furniture, diamond jewelry.
   The government has been urging them to spend the yen they
ordinarily put in the bank, in hopes of spurring the domestic
economy.
   Analysts say skyrocketing property values, easy credit, price
stability and the yen's rise in value are generating a fast-growing
market for luxury goods _ a turnaround from three years of slumping
consumption when the surging yen subdued the export-driven economy.
   ``Selling well are expensive and luxurious durable goods such as
large-size TV sets, refrigerators, furniture and dining ware
imported from Europe,'' said Mitsuhiro Hirose of the Sales
Promotion Division at Matsuya Co., a major department store on
Tokyo's bustling Ginza.
   A recent Bank of Japan report called brisk personal buying a
``key element'' of Japan's current economic success. The government
has cut income taxes and launched a 5-trillion-yen ($40 billion)
public spending program, spurring housing starts. The bank cut its
discount rate to a record low 2.5 percent, and the public Housing
Loan Corp. trimmed more than a percentage point off its interest
rate, currently 4.35 percent.
   Consumer demand as measured by department store sales jumped 8.2
percent in April from a year earlier, according to the Japan
Department Stores Association. Total sales by 254 major department
stores last year rose an average 4.7 percent every month, the
association said.
   And the gross national product, which measures total output of
goods and services, grew at an annualized rate of 11.3 percent in
the first quarter of this year, figures from the Economic Planning
Agency indicate.
   ``People regard expensive, new products as a means of being
somewhat different from others,'' said Takayuki Ikeda, manager of
the Consumer Electronics Product Division at Mitsubishi Electric Co.
   In 1985 the company began marketing its 37-inch color television
set, the industry equivalent of 35-inch American models, for
478,000 yen ($3,825).
   ``At first we never thought a large-sized TV with a built-in
picture tube would be accepted in Japanese homes, which some
Europeans have ridiculed as `rabbit hutches','' Ikeda said in an
interview, ``but the opposite is true. People have realized that
the larger the TV screen, the more fun they can have, the more
feeling of real ambience.''
   Japanese bought 9.6 million color TV sets last year, 20 percent
of which measured 22 inches or larger, up 12 percent from 1986,
according to industry figures.
   Automakers are benefiting from the Japanese who now want bigger,
more expensive cars. Toyota Motor Co. in April sold 14,673 of its
large-size, 4.6-million-yen ($37,000), top-of-the-line Crown models
_ a 92.5-percent jump from a year earlier.
   ``People's sense of money has become accentuated,'' said Isao
Takayama, chief of the jewelry division at the swank Mitsukoshi
department stores. ``Several years ago you could buy a house for 50
to 60 million yen. Now it costs up to 500 million yen ($4 million).
It tends to dull people's sense of money.''
   Reflecting a demand for expensive ornaments, imports of polished
diamonds rose 61.6 percent to 1.06 million carats in the first four
months of this year over last year, according to the Ministry of
International Trade and Industry.
   Takayama said the hottest items are diamond rings priced at 2
million yen ($16,000).
   ``Nowadays customers come in asking to see diamonds of about 100
million yen ($228,000),'' he said. ``Four or five years ago, that
was the stuff of dreams.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Thursday AMs July 28</NOTE>
</DOC>
