<HEAD>Stocks Fall</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates thruout with closing figures.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices fell Monday in quiet trading on the London
Stock Exchange as the market awaited British economic reports due
later in the week.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index fell 6.3
points, or 0.3 percent, to 1,838.5, after sinking as low as 1,826.7
shortly after the opening.
   Volume was a meager 288.4 million shares, compared with 402.6
million shares traded Friday.
   Some traders said they were encouraged by the market's ability
to claw back from its initial decline of 18.1 points.
   The early declines came as the pound strengthened and stock
prices had fallen Friday in New York and earlier Monday in Tokyo.
   ``We're ticking a bit better all the time,'' one equity salesman
said.
   But there was little news on which the market could trade,
traders said.
   The salesman cautioned that dealings would likely remain light
until release of British economic reports later in the week.
Britain's next trade report is due Wednesday.
