<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Computers     07-25 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Computers,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Computer Firm's Income Jumps 91 Percent In 2nd Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Compaq Computer Corp., enjoying higher than
expected orders for two new desktop computers, Monday reported a 91
percent jump in net income for the second quarter.
   Sales for the second quarter increased 71 percent compared to
the same period a year ago.
   The Houston-based firm on June 20 began volume shipments of two
new desktop computers and were met with stronger initial dealer
demand than any other product in the company's history, officials
said.
   ``Our solid second-quarter financial results reflect continued
strong worldwide demand for our high-performance, industry-standard
products,'' said Rod Canion, president and chief executive officer.
   Part of the increase was a non-recurring, pretax gain of nearly
$10 million that resulted from an increase in the carrying value of
the company's investment in Conner Peripherals Inc., which was
offered publicly for the first time during the quarter.
   During the second quarter of 1988, net income rose to $59
million, or $1.45 per share, on sales of $457 million from $31
million, or 80 cents per share on sales of $268 million a year ago.
   Compaq's gain from the Conner Peripherals public offering
increased earnings per share by about 15 cents in the period,
officials said.
   Net income for the first six months of 1988 was $105 million, or
$2.66 per share, compared with $51 million, or $1.36 per share, in
the first half of 1987. Sales totaled $896 million up from $478
million.
   The company established a subsidiary in Belgium during the
second quarter, bringing to 43 the number of countries where Compaq
computers are available.
</TEXT>
