   The stock market drifted in a narrow range today
in an inconclusive session.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which fell 68.46 points
last week, recovered 3.38 to 2,064.37 by 2 p.m. on Wall Street.
   But losers outnumbered gainers by about 4 to 3 in the overall
tally of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 561 up, 783
down and 530 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 175.84 million shares with two
hours to go.
   More than half that activity came in just two issues _ Southern
Co., up [ at 22|, and Pinnacle West, down [ at 24~.
   Analysts said both were the targets of large-scale trading
strategies based on the companies' impending dividend payments.
   Otherwise, brokers said traders were still put off by worries
over inflation and fears of a continuing rise in interest rates.
   The government is due to report Wednesday on the gross national
product for the second quarter. If the figures show persistent
strong growth in business activity, as many analysts expect, they
could raise fresh fears of upward pressure on interest rates.
   In addition, brokers said, morale on Wall Street was generally
low after the market's weak performance last week.
   Among the blue chips, International Business Machines rose ~ to
121; General Electric gained \ to 41{; Ford Motor dropped { to 50|,
and Philip Morris was unchanged at 88\.
