<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Robins     07-25 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Robins,0261</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Posts 3.9 Percent Profit Increase in 2nd-Qtr</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A.H. Robins Co. reported Monday that its
second-quartyer earnings rose 3.9 percent on an 11 percent sales
increase.
   The pharmaceutical manufacturer, which is operating with
protection from its creditors under Chapter 11 of the federal
bankruptcy laws, said its earnings were hurt by the accrual of
certain costs and expenses that it expects will be incurred as part
of its Chapter 11 reorganization plan.
   Robins earned $8 million, or 33 cents per share, in the three
months ended June 30, compared to $7.7 million, or 32 cents per
share, a year earlier.
   But the company said its earnings for the quarter would have
increased 130 percent without the Chapter 11 costs.
   Sales for the quarter rose to $202.6 million from $182.2 million
in 1987.
   Operating earnings for the second quarter were $24.8 million, up
2 percent from the $24.5 million in the comparable period last year.
   For the first six months of the year, Robins said it earned
$22.1 million, or 91 cents per share, down 34 percent from $33.7
million, or $1.40 a share, a year ago.
   Six-month revenue rose 9 percent to $428.7 million from $392
million a year earlier.
   Robins sought Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection in August 1985 as
injury claims mounted against its Dalkon Shield birth control
device.
   The company's reorganization, including a merger with the New
York-based American Home Products Corp., is expected to receive
court ratification later this summer.
</TEXT>
