<1ST_LINE>u f BC-AutoSales     07-25 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Auto Sales,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ford, Chrysler Daily Car Sales Rise</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: An AMer expected by 6:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Big Three automakers posted a 3.7 percent
increase on Monday in their daily domestic car sales in mid-July,
as double-digit increases at Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp.
offset a slight decline at General Motors Corp.
   GM sold 106,791 cars in the July 11-20 period, up from 96,746 in
the mid-July period of 1987. But with nine days in the period this
year and eight last year, GM's daily sales rate slowed by 1.9
percent.
   Ford sold 69,039 cars, up from 55,686 a year earlier and up 10.2
percent on a daily basis, while Chrysler sold 29,956 cars, up from
24,037 a year earlier and up 10.8 percent on a daily basis.
   Overall, the Big Three sold 205,786 cars, up from 176,469 a year
earlier and 3.7 percent on a daily basis.
   GM sold 53,434 domestically made light trucks, a 7.7 percent
rise in daily sales and Chrysler sold 29,172, up 9.8 percent. Ford
sold 45,426 light trucks, down 0.8 percent on a daily basis.
   Honda Motor Co. sold 6,344 of its U.S.-made cars during the
period for a 3.1 percent gain in daily sales. Toyota sold 1,745
domestically produced autos, up from 874 in a period affected by
tooling changes a year earlier.
   Imported car and truck sales are reported at the end of each
month.
</TEXT>
