<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     07-25 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dollar-Gold,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises, Gold Falls In Profit-Taking</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: AMer expected by 5:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar climbed higher at the end of trading in
Europe Monday, despite central bank intervention to hold it down,
dealers said.
   Gold prices fell more than $7 an ounce in London on what dealers
said profit-taking after last week's advance.
   Dollar trading was initially hectic Monday, dealers said. The
U.S. currency jumped sharply in Frankfurt, but was brought lower
when the West German central bank intervened to sell dollars, they
said.
   ``At present levels, there is new demand,'' a Frankfurt dealer
said.
   Dealers said they believed the dollar hit bottom late last week
and is heading for higher ground again.
   Some dealers in Frankfurt said the central bank may have
intervened partly to prop up the mark against the British pound,
which also strengthened against the West German currency Monday.
   Dealers in London said the pound continued to be buoyed by the
market's belief that Britain's relatively high interest rates are
unlikely to come down in the near future, putting the brakes on
inflation.
   But the British currency fell against the dollar. In London, the
British pound was quoted at $1.7265, compared with $1.7405 Friday.
   Other late dollar rates, compared with late Friday's rates,
included: 1.8452 West German marks, up from 1.8265; 1.5345 Swiss
francs, up from 1.5175; 6.2215 French francs, up from 6.1630;
2.0745 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0615; 1,359.50 Italian lire, up
from 1,353.75; 1.2075 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1983.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends before Europe's begins,
the dollar fell 0.28 yen to a closing 131.80. Later, in London, it
was quoted at 132.08 yen.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid price of $434.75 a troy ounce,
compared with late Friday's $442.
   In Zurich, gold was lower, closing at a bid $437.50, compared
with $442.50 late Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 34 cents to close at a bid
$444.28.
   Silver bullion prices fell on the London market where the metal
was trading at a late bid price of $7.60 a troy ounce, compared
with Friday's $7.76.
</TEXT>
