<HEAD>Dun & Bradstreet Selling Airline Guides Division</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dun & Bradstreet Corp. said Monday it plans to
sell its airline guide and travel agency division.
   Charles W. Moritz, Dun & Bradstreet's chairman and chief
executive officer, said, ``The divestiture of Official Airline
Guides continues a process begun in 1983 of sharpening D&B's focus
on key markets for information services.''
   The company said it would use the money from the sale as well as
``other actions to be taken'' to offset the division's income. The
division had operating income of about $65 million on revenue of
$180 million in 1987, the announcement said.
   Dun & Bradstreet, which markets business information and related
services, said properties to be sold include the division's
transportation and travel guides, travel magazines, a ticketing and
reservations service and Thomas Cook Travel U.S.A.
