<DOCNO> AP880725-0281 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 1534EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-PillsburyCEO Bjt   07-25 0847</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pillsbury CEO, Bjt,0871</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pillsbury Names Philip Smith New CEO</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will be updated with final stock price.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troubled food giant Pillsbury Co. named the head
of rival General Foods Corp. as its new top executive Monday, but
the announcement drew a negative reaction on Wall Street.
   Analysts said they were skeptical that Philip L. Smith, who
lacks solid experience in the restaurant business, would be able to
quickly turn around Pillsbury's flagging Burger King fast-food
chain as well as engage in tough competition to defend the
company's consumer food products.
   Echoing those concerns, Pillsbury stock fell $1.50 a share to
$35.37{ in afternoon trading on the New York Stock Exchange.
   Smith, 54, has been chairman of General Foods, the nation's
largest food concern, and vice chairman of Philip Morris Cos. Inc.,
which acquired General Foods in 1985. He is to begin his new job
Aug. 1.
   He is taking over from William H. Spoor, who returned from
retirement to run Pillsbury on an acting basis nearly five months
ago when the previous chief executive was pressured to leave the
company.
   Minneapolis-based Pillsbury, the nation's fourth largest food
conglomerate, produces Green Giant vegetables, Haagen-Dazs premium
ice creams and Van de Kamp's frozen fish. In addition to the
5,500-unit Burger King chain, it also owns Steak & Ale and
Bennigan's restaurants.
   Separately, Pillsbury announced Monday it had agreed to purchase
Bumble Bee Seafoods Inc., a privately held San Diego-based producer
of canned seafood with annual revenue of $265 million. Pillsbury
also said it had decided to sell off its grain merchandising
division and use the proceeds to finance the Bumble Bee acquisition.
   In prepared statement, Spoor said that ``attracting a top-flight
chief executive has been a major priority.'' He called Smith ``a
gifted and capable leader (who) has the unanimous support of our
board of directors and the senior management.''
   Analysts have been critical of Pillsbury, saying it lacked clear
and vital leadership over the past few years.
   Its after-tax profit plummeted 62 percent in fiscal 1988 to
$69.3 million on sales of $6.2 billion, largely because of a
restructuring charge associated with the sale of the Godfather's
Pizza chain and a number of other restaurant operations and
consolidations.
   The restaurant unit, which accounts for nearly half of the
company's total revenue, reported a 5 percent drop in sales in the
fiscal year ended May 31 as Burger King continued to lose market
share to rival McDonald's Corp.
   ``Pillsbury's weakness has been more related to restaurants, and
if they got a guru in restaurants, they may have been better off,''
said Edward Froelich, an analyst at Pershing & Co.
   Pillsbury has been pouring as much as $200 million a year into
touting Burger King restaurants amid criticism that the advertising
campaigns were less than effective. The company also faces stiff
competition in its consumer foods business.
   Under Smith's leadership, General Foods also has suffered
lagging growth and earnings. ``You can't say his track record at
General Foods would lend itself to any wide-eyed enthusiasm,''
Froelich said.
   Much of General Foods' difficulites can be linked to its core
Maxwell House coffee business, which is suffering from lackluster
growth. But analysts point to other potential problems.
   ``Smith has been a big cheese in a company with a lot of easy
brands,'' said Stephen Carnes, a managing director at Piper Jaffray
& Hopwood in Minneapolis, referring to Oscar Mayer luncheon meats
and Jell-O brand gelatin.
   Because Pillsbury has few high-growth products, Smith ``will
have to get down to trench warfare, and he was never in that mode
before,'' Carnes said.
   While some analysts speculated that Philip Morris might be
unhappy with Smith's performance at General Foods, others suggested
Smith merely wanted to run his own show.
   Smith, a 22-year veteran of General Foods, said in a statement
that ``Pillsbury is a terrific company with fine businesses and
excellent people.''
   ``I'm looking forward to leading this company aggressively with
its exciting and challenging opportunities,'' he said.
   The 65-year-old Spoor returned to the helm at Pillsbury after
the ouster of John Stafford, whom Spoor had groomed as his
successor and who presided over Pillsbury's first earnings decline
in 16 years. Spoor had run the company from 1973 through 1985.
   Speculation had been swirling on Wall Street recently that
despite its difficulties, Pillsbury might be a takeover target.
   But analysts are divided as to how attractive a takeover
candidate Pillsbury may be. Carnes, for instance, said Pillsbury
had ``too many wrecks in the ditch right now.''
   Some people have said the Burger King chain could fetch as much
as $1.5 billion if it were spun off as a separate company, but
Carnes estimated the chain would bring only about $900 million
because it was at least two years away from a turnaround.
   Pilip Morris Chairman Hamish Maxwell issued a statement praising
Smith's tenure at General Foods and said Smith's position would not
be filled. Maxwell said the heads of the subisidary's domestic
foods, coffee and Oscar Mayer units would report directly to him.
</TEXT>
