<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blue chip issues staged a mild rally, but the
rest of the stock market continued to struggle Monday in the
aftermath of last week's sharp drop.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, down 68.46 points last
week, recovered 10.84 to 2,071.83.
   But declining issues slightly outnumbered advances in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with 682 up, 778
down and 485 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 215.14 million
shares, against 148.88 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in
those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter
market, totaled 233.18 million shares.
   Nearly half of Monday's activity came in just two issues _
Southern Co., up \ at 22} on volume of nearly 74 million shares,
and Pinnacle West, down [ at 24~ on turnover of more than 25
million shares.
   Analysts said both were the targets of large-scale trading
strategies based on the companies' impending dividend payments.
   Otherwise, brokers said traders were still put off by worries
over inflation and fears of a continuing rise in interest rates.
   The government is due to report Wednesday on the gross national
product for the second quarter. If the figures show persistent
strong growth in business activity, as many analysts expect, they
could raise fresh fears of upward pressure on interest rates.
   In addition, brokers said, morale on Wall Street was generally
low after the market's poor performance last week.
   Gainers among the blue chips included International Business
Machines, up 2\ at 122]; General Electric, up { at 41}; General
Motors, up 1] at 80, and Philip Morris, up } at 89.
   Japanese stocks were broadly higher, amid what some analysts
described as a ``squeeze'' on short sellers who had borrowed the
stock and sold it in hopes of profiting from a decline.
   Matsushita Electric climbed 10{ to 218{; Honda Motor 2} to 177\;
Kyocera 6[ to 91{; Hitachi 2| to 146~; Pioneer Electronics 3} to
55\, and Sony 4 to 49\.
   Precious metals stocks fell as gold and silver prices tumbled.
ASA Ltd. lost 1 to 40|; Hecla Mining ~ to 15|, and Callahan Mining
1[ to 19\.
   Postal Instant Press, traded on the American Stock Exchange,
dropped 1~ to 15. The company said financing delays had occurred in
a planned buyout at about $17.41 a share.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market increased $6.62 billion, or 0.25
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
gained .49 to 149.74.
   Standard & Poor's industrial index rose 1.58 to 305.94, and
S&P's 500-stock composite index was up 1.18 at 264.68.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
dipped .23 to 387.12. At the Amex, the market value index closed at
304.68, down 1.43.
