<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 1855EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-McSleep     07-25 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-McSleep,0583</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>McDonald and Quality Inns at Odds Over McSleep</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DENISE LAYFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Representatives of fast-food giant McDonald's
Corp. testified Monday that Quality Inns International Inc. was
infringing upon its trademarks by using the name McSleep Inn for a
new chain of economy hotels.
   McDonald's took immediate exception last September to the use of
the ``Mc'' prefix after Quality Inns announced the new chain of
hotels, which will offer a night's lodging for $20 to $29.
   After repeated warnings from McDonald's to stop using the name,
Quality Inns filed suit against the international hamburger chain,
asking a federal judge to declare that McSleep does not infringe on
the chain's trademarks.
   McDonald's counter-sued Quality Inns, charging that use of the
``Mc'' prefix constitutes an infringement and that the public will
likely confuse the inns with McDonald's.
   ``We wanted to remove any cloud that was hanging over Quality,''
said Laurence Hefter, chief trial counsel for the lodging company
based at Silver Spring, Md. ``There's absolutely no likelihood of
confusion with McDonald's. The (McSleep) logo is very distinctive.''
   The McSleep logo is a variation on the Quality Inns logo of a
setting sun bordered by a black square, very distinct from
McDonald's golden arch, said Hefter.
   Hefter said the ``Mc'' prefix was selected because it connotes a
clear impression of value, affordable quality service. ``McDonald's
may have played a part in promoting that type of image, but we
believe that it has gone beyond that into the lexicon,'' he added.
   McDonald's began its defense Monday in the trial which began
July 18 before U.S. District Judge Paul Niemeyer.
   Roy T. Bergold Jr., vice president of advertising for
McDonald's, said the company spent more than $404 million last year
in advertising.
   In one of more than a dozen videotaped McDonald's commercials
presented in court Monday, the promotional character Ronald
McDonald taught children to put the prefix before many different
words, including Mc-fries, Mc-(milk) shakes and Mc-best.
   The purpose of the commercial was to create a Mc-language,
specifically associated with McDonald's, Bergold said.
   ``McDonald's is the largest single-brand television advertiser
in the country,'' he said. Surveys found that in the last four
weeks, 89 percent of the nation's children between 2 and
7-years-old have visited a McDonald's, and 96 percent of all adults
have visited a McDonald's at least once, Bergold testified.
   ``We're trying to establish the impact and awareness that
McDonald's has on the public, and why it's likely that they're
going to be confused'' by the McSleep chain, said Karen Kasander,
an attorney for McDonald.
   Chief trial counsel for McDonald's, former Maryland attorney
general Stephen H. Sachs, said a McDonald-sponsored survey
indicated that more than 30 percent of the participants associated
McSleep with McDonald's.
   McDonald's successfully sued the owner of a New York store
called McBagel. A federal judge ruled that the business community
generally recognizes that the ``Mc'' formative stands as a symbol
of McDonald's services and products.
   But Hefter said other company names not associated with food
bear the ``Mc'' prefix, including McThrifty and McLube.
   The McSleep Inns will offer a basic room with a bath, but no
pool, meeting rooms, food service or restaurant. Quality Inn, a
subsidiary of Manor Care Inc., hopes to franchise about 200 such
inns by 1991.
   Testimony in the trial is expected to end Wednesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
