<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Sprint-Billing     07-25 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sprint-Billing,0474</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FCC Threatens US Sprint With Sanctions Over Consumer Billing
Problems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission has
indicated it may fine US Sprint Communications Co. unless the
long-distance phone company does a better job responding to
consumer billing complaints.
   Customer complaints about inaccurate, incomplete and late bills
have plagued the nation's third-largest long-distance company since
it was formed in July 1986 and have contributed to its losses.
   In a letter last week to US Sprint President Robert H. Snedaker,
the FCC said it was concerned about the volume of billing
complaints it has received from US Sprint customers and the
company's ``inadequate and inaccurate responses.''
   While other carriers have experienced billing complaints, they
usually correct the problem within two to three months, said the
letter, signed by Gerald Brock, the FCC's top telephone official.
   ``In US Sprint's case, however, various billing and related
problems have been occurring for well over a year,'' Brock said.
``These problems have been compounded by US Sprint's apparent
inability to promptly rectify complaints either when a customer
directly contacts US Sprint or when the customer contacts the
commission.''
   The FCC gave Sprint 20 days to explain the procedures it has in
place to investigate complaints forwarded by the FCC and what steps
it intends to respond to these complaints within the 30 days
required by law.
   US Sprint officials had no comment Monday on the letter.
Previously, the company has blamed the billing errors on computer
problems and has said it was bringing the foulups under control.
   Greg Vogt, chief of the FCC's telephone enforcement unit, said
the agency received 1,821 complaints against Sprint between Oct. 1,
1986, and July 14, but said ``we would be seeing the tip of the
iceberg of what Sprint sees'' in complaints directly from customers.
   During the same period, the FCC received 1,114 complaints
against American Telephone & Telegraph Co. and 494 against MCI
Communications Corp., he said.
   AT&T, the nation's largest long-distance company, says it serves
about 70 percent of the interstate long-distance market, while MCI
claims about 10 percent and Sprint about 6 percent.
   Vogt said the FCC, if not satisfied with Sprint's efforts to
make timely responses to complaints, could fine the company as much
as $2,000 per violation, up to a total of $20,000.
   Last week, GTE Corp. announced it was selling most of its 50
percent stake in US Sprint to its partner in the venture, United
Telecommunications Inc. United Telecom will raise its stake in US
Sprint to 80.1 percent early next year.
   US Sprint lost $138 million in the first quarter of 1988 after
racking up losses of $800 million last year. The two parents have
shared those losses equally.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
