<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Manville     07-25 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Manville,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Manville Reports Second Quarter Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Manville Corp. said Monday that its after-tax
profit slumped 19.5 percent in the second quarter because of
special charges related to asbestos clean-up costs and the shutdown
of a plywood operation.
   The building materials company said its net profit totaled $33.1
million, or $1.12 a share, in the April-June period, compared with
earnings of $41.1 million, or $1.45 a share, in the same 1987
quarter. Revenue rose 8.3 percent to $561 million from $517.8
million.
   For the first six months, profit fell 18.1 percent to $68.8
million, or $2.35 a share, from $84 million, or $2.97 a share, in
1987. Revenue rose 10.8 percent to $1.1 billion from $992.9 million.
   Manville said the $13.9 million after-tax charge primarily
covered removing asbestos from company property. It also included a
provision for the closing of a plywood operation at Manville's
facility in Huttig, Ark.
   Net earnings for the first six months of 1987 included a
one-time gain of $9 million from the sale of two real estate joint
ventures.
   ``While our overall operating performance remains strong, we
continued to experience severe competition in most construction
markets during the second quarter,'' said Tom Stephens, Manville
president and chief executive officer.
   Manville filed for reorganization under Chapter 11 of the
federal bankruptcy code on Aug. 26, 1982.
   The company's reorganization plan was approved by the bankruptcy
court judge on Dec. 22, 1986, and upheld by the 2nd U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals in New York this past March. An appeal of the
approval is now before the Supreme Court.
</TEXT>
