<2ND_LINE>AM-Bank Merger, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0214,0407</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fleet-Norstar to Buy Indian Head Banks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 new graf after 3rd graf pvs The exchange...to
CLARIFY that $240 million total includes exchange of convertible
preferred stock. Picks up 4th graf pvs, They said...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NASHUA, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fleet-Norstar Financial Group said Monday it
has agreed to acquire Indian Head Banks Inc., a leading bank
holding company in New Hampshire, in an exchange of stock valued at
$240 million.
   The deal, which is subject to approval by regulators and
shareholders of Indian Head, calls for Fleet-Norstar to exchange
1.775 shares of its common stock for each of Indian Head's 4.7
million shares of common stock outstanding.
   The exchange ratio represents a price of about $44.37{ for each
Indian Head share, based on Fleet-Norstar's closing price of $25 a
share on Friday, the companies said in a statement.
   The exchange of Indian Head convertible preferred stock into an
equal number of Fleet-Norstar convertible preferred shares would
boost the total value of the deal about $240 million, the banks
stated.
   They said that price is approximately 1.7 times Indian Head's
book value per common share and is a 30 percent premium over its
market price, based on its close on Friday at $34.25 a share.
   Indian Head Banks, based in Nashua, has assets of about $1.8
billion; Fleet-Norstar's assets are about $25 billion.
Fleet-Norstar has dual headquarters in Providence, R.I., and
Albany, N.Y.
   Indian Head has 46 branches throughout New Hampshire and earned
$16.6 million in 1987, the company said.
   Peter D. Kiernan, chairman and chief executive of Fleet-Norstar,
said the proposed acquisition would be ``a major step'' in
expanding Fleet-Norstar's New England banking franchise.
   He noted that Fleet-Norstar already has four Norstar banks in
New York state, and operates Merrill-Norstar Bank in Maine, United
Bank in Connecticut and Fleet National Bank in Rhodse Island.
   J. Terrence Murray, president of Fleet-Norstar, said that after
the acquisition, it is expected that James Chandler will continue
as Indian Head's chairman and H.E. Harrington Jr. will continue as
its president and chief executive.
   Harrington said he expects the bank to operate ``as an
autonomous unit'' of Fleet-Norstar after the transaction is
completed. ``We do not see any significant cahnges for the next few
years,'' he said.
   Fleet-Norstar Financial Group is a diversified national
financial services company with about 1,000 offices in 40 states.
</TEXT>
