<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Spelling-Lindner     07-25 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spelling-Lindner,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>TV Producer Spelling in Deal with Cincinnati Billionaire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aaron Spelling, producer of TV's ``Dynasty,''
said he has made a $82.5 million deal with Cincinnati billionaire
Carl Lindner that would give Spelling a television distribution
company and Lindner a half-interest in Spelling's company.
   The transaction announced Monday revolves around Spelling's
cash-and-stock purchase of Worldvision Enterprises Inc.,
distributor of ``Love Boat'' and other TV shows, from Lindner's
Great American Communications Co.
   A new holding company, Spelling Inc., would be created to be
parent of Worldvision and of Spelling's present company, Aaron
Spelling Productions Inc.
   Spelling Inc. would pay $82.5 million in cash and Spelling stock
for Worldvision, with enough stock changing hands to give Great
American 50 percent of Spelling Inc., the companies said.
   The transaction would be mostly cash, said Spelling's executive
vice president, Ronald Lightstone, but he refused to disclose the
amount being considered.
   Lindner's Great American controls the company that bought Taft
Broadcasting Co. of Cincinnati, owner of seven television stations
and 15 radio stations, for $1.45 billion in October. Lindner, whose
personal fortune was estimated at $1 billion by Forbes magazine
last year, has a wide range of investments.
   The transaction announced Monday requires approval of
stockholders and regulators and was expected to close in three or
four months, Lightstone said.
   Shareholders in Spelling Productions, a publicly-traded company,
would get shares in Spelling Inc. on a one-for-one basis.
   Lindner, who owns about 4.5 percent of Spelling's 18.25 million
shares, would end up with half the shares in the new company after
issue of new common and preferred stock.
   Spelling is creator of ``Dynasty,'' ``Love Boat'' and ``Hotel,''
and plans a new fall series, ``Angels '88,'' similar to his earlier
``Charlie's Angels.''
   Worldvision distributes ``Barnaby Jones,'' ``Quincy,'' ``Little
House on the Prairie,'' and cartoons by Hanna Barbera, another
Lindner company.
</TEXT>
