<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Eaton     07-25 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Eaton,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Judgment Reduces Eaton Second-Quarter Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eaton Corp. said Monday its second-quarter
profit fell by 29.5 percent from a year earlier, due mainly to a
charge taken to reflect a $17.6 million court judgment against the
company.
   Eaton posted after-tax profits of $46.6 million, or $1.87 a
share, down from $66.1 million, or $2.31 a share during the same
period last year.
   The latest quarter's earnings also included net income of
$700,000 from discontinued operations. The year-earlier quarter
included a $7 million gain from the sale of the company's polymer
products division.
   Quarterly sales were $886.3 million, up from $807.7 million
during the same period last year.
   The company said its net earnings from continuing operations
rose 2.9 percent during the period, to $63.6 million from $61.8
million.
   The California Court of Appeals last week affirmed a 1983 jury
award of $17.6 million against Eaton stemming from a 1976 lawsuit
that PKL Liquidating Trust filed against Cutler-Hammer, Inc., a
company Eaton bought in 1978. The lawsuit concerned PKL's minority
shareholding in Macrodata, which merged with Cutler-Hammer in 1977.
   Eaton said it is appealing the ruling to the California Supreme
Court.
   Eaton makes automotive, industrial, commercial and defense
products including truck transmissions, engine components,
electrical equipment and controls.
   For the first half of 1988, Eaton reported net income, including
discontinued operations, of $106.9 million, or $4.28 a share, down
15.3 percent from the $126.3 million, or $4.33 a share, in the same
period last year.
   Earnings on continuing operations were up 6.7 percent to $123.7
million, or from $115.9 million in the first half of 1987.
   Sales for the first six months of this year were $1.75 billion,
up from $1.58 billion a year earlier.
</TEXT>
