<1ST_LINE>r f AM-York-Antitrust     07-25 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-York-Antitrust,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>York International Announces Antitrust Investigation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YORK, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Justice Department is investigating
the proposed merger of heating and air conditioning equipment
manufacturers SnyderGeneral Corp. and York International Corp.,
York announced Monday.
   SnyderGeneral, a Dallas, Texas-based company, has offered about
$795 million, or $61 per share, to acquire York.
   But in light of the inquiry, York's board reaffirmed its support
for an earlier $750 million, or $57.50 per share, buyout bid from a
group of investors backed by a unit of Citicorp, York said.
   York said the antitrust investigation presented risks of delays
and possible non-completion of its proposed acquisition.
   The length of the investigation into whether the SnyderGeneral
acquisition of York would violate antitrust laws could not be
determined, York said.
   Several weeks before the SnyderGeneral offer was made in
mid-June, York had agreed to be acquired by York Holdings Corp., a
new group capitalized by Citicorp Capital Investors Ltd. and other
investors.
   York Holdings is due to complete its tender offer for about 88
percent of the outstanding York shares by Friday, York said.
   More than a dozen suits have been filed by shareholders who are
attempting to block the Citicorp-led offer on the grounds the
$57.50 a share price is too low.
   SnyderGeneral is a privately-held company that employs about
4,800 people at nine facilities, including two in Europe.
   York International employs 1,600 people. It was a division of
Borg-Warner Corp. until it was spun off to stockholders in 1986.
</TEXT>
