<FILEID>AP-NR-07-25-88 2025EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-DetroitNewspapers     07-25 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Detroit Newspapers,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guild Drops Opposition to JOA</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Newspaper Guild of Detroit, the only union at
the city's two largest daily newspapers, on Monday dropped
opposition to a proposal to partially merge the two publications, a
union official said.
   The decision came during a union meeting Monday morning and
after the union received concessions from the Detroit Free Press
during labor negotiations in three areas, said Don Kummer,
administrator of Local 22 of The Newspaper Guild.
   He said the Free Press had agreed to better pension language, a
retraining program for employees laid off if the proposed joint
operating agreement is approved and a cap on the number of Guild
members subject to such layoff.
   Knight Ridder Inc., owner of the Free Press, issued a statement
Monday welcoming the Guild's decision.
   ``The Guild thus joins the other five unions which originally
intervened in this proceeding, in urging approval of the JOA,'' the
statement said.
   The Free Press and the Detroit News asked the Justice Department
in 1986 for an exemption in antitrust law allowing them to merge
their business, advertising and circulation departments. Editorial
departments would remain separate.
   A spokesman for Attorney General Edwin Meese III, who must rule
on such exemptions, has said he plans to decide on the JOA sometime
before he leaves office Aug. 15.
   A Justice Department staff report and an administrative law
judge, who held hearings into the proposal, recommended the
arrangement be turned down.
   Knight-Ridder has said that if Meese rejects the request, it
would close the newspaper, with the loss of 2,200 jobs.
   The Free Press had 1987 circulation of 639,720 daily and 724,342
on Sundays, while circulation of the News was 678,720 daily and
839,319 on Sundays, according to the Audit Bureau of Circulation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
