<HEAD>Stocks Lower; Dollar Stronger In Tokyo Morning Trading</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with morning Nikkei closing, details, comments. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices eased after an early surge Tuesday
morning in Tokyo and the U.S. dollar firmed against the Japanese
yen as market players awaited news of American economic growth
figures.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which shed
117.81 points Monday, closed the morning session 46.78 points
higher at 27,230.31.
   The widely-watched market barometer gained almost 140 points
within minutes of the market's opening, but concern over U.S. gross
national product figures to be released Wednesday in Washington
erased most of the gain in thin trading, analysts said.
   Many investors stock market participants were taking a
wait-and-see attitude in advance of the report on second quarter
U.S. gross national product.
   ``If the U.S. GNP number is too strong, people are concerned
about inflation in the United States,'' said Hisamichi Sawa of
Prudential Bache.
   In foreign exchange, the dollar opened at 132.25 yen, up from
its 131.80 yen close on Monday, and was trading at around 132.45
yen by midmorning.
   ``Trading is directionless,'' said an exchange dealer, speaking
on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
